<FIRST>r a PM-WrestlingWar     09-08 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wrestling War,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle of the Titans: Hulk Hogan Vs. Ted Turner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two national wrestling organizations, in
a no-holds-barred grudge match, are pitted against each other over
use of Nashville's Municipal Auditorium and other arenas in the
country.
   Squaring off are representatives of muscular wrestler Hulk Hogan
against representatives of cable TV strongman Ted Turner.
   Just like the classic wrestling gimmick, the loser may have to
leave town.
   The National Wrestling Alliance, which Turner purchased last
November, claims the World Wrestling Federation decided to rent the
auditorium May 6 to hurt the attendance of alliance matches the
following day. The alliance claims the same thing happened again
last week and also has occurred in Boston, Baltimore, Philadelphia
and Little Rock, Ark.
   ``The WWF is trying to dominate a lot of the markets by shutting
us out or monopolizing,'' said Don Glass, director of arena bookings
for the Atlanta-based alliance.
   He added, ``They come in and use squash tactics.''
   Ed Cohen, vice president of arena booking for the WWF, refused to
comment Thursday on the matter.
   The auditorium commission heard five-minute presentations from
both Glass and Cohen this week and got a ringside view of the
wrestling promotion companies.
   The tug-of-war left commission member Joe Meeks exasperated.
   ``Why don't we just put up a ring and let 'em fight it out,'' he
suggested.
   The commission, in a decision comparable to a draw in wrestling
terms, agreed to study the dispute further. But in the meantime the
commissioners decided on a temporary policy to schedule only one
night of matches every 10 days in the 9,000-seat auditorium.
   The WWF televises its matches from throughout the country on the
USA cable network and on local stations. It also has matches
periodically on NBC, often in the time spot normally occupied by
``Saturday Night Live.''
   Its wrestlers include Hogan, Andre the Giant and Randy ``Macho
Man'' Savage.
   The alliance uses Turner's WTBS cable superstation to popularize
its wrestlers, who include flamboyant blond Ric Flair, Lex ``The
Total Package'' Lugar and the Road Warriors.
</TEXT>
