<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer Randy Travis and his
band could be expelled from the musicians union and fined up to
$10,000 for crossing a picket line at a Las Vegas hotel.
   ``Randy chose to make his fans happy as opposed to making the
union happy,'' said Evelyn Shriver, a spokeswoman for Travis. ``He
had to disappoint someone and he believes that his success is due to
the support he's received from his fans.''
   Travis performed last weekend at the Bally hotel despite a
summerlong strike against four hotels, including Bally's, which
replaced live musicians with taped accompaniment.
   Mark Tully Massagli, president of the Las Vegas local of the
American Federal of Musicians, said Wednesday: ``Because of the
gravity of the situation, we would request the strongest penalties
possible.''
   A ruling by the union's executive board will take four to six
months, union officials said.
   Dean Martin, Rodney Dangerfield, Connie Francis, Burt Bacharach,
Dionne Warwick and Bill Medley all refused to cross the picket
lines. Pop vocalist Engelbert Humperdinck and magician David
Copperfield did cross the picket lines to perform.
