<FIRST>r w PM-Stallings-Sex     09-08 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stallings-Sex,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stallings Refuses to Answer Allegation About Sex With Youth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Roman Catholic priest the Rev. George
A. Stallings, accused of having sex with an altar boy 12 years ago,
is refusing to say whether he has ever had sexual relations with
young males.
   Stallings, appearing on a talk show Thursday on WJLA television,
declined to answer questions about whether he ever had sex with boys.
   The Washington Post has reported that a former altar boy swore in
a signed statement that he had sexual relations 12 years ago with
Stallings, who was suspended by the church this summer for starting
an unsanctioned African-American congregation.
   Asked Thursday whether he had ever had sexual relations with
young males, Stallings said: ``My answer (is) to those people whom I
served, those persons who are touched by my ministry. I say to them,
`I am the same pastor today as I was 12 years ago ... when I first
ministered to you. I have not changed. You know that my credentials
are impeccable and that my morals are beyond reproach.'''
   Asked the same question again, Stallings said: ``It's not a
question of answering yes or no. For me to give any type of response
... would mean first and foremost that I would allow a single issue
_ whether it would be my life ... whether I wear my hair long or
short _ to become the driving concern, rather than the central issue
or focus that there is racism in the Catholic Church.''
   According to the Post story published Monday, a former altar boy,
now 28, said that when he was 16 he repeatedly had sex with
Stallings in the rectory of St. Teresa of Avila Catholic Church
during a three- to four-month period in 1977. The man was not
identified in the article.
   The story also said Washington Cardinal James A. Hickey had
confronted Stallings with allegations of more recent sexual
misconduct and asked him to seek treatment in a New Mexico church
facility that treats pedophilia and other emotional disorders.
Stallings, however, said Thursday that Hickey ``never brought forth
any sexual charges.''
   Stallings has labeled the article ``scurrilous'' and ``baseless''
and called it an attempt to divert attention from his mission of
establishing a congregation attentive to the needs of blacks.
</TEXT>
