<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-08 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California lawmakers were deep in an
ethics discussion Thursday when somebody smelled a rat.
   Actually, everyone saw the rat when it stuck its brown nose over
the edge of a decorative Corinthian column on the wall of the
Assembly balcony Thursday.
   Bedlam ensued and little attention was paid to the serious debate
on details of a proposed constitutional amendment that would enact a
series of ethics standards for legislators.
   ``You'd think nobody around here'd ever seen a rat,'' said the
presiding officer, Assemblyman Mike Roos.
   The Capitol, built in the 1860s and renovated a decade ago, has
suffered cricket and mouse infestations. But this was a different
matter.
   ``Where's the assault rifle?'' joked Assemblyman Trice Harvey.
The Legislature last spring passed a law restricting sales of many
assault-style semiautomatic guns.
   Speaker Willie Brown went up to the balcony and peered at the
column.
   But the rat, perhaps having its fill of ethics debate, did not
reappear.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHESTERTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toto, you're invited to the eighth annual
Wizard of Oz Festival in Chesterton.
   The festival's executive director, Ross Amundson, has invited all
200 residents of the town of Toto to the Sept. 15-17 festival, which
will honor the 50th anniversary of the MGM film classic.
   ``Actually, the author of `The Wizard of Oz,' L. Frank Baum,
summered at Bass Lake,'' Amundson said. ``He did some of his writing
there. He probably came up with the name of Toto from that.''
   Bass Lake is about 5 miles from Toto. Chesterton is about 30
miles further away and near Lake Michigan.
   For those who've been somewhere over the rainbow the past half
century and don't know, Toto is Dorothy's dog in Baum's book and in
the 1939 Judy Garland movie.
   Amundson addressed the festival invitation to ``the Honorable
Mayor and the Grand People of Toto,'' even though Toto has no mayor.
The invitation was mailed to Toto resident Rose Wineberg, whose
brother Joe owns Joey's Wallpaper Inc.
   ``Well, Toto is just a little wide spot in the road,'' said a
woman in Toto who answered the phone at Joey's Wallpaper and who
said her first name was Dorothy.
   Amundson expects up to 30,000 people to attend the festival. He
has no idea how many to expect from Toto.
   Ten of the 116 people who played munchkins in the movie will
attend the festival. Among them will be munchkin soldier Lewis Croft
and Ralph Ayres, the honorary mayor of Munchkin Land.
   ``We've been able to finance this thing through a
sponsor-a-munchkin program we sold to five businesses here,''
Amundson said. ``McDonalds, Wendy's, Burger King, Costas Foods and
Lewis Dairy Queen each put up $500 to sponsor a munchkin. The
munchkins will be at their stores a couple of hours during the
festival.''
</TEXT>
