<FIRST>r w PM-DC-10Crew     09-08 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crew,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 232 Crew Meets With Bush, Vows to Return to Flying</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot and co-pilots of United Flight 232,
hailed as heroes by President Bush for guiding their plane to a
crash-landing that most on board survived, say they want to resume
flying DC-10s.
   ``The only thing that upsets me is I have to wait to get well to
do it,'' said Dennis Fitch, a pilot trainer who joined the crew from
the passenger compartment and helped land the plane July 19 at the
Sioux City, Iowa, airport.
   Pilot Albert Haynes, Fitch, the two co-pilots, flight attendants
and air traffic controllers involved with the flight met Thursday
with Bush after the cockpit crew held their first joint news
conference.
   The crash killed 112 people, including one who died from injuries
a month later; 184 passengers and crew members survived after the
DC-10 cartwheeled and burst into flames during an emergency landing
on a flight from Denver to Chicago.
   The landing followed an explosive engine failure that
investigators say cut hydraulic systems that control flight. The
pilots said they were left with the thrust from two engines to steer
and level off the plane, which Haynes said began descending and
turning to the right after the engine failed.
   ``I know Al (Haynes) would disclaim all credit, but certainly he
deserves an awful lot,'' Bush said. ``And there's the controllers,
and there's the ground crew, and there's the cabin crew and then
there's a lot of plain people that just were watching with wonder
and great pride.''
   Three of the 16-member group still bore outward evidence of their
injuries: a man on crutches, another with his hand in a large cast,
and a woman in a wheelchair with a bandaged hand.
   Haynes, Fitch and co-pilots William Records and Dudley Dvorak
said at the news conference that they plan to fly when they have
fully recovered. None expressed qualms about the DC-10 and said they
believe investigators will determine the cause of the crash.
   ``I'm looking forward to flying the DC-10 as soon as possible,''
Records said.
   Federal Aviation Administrator James B. Busey said last month
that there was no evidence to warrant grounding DC-10s, despite the
Iowa crash and an Aug. 10 emergency landing by a Northwest Airlines
DC-10 in Denver. The Northwest plane made a safe landing with holes
blasted in the housing of its tail-mounted engine.
   All DC-10s were grounded for a month in 1979 after an American
Airlines plane crashed after taking off from Chicago, killing 273
people.
   Busey did form a task force after the Iowa crash to examine
possible changes in the design of wide-body planes.
   Haynes said the thought of dying never entered his mind as he and
other crew members tried to land the plane by applying power
selectively to its two remaining engines.
   ``My life did not flash before me,'' he said.
   He said pictures of the plane coming in for a landing are
deceiving.
   ``It looks like we're flying a standard instrument approach and
we weren't,'' he said. ``The airplane was ... still wanting to roll
on us. It was a constant battle all the way down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
