<DOCNO> AP890908-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Top12     09-08 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Top 12,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extradition Requests Prepared for Drug `Dirty Dozen'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Extradition Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the arrival of the first alleged drug
trafficker extradited from Colombia in two years, U.S. attorneys are
working on extradition requests for the dozen most wanted, the
Justice Department says.
   Eduardo Martinez Romero, an alleged member of the Medellin
cocaine cartel who arrived early Thursday in Atlanta, was not on the
list of the top 12 drug traffickers issued by Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh.
   The list was issued shortly after Colombian President Virgilio
Barco imposed emergency regulations allowing the resumption of
extraditions that were stopped in 1987 by the Colombian Supreme
Court. By the time the list came out, Martinez was in custody.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said Thursday that U.S.
attorneys around the country were still preparing the extradition
requests for the 12, none of whom has been arrested.
   Named on the list are six members of the Medellin cartel, which
authorities believe was among the first to organize a corporate-like
structure, and six of the Cali cartel.
   The Justice Department has released the following information on
the 12 fugitives:
   _Pablo Emilio Escobar-Gaviria, 39, Medellin cartel. A former
alternate senator from Medellin, he faces a 1986 indictment in
Colombia for the murder of a newspaper owner.
   The Justice Department says he traffics in cocaine, marijuana,
and possibly heroin and has been indicted five times in the United
States on drug-trafficking, conspiracy, racketeering and obstruction
of justice charges. He is named in indictments in Florida, Louisiana
and Colorado.
   _Gustavo de Jesus Gaviria-Rivero, 42, Medellin cartel. Gaviria
allegedly deals in cocaine and marijuana and was arrested in the
Bahamas in 1981 on charges of transporting marijuana. He was
indicted in Florida last year on drug and conspiracy charges.
   _Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez-Gacha, 42, Medellin cartel. He allegedly
traffics in cocaine and marijuana and reputedly heads an
international cocaine production and distribution organization based
in Bogota that is believed responsible for sending hundreds of
kilograms of cocaine to the United States each week.
   He faces drug-trafficking, conspiracy and racketeering charges in
six separate indictments in Florida and New York.
   _Jorge Luis Ochoa-Vasquez, thought to be 40, Medellin cartel. He
allegedly has been involved with cocaine and marijuana trafficking
for more than a decade, taking over and modernizing the
drug-smuggling business started by his father, Fabio Ochoa Restrepo.
   Ochoa-Vasquez has been arrested at least twice, once in Madrid,
but served little time in Colombia. He faces drug-trafficking,
conspiracy and racketeering charges in indictments returned in
Florida and Georgia.
   _Juan David Ochoa-Vasquez, 41, Jorge's brother, Medellin cartel.
He allegedly is involved in the financial end of his family's
business and in smuggling cocaine to the United States. He was
indicted in Florida on drug-trafficking, conspiracy and racketeering
charges.
   _Fabio Ochoa-Vasquez, 32, known as Fabito, the youngest of the
Ochoa brothers, Medellin cartel. He reportedly took control when
Jorge was imprisoned in Spain in 1984 and allegedly traffics in
cocaine.
   Indicted in both Louisiana and Florida, he faces
drug-trafficking, conspiracy and racketeering charges and a charge
of causing interstate travel for the commission of a murder for hire.
   _Jose Santacruz-Londono, 45, Cali cartel. The Justice Department
believes Santacruz has operated a cocaine trafficking network since
1975, primarily in New York, Miami, Los Angeles, San Francisco,
Houston, Las Vegas and Chicago.
   Santacruz has been indicted in Florida and New York, which
originally indicted him under the pseudonym of Victor Crespo, on
charges of importation and distribution of cocaine, conspiracy and
involvement with a continuing criminal enterprise.
   _Gilberto Rodriguez-Orejuela, 50, Cali cartel. The department
says he is believed to oversee the logistics of the organization's
cocaine-smuggling and money-laundering operations. He has been
indicted in New York and Louisiana on drug-trafficking, conspiracy
and criminal enterprise charges.
   _Miguel Angel Rodriguez-Orejuela, 45, Cali cartel. The Justice
Department contends Miguel Rodriguez has been involved in cocaine
and marijuana drug trafficking since 1980 while operating legitimate
banks, real estate and construction companies in Colombia. He was
indicted in Louisiana on drug-trafficking and conspiracy charges.
   _Jaime Raul Orjuela-Caballero, 46, Cali cartel. The department
believes he controls the cartel's cocaine distribution to the United
States, primarily in the New York area. He was indicted in New York
on drug-trafficking and continuing criminal enterprise charges.
   _Jose Ivan Duarte-Acero, 37, Cali cartel. A former Colombian
National Police lieutenant dismissed from the force because of
corruption charges, he is wanted in the United States for the
alleged kidnapping and attempted murder of two Drug Enforcement
Administration agents in February 1982 in Cartegena, Colombia. The
indictment was returned that year in Florida.
   _Gerardo Moncado, about 23, Cali cartel. Moncado allegedly
collects money for the cartel. He was indicted this year in Georgia
on conspiracy charges.
</TEXT>
