<FIRST>r w PM-BadRays     09-08 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bad Rays,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ultraviolet Rays Destroy Photosynthesis Protein, Scientist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Depletion of ozone in the skies above may lead
to sick and dying plants on the Earth below, according to studies by
a U.S. Department of Agriculture researcher.
   Autar K. Mattoo, leader of the USDA's plant molecular biology lab
in Beltsville, Md., said ultraviolet-b radiation, or UV-B _ the
solar rays that give people tans and skin cancer _ will destroy half
of a plant's store of a critical photosynthesis protein every half
hour.
   The plant is able to restore the protein and continue
photosynthesis when it receives normal levels of UV-B radiation,
Mattoo said, but at higher levels of UV-B the plant would be
stripped of the protein and photosynthesis would stop.
   ``In a few hours time, you would have hardly any of this protein
left in the plant,'' he said Thursday in a telephone interview.
``The plant would wither away and die.''
   Mattoo said that, based on his studies, an increase in UV-B also
could weaken and kill some plants.
   Experiments in Beltsville and Israel showed that UV-B causes a
breakdown of a plant molecule called D1 protein. That protein, he
said, is an essential component in the photochemistry that enables
plants to convert sunlight into chemical energy, a process called
photosynthesis.
   ``The plant does try to replenish the molecules,'' Mattoo said.
``But if you have higher UV-B radiation the plant will not keep up
with the molecules that are being destroyed. That's when we think
there will be an effect on photosynthesis.''
   Such an impact on the normal growth of agricultural crops would
inevitably lead to a smaller harvest and less food, he said.
   UV-B is a normal component of sunlight. Most of the radiation is
filtered out by ozone in the Earth's stratosphere and never reaches
the ground. But recent studies have shown that some types of
pollution are causing the ozone layer to thin in places, creating
what scientists called ``ozone holes.''
   Experts are concerned that a thin ozone layer would allow enough
additional UV-B to reach the Earth's surface to cause a rise in skin
cancers.
   UV-B can damage the skin and that damage is related to
development of cancers.
   Mattoo said he and a colleague, Marvin Edelman of the Weizmann
Institute of Science in Israel, discovered the effect of UV-B on
photosynthesis by studying the level of D1 protein in the duckweed
plant at different light exposures.
   Specimens of the plant, which grows in water, were exposed to
various wavelengths of light, he said. The amount of protein found
in the plants through chemical analysis was then related to the
amount and type of light exposure.
   At a UV-B exposure equivalent to noon sunshine, Mattoo said, the
plant lost half of its D1 protein stores every 30 minutes.
   A report on the research will appear this month in the
Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890908-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0408EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Tocqueville     09-08 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tocqueville,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Commemorates Tocqueville Who Described it 150 Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Library of Congress today opens this
country's first big exhibition on Alexis de Tocqueville, who
finished his classic ``Democracy in America'' just 150 years ago.
   ``The Anglo-American relies upon personal interest to accomplish
his ends, and gives free scope to the unguided exertions and common
sense of the citizens; the Russian centers all the authority of
society in a single arm,'' Tocqueville wrote.
   ``The principal instrument of the former is freedom; of the
latter servitude. Their starting point is different, and their
courses are not the same; yet each of them seems to be marked out by
the will of Heaven to sway the destinies of half the globe.''
   The exhibit, which will run until Oct. 29, is part of a
French-American commemoration. The year 1789 also was marked by the
proposal of both the U.S. Bill of Rights and French Declaration of
the Rights of Man.
   One of the 250 items on show is a letter from the Marquis de
Lafayette. It asks Thomas Jefferson, then U.S. envoy in Paris, to
look over the marquis' draft of the French declaration.
   Tocqueville made his first trip to this country at age 25, an
unpaid apprentice judge who obtained leave to write a study of the
American prison system.
   ``English was a language not much studied then in France,'' said
Francoise Melanio, co-curator of the exhibit, who is preparing a new
edition of his work.
   ``But he worked hard on the voyage, which took over a month in
1831, and he did without an interpreter when he got here.''
   With his friend Gustave de Beaumont, a state prosecutor, he
roamed for 18 months from Quebec to New Orleans to Memphis to Green
Bay, Wis. They met the leading Americans of the time, including
President Andrew Jackson.
   His book, the first part of which was published in 1835, was an
immediate success. It has long been recognized in this country for
evaluations of the American character and political system.
   ``Man is not made for slavery; that truth is perhaps even better
proved by the master than by the slave,'' he wrote almost 30 years
before Abraham Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation.
   He did not live to see that, dying in 1859 after a political
career that led him to become minister of foreign affairs. His
political career ended when he was briefly jailed for his opposition
to the coup by Louis Napoleon, who became Napoleon III.
   Ms. Melanio said his preference for decentralized government was
not popular in France _ a proposal for decentralization led to
President Charles de Gaulle's political downfall 20 years ago. Local
government has become more popular under President Francois
Mitterrand, who quoted Tocqueville in his speech last month
celebrating the 200th anniversary of the fall of the Bastille.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
