<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Drugs     09-08 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman Claims He Supplied Drugs for Barry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington businessman, recently convicted on
drug charges, says he gave cocaine to a friend of Mayor Marion Barry
Jr. for Barry's use while the mayor was present, according to a
report published today.
   The Washington Post reported that George H. Van Wagner III met
with federal prosecutors to discuss the alleged January 1987
incident.
   Van Wagner told federal prosecutors and the Post that he
delivered one-eighth of an ounce of cocaine to the mayor's friend
while Barry and his friend sat in a parked car in downtown
Washington, the newspaper reported.
   Van Wagner met with federal investigators Thursday in Alexandria,
Va., the Post said.
   Van Wagner also reportedly said he handed another eighth of an
ounce of cocaine to either Barry or the mayor's friend at a private
party at a downtown restaurant a week earlier.
   Barry told the Post he had never heard of or met Van Wagner.
Barry, who has not been charged with any criminal wrongdoing, has
repeatedly denied he has ever used drugs.
   ``It seems to be the popular thing to do now, when people want to
make a deal, to lie on the mayor. Once again, a convicted drug
dealer with nothing to lose and everything to gain by lying,'' the
Post quoted Barry as saying.
   Van Wagner, 36, told the newspaper he was cooperating with
federal prosecutors in the hope of getting a lighter sentence.
   The mayor's unidentified friend, an advertising executive, told
the Post that Van Wagner's allegations were ``an absolute
fabrication.'' The friend told the newspaper he briefly met with Van
Wagner twice but never received any drugs from him.
   Van Wagner was convicted Aug. 25 of conspiracy to distribute
cocaine and to launder the proceeds from the transactions. He is
being held in the Alexandria jail and faces a minimum of 10 years in
prison.
   Federal investigators are probing former Barry associate Charles
Lewis' allegations that he smoked crack with Barry at a downtown
hotel and during trips to the Virgin Islands.
</TEXT>
