<FIRST>r w PM-WeaponsLab     09-08 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weapons Lab,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weapons Lab is Target of Four Congressional Investigations</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: `n-Chip' is CQ name of company.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California nuclear weapons lab with a history
of drug trafficking problems is the target of at least four
congressional investigations focusing on possible security and
ethics violations, sources say.
   The latest probe, begun two months ago by the House Energy and
Commerce oversight and investigations subcommittee, focuses on the
terms under which the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory
transferred a new computer technology to a company led by former lab
scientists who had helped develop the process.
   Subcommittee Chairman John Dingell, D-Mich., has suggested the
deal violated conflict-of-interest standards, although officials at
the laboratory and the company _ n-Chip Inc. of Livermore, Calif. _
deny any wrongdoing.
   Congressional sources involved in the investigations disclosed
Thursday that lab officials also have come under investigation for
allegedly ``failing to protect important security assets'' at the
site.
   The sources, who spoke on the condition they not be identified,
declined to reveal details of the security lapse but said Energy
Undersecretary John Tuck acknowledged in a closed hearing in July
that the problem posed an unacceptable risk to national security.
Immediate corrective actions were promised, they said.
   Tuck did not return a telephone call seeking comment.
   Plutonium and other sensitive materials are used at Lawrence
Livermore in nuclear weapons design and research activities. The
lab, one of three major weapons design facilities, is operated by
the University of California under an Energy Department contract.
   The Dingell subcommittee also is investigating the national
security implications of an allegation by Roy Woodruff, formerly a
leader of the lab's weapons program.
   Woodruff contends he was blocked by superiors from writing to
national security officials in Washington in 1983-85 to dispute
optimistic projections by physicist Edward Teller about the X-ray
laser weapon being developed there.
   The X-ray laser uses the energy of a nuclear explosion in space
to destroy enemy rocket boosters.
   Separately, the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm
of Congress, is looking into allegations of thefts of government
property at the lab. That investigation was launched last year after
Dingell's panel was told in a public hearing that some lab employees
had sold computers and other government assets for drug money.
   The lab in 1986 launched its own investigation of drug
trafficking by employees after a number of workers became involved
in drug-related incidents and arrests.
   Last month, the lab was embarrassed when small amounts of cocaine
and other drugs were stolen from a locked safe. The narcotics were
being used to train a drug-sniffing dog that had been brought onto
the site to fight a drug problem.
   Dingell stepped up pressure on Energy Secretary James D. Watkins
to review the University of California's management of the lab by
pressing him for information about the circumstances of a licensing
deal the lab made earlier this year with n-Chip.
   The department's internal auditors also are investigating the
licensing deal.
   In a July 7 letter to Watkins, a copy of which was made public
Wednesday, Dingell called the awarding of the license to n-Chip to
commercially develop a technology known as laser pantography
``highly curious.''
   He cited ``the appearance of a conflict of interest'' in granting
an exclusive license to a company whose top officials include at
least three people who helped develop the technology.
   Laser pantography is used for connecting computer chips in a way
that permits supercomputers to be compressed to the size of a
cigarette pack.
</TEXT>
