<FIRST>r w PM-NixonImpeachment     09-08 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nixon Impeachment,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Relates Call to Nixon on Son's Behalf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer representing U.S. District Judge
Walter Nixon at an impeachment hearing before a Senate panel says a
key witness is unreliable.
   David Stewart said Thursday that Wiley Fairchild had changed his
story about Nixon's intervention in a drug-smuggling case involving
Fairchild's son, but the Hattiesburg, Miss., oil man said the
discrepancies were caused by confusion.
   ``I've always intended to tell the truth,'' Fairchild said. ``I
got confused.''
   The testimony came as a 12-member Senate panel considered the
impeachment case against Nixon, who is serving a five-year prison
sentence for perjury. He continues to draw his $89,500 annual salary.
   ``The real reason I went to Judge Nixon was because Bud Holmes
was not treating my son right,'' Fairchild said about Paul ``Bud''
Holmes, who was prosecuting Drew Fairchild in a marijuana smuggling
case.
   Fairchild said he and Nixon became friends after he sold him
lucrative oil properties.
   Fairchild, 76, said he thought Holmes was trying to blackmail him
by pressing charges against his 50-year-old son in an effort to get
the elder Fairchild to pay more legal fees.
   Fairchild contended it wasn't fair that his son was being
prosecuted while his son's partner in the alleged scheme was not.
   Fairchild admitted to failing and confused memory about his
previous testimony in the long case against Nixon, which began in
1983, but said he would remember ``for as long as I live'' what
Nixon told him on the telephone from Holmes' house.
   ``He said, `Everything is going to be taken care of to your
satisfaction,''' Fairchild said.
   After the call, Fairchild said, the case was ``passed to the
file,'' which meant the prosecutor would be taking no action against
his son.
   The articles of impeachment approved unanimously by the House
allege:
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he never discussed the case
against Drew Fairchild with Holmes.
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he had nothing to do
officially or unofficially with the Fairchild case and never
influenced anyone in the case.
   _Nixon undermined ``the integrity of the judiciary'' and
disobeyed the law by making 14 false or misleading statements during
an interview with federal investigators and in his sworn grand jury
testimony.
   Stewart charged that Fairchild changed his story at a
post-conviction hearing.
   ``He testified that the phone call actually occurred after Drew's
case was passed to the files,'' Stewart said.
   But Fairchild said he ``got confused real bad'' at that hearing
and based his testimony on information given to him by his brother,
not on what he had remembered.
   Stewart argued that Nixon's only involvement was to talk to
Holmes about Fairchild's fears that he was being blackmailed, not to
interfere in the case.
   ``While Judge Nixon visited Bud Holmes at his farm outside of
Hattiesburg, he mentioned Wiley Fairchild's blackmail complaint,''
Stewart said. ``Holmes said that Wiley was crazy and offered to tell
Judge Nixon about Drew's case, but the judge told Holmes that he did
not want to hear about it.''
   Stewart said Holmes called Fairchild and said he intended to
honor a plea bargain with Drew that would keep him out of jail.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., said in his opening remarks before
the committee that the evidence would show Nixon had ``little regard
for the truth and cannot be trusted'' to continue as a federal judge.
   The Senate will the vote whether to remove Nixon as a judge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
