<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0440EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-JailedMother     09-08 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jailed Mother,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Action Moves Elizabeth Morgan Closer to Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate action to limit civil contempt-of-court
jailings in the District of Columbia is expected to free a physician
jailed for two years for refusing to reveal the whereabouts of her
daughter in a custody dispute.
   Thursday's Senate action is the penultimate step in a long march
to freedom for Dr. Elizabeth Morgan, a prominent Washington plastic
surgeon.
   ``This bill is simple, it's clear and it's fair,'' said Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who sponsored the legislation. ``At this time,
there has to be a limit to this thing and a way to resolve this
problem.''
   Rep. Frank Wolf, R.-Va., sponsor of a similar measure approved in
the House in June, said the final step to Morgan's freedom could
come next week with a conference between the House and Senate to
work out differences in the bills.
   Congress has review power over all city laws and court
regulations.
   Morgan was jailed in August 1987 after refusing to disclose the
whereabouts of her 7-year-old daughter, Hilary, saying she feared
the girl's father would sexually abuse her.
   The battle between Morgan and her ex-husband, Dr. Eric Foretich,
has become a national rallying point for women's group and
anti-child abuse organizations.
   ``We're delighted to have the Senate take care of this matter,''
said Alice Monroe, a spokeswoman for the Friends of Elizabeth
Morgan. ``We had such an abusive situation here it demanded some
action.''
   Foretich, who denies sexually abusing his daughter, has been
supported by a host groups backing the rights of fathers in custody
battles.
   His lawyer, Elaine Mittleman, criticized the Senate for refusing
to ``consider the health and safety of Hilary.''
   Both bills are to be applied retroactively to Morgan's case, but
the House bill sets a 12-month cap on civil-contempt jailings and
requires that the person either be freed after that period or be
subjected to criminal-contempt charges, which guarantee a jury trial.
   The Senate measure sets a 12-month cap on child-custody jailings,
but it doesn't apply to all civil-contempt jailings.
   The Senate version, which passed without opposition, includes a
sunset measure that would wipe the legislation off the books in 18
months.
   Wolf has said he didn't intend his legislation to apply only to
Morgan.
   Charlie Lyons, a spokesman for Wolf, said the congressman isn't
likely to object to the sunset amendment even though it means the
law likely will affect only Morgan.
   Mittleman has complained that neither bill guarantees that Hilary
will be returned or that Foretich will be allowed his court-approved
visits.
   D.C. Superior Court Judge Herbert Dixon ordered Morgan jailed
until she produced the child. In May, Dixon rejected a request that
she be freed and his decision was upheld last month by a D.C. Court
of Appeals.
   Neither the House nor the Senate bill prevents Morgan from being
jailed after future court proceedings.
</TEXT>
