<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-08 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo Friday, while stock prices declined for a fourth consecutive
day.
   The dollar finished the week at 146.62 yen, down 0.25 yen from
Thursday's close of 146.87 yen. After opening at 146.59 yen, the
currency ranged between 146.40 and 146.90 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 118.75 points Thursday, shed 36.75
points, or 0.10 percent, closing at 34,115.81.
   Currency dealers said the dollar rose in early trading due to
dollar-buying sentiment following the decision Thursday by West
Germany's central bank to leave interest rates unchanged.
   But intervention by the Bank of Japan and profit-taking quickly
braked the dollar's rise, said a dealer for a major commercial bank
in Tokyo who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index fell during the afternoon
session, reversing its morning gains. Dealers said the market
declined because of profit-taking and concern over forecasts of
higher interest rates.
</TEXT>
