<DOCNO> AP890908-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0519EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HomelessHealth     09-08 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homeless Health,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Homeless Face Multiple Health Problems, Receive Little Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proper health care is mostly unavailable for the
more than 80 percent of homeless people studied in Baltimore
suffering from mental illness, a medical researcher says.
   ``Current resources are woefully inadequate'' to meet the needs
of the homeless, concluded a study published in today's Journal of
the American Medical Association.
   In an accompanying commentary, Dr. David Hilfiker of the
Community of Hope Health Services in Washington said that behind the
statistics of the study ``lies human pain we who are affluent can
scarcely imagine.''
   The study by Dr. William R. Breakey of the Johns Hopkins
University School of Medicine psychiatry department and his
colleagues found that 80 percent of the women surveyed and 91
percent of the men suffered from mental health problems.
   Schizophrenia was diagnosed in 12 percent of men and 17 percent
of women, and major depression or manic-depressive disorders in 19
percent of men and 24 percent of women. Less severe psychiatric
problems, such as phobias or anxiety disorders, were found in 28
percent of men and 44 percent of women.
   Alcohol abuse was found in 68 percent of men and 32 percent of
women in the sample.
   Although more than half of those surveyed acknowledged having
used illegal drugs, just 22 percent of men and 17 percent of women
were considered to have a problem with drug dependency.
   Among the most common physical problems observed were dental,
gynecological, skin, heart, respiratory and neurological disorders,
the researchers said.
   On average, 8.3 physical problems were found in men and 9.2
problems in women.
   The study was based on a random sampling in 1986 and 1987 of 298
homeless men and 230 women from missions, shelters and jails in
Baltimore.
   A subgroup of 203 people was selected for detailed psychiatric
and physical examinations.
   Hilfiker said the statistics ``all testify to enormous suffering,
much of it preventable.'' The government must spend more money to
provide health care for the poor, Hilfiker said.
   Congress is trimming the allocation for health-care programs for
the homeless from the $207 million recommended by the Bush
administration in its fiscal 1990 budget to $160 million, said Mary
Ellen Hombs, acting director of the Washington office of the
National Coalition for the Homeless.
   Ms. Hombs sid the Baltimore study reflects national trends.
   ``We see rates of mental illness running around 30 percent
nationwide and about the same for alcohol abuse,'' she said.
``Homelessness is a serious health threat and it can actually kill
you.''
   Both Ms. Hombs and authors of the study said the homeless need
more community mental health services, specialized services for
substance abusers, and special treatment programs staffed by people
familiar with their problems.
   Estimates of the number of homeless people in the United States
range from 250,000 to 3 million.
</TEXT>
