<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion-Rights Backers Announce Rallies Around Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abortion-rights coalition is planning to
stage rallies in the nation's capital and in cities across the
country this fall to kick off a nationwide political organizing
effort.
   The aggregation of women's groups and religious, labor, business
and advocacy organizations Thursday announced that they will hold
rallies and other events Nov. 12 to register supporters to vote,
enlist their help in political organizing and boost the campaigns of
abortion-rights candidates.
   ``We will make it the political issue of 1989, 1990, 1992, and we
will change the legislative halls of this country so that we have
pro-choice legislators everywhere in the majority,'' said Molly
Yard, president of the National Organization for Women. The actions
will be conducted under the banner ``Mobilize for Women's Lives.''
   Organizers said the coalition was formed before the Supreme
Court's July 3 decision giving states broad powers to regulate
abortions. NOW had wanted to stage a Washington rally this fall to
protest the court ruling, but other groups wanted more state and
community involvement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Group Accuses Election Watchdog of Willful Inaction</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Common Cause charges that the Federal Election
Commission is falling down on its job of policing federal campaign
finance laws and has actually encouraged illegal practices by its
``seemingly willful refusal to act.''
   The citizens lobby Thursday said the problems are so pervasive
``the best, albeit drastic, remedy may be to abolish the FEC
altogether and to create a new election law enforcement agency.''
   ``The FEC in recent years increasingly has abdicated its most
basic responsibility _ to enforce the law,'' Common Cause said in a
report.
   Fred Eiland, a spokesman for the election commission, said he
wasn't certain whether the agency would issue a response. Common
Cause is an enduring critic of the FEC and has sued the agency
frequently.
   The study charged that the failure to enforce the federal
campaign finance laws ``springs both from the structural defects
Congress created in the agency and from the recalcitrance of the
commissioners themselves. Congress virtually has ignored the FEC's
failure to enforce the law.''
   Under laws passed after the Watergate scandals in the early
1970s, the FEC is charged with administering public funding of
presidential campaigns, policing public disclosure, interpreting
laws pertaining to presidential and congressional elections,
investigating alleged violations and undertaking enforcement actions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>UAW, Auto Industry Criticize Proposed Efficiency Standards</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forcing automobile manufacturers to boost fuel
efficiency 40 percent by the turn of the century could make cars
less safe, hurt sales and cost jobs, industry representatives and
Senate opponents said.
   ``The increase in prices may make it prohibitively expensive for
people to purchase automobiles, therefore ... they'll continue
driving their old gas guzzler,'' Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., said.
   But the sponsor of a proposed update of the Corporate Average
Fuel Economy law said the same dire warnings were proven false after
the original measure was debated and enacted in the mid-1970s.
   ``Your predecessors ... in effect forecast the collapse of
Western civilization as we know it,'' Sen. Richard H. Bryan, D-Nev.,
told industry lobbyists during a hearing of the Commerce, Science
and Technology consumer subcommittee Wednesday.
   Instead, he said, the domestic industry remained profitable while
doubling the fuel economy of its cars. ``Why should I believe you,
based upon your previous testimony?''
   The CAFE law requires that each manufacturer's fleet of new cars
and light trucks sold in the Unites States average at least 27.5
miles per gallon. Bryan wants to require a 20 percent improvement in
fuel efficiency by 1995 and a 40 percent improvement by 2000.
   Spokesmen for domestic and foreign manufacturers said such large
increases were not technologically feasible.
</TEXT>
