<FIRST>r a PM-Iowa-Reax     09-08 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa-Reax,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailor's Family Calls for Independent Review of Iowa Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iowa Inquiry, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of the sailor cited by the Navy as
most likely causing the USS Iowa explosion says he was made a
scapegoat and has called for an independent review of the disaster.
   ``The Navy reached the conclusion that they must have a scapegoat
in this matter to deflect attention away from their negligence,
their incompetence and their indifference in the operation of the
USS Iowa,'' said Kreig J. Brusnahan, an attorney representing the
family of Clayton Hartwig.
   Navy officials briefed Hartwig's family Thursday morning before
the report was released.
   ``I've never believed it right from the start,'' Hartwig's
sister, Kathy Kubicina, said when asked if she thought her brother
had caused the April 19 blast which killed him and 46 shipmates.
   Ms. Kubicina, who has been an outspoken defender of her brother,
said families of other Iowa victims had offered their support.
   ``We've been in touch with a few of the families who lost people
in that turret explosion and they're on our side,'' she said. ``They
said that the Navy is basically trying to cover their own self. We
got word from a few families, `Keep your heads up. You have nothing
to be ashamed (of).'''
   Ms. Kubicina and her father, Earl V. Hartwig, said they wanted a
congressional investigation into the Navy's handling of the Iowa
probe.
   ``The Navy is kind of investigating itself and clearing itself,''
Brusnahan said.
   Earl Hartwig, a Navy veteran, said he was unconvinced that his
son or any other crew member had caused the explosion.
   Family members disputed allegations reported in the media since
the blast that Clayton Hartwig was a suicidal homosexual.
   ``Why didn't he slit his wrists? Why didn't he jump off the
ship?'' Brusnahan said. ``Why would he take 46 of his closest
friends with him?''
   The Navy ``has concocted this fable in the guise of a 1,001-page
report in an attempt to shift the blame away from its dismal track
record in their operation of this battleship and lay the blame on a
dead sailor who isn't here to defend himself,'' Brusnahan said.
   ``Dead men can't defend themselves, the Navy knows that,''
Brusnahan said. ``Dead men can't be libeled, the Navy knows that.''
   Elsewhere, the findings were greeted with skepticism.
   Retired Rear Adm. Eugene Carroll said the Navy was grasping at
straws to explain the explosion. ``This probable cause diverts
attention from the question of the performance of the equipment and
the personnel,'' said Carroll, deputy director of the Center for
Defense Information in Washington.
   Still, others accepted the report.
   ``I would say the Navy Investigative Service has probably done
their homework. They probably know for fact, or have enough
evidence, circumstantial or not, to back up this theory,'' said
Steven Haight, a retired Navy man who worked mostly in intelligence
during a 20-year career.
   ``I don't think it's a cop-out,'' agreed Petty Officer 3rd Class
Michael Glass, a crewman on the amphibious cargo ship Charleston at
Norfolk, Va.
   The Iowa left its Norfolk homeport in June for six months in the
Mediterranean Sea. The crew received copies of the report Wednesday
during a port call in Gaeta, Italy, said Capt. Paul Hanley, an
Atlantic Fleet spokesman.
</TEXT>
