<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     09-08 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Nurse's Aide Pleads Guilty to Murder, Will Testify</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nurse's aide pleaded guilty
to murder and conspiracy and agreed to testify that she helped her
co-worker and lover kill one of five slain nursing home patients.
   Catherine May Wood told a judge on Thursday that she and
Gwendolyn Graham discussed killing as many as 20 patients at Alpine
Manor Nursing Home in Walker, a Grand Rapids suburb.
   In her appearance before Kent County Circuit Judge Robert Benson,
Wood admitted helping Graham kill Marguerite Chambers, 60, on Jan.
17, 1987. Two murder charges against Wood were dropped in exchange
for her guilty pleas to second-degree murder and conspiracy.
   In the plea bargain, Wood agreed to testify for the prosecution
in Graham's trial on five counts of first-degree murder and a count
of conspiracy to commit first-degree murder. Jury selection in
Graham's trial is to begin Monday.
   Attorney James Piazza, who is representing Graham, said Wood's
plea makes little difference in his case. He has called Wood a
pathological liar whose credibility he planned to challenge.
   Wood, tentatively scheduled for sentencing on Oct. 11, faces a
maximum of life in prison, with parole possible after 10 years.
   The five victims died at the nursing home between Jan. 18 and
April 7, 1987, of what was assumed at the time to be natural causes.
   Walker police began an investigation after Wood's ex-husband said
his former wife had confessed to him.
   At a preliminary hearing in April, Wood testified the deaths were
part of a pact she and Graham hoped would bind them as lovers. She
said Graham suffocated residents ``to relieve tension.''
   The pair chose patients whose poor physical condition would leave
no signs of a struggle, Wood testified. They abandoned a plan to
spell ``murder'' with the victims' initials after some of the
slaying attempts failed, she said.
</TEXT>
