<DOCNO> AP890908-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-08 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower Against Yen, Nikkei Also Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concern over rising interest rates in Japan and
profit-taking pushed the dollar lower against the yen and depressed
stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today, dealers said.
   The dollar ended the week at 146.62 yen, down 0.25 yen from
Thursday's close of 146.87 yen. After opening at 146.59 yen, the
currency ranged between 146.40 and 146.90 yen.
   Currency dealers said the dollar rose in early trading but
intervention by the Bank of Japan and profit-taking in the afternoon
session quickly stemmed the dollar's rise due to fears of an
interest-rate increase.
   Market participants speculate that the central bank could be
forced to increase the official discount rate, the interest it
charges on loans to commercial banks, to shore up the weaker yen.
   The Bank of Japan last raised the discount rate in May. The 0.75
percentage point increase to 3.25 percent was the first rise in the
key rate in almost a decade.
   ``Some importers bought the dollars for weekend account
settlement, but there was a considerable dollar selling on
profit-taking over concern about rising interest rates,'' said Osamu
Seto, a dealer with Mitsui Bank, a major Japanese commercial bank.
   Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told a news conference that
current exchange rate levels should be viewed ``cautiously,'' and he
said he was ``nervous'' about the yen's recent decline against the
dollar.
   In the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 118.75 points Thursday, shed another 36.75
points, or 0.10 percent, to close at 34,115.81.
   The Nikkei index lost a total of 367.97 points during the past
four trading days after a 135.56-point gain on Monday.
   Securities dealers said the market's main barometer fell during
the afternoon session, reversing morning gains.
   In the market's key first section, an estimated 800 million
shares changed hands in moderately active trading, up from 600
million shares on Thursday.
</TEXT>
