<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0623EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DeathWish-Ethics     09-08 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Wish-Ethics,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judicial-Ethical Experts Say Judge OKing Death Wish Confirms Legal
Doctrine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Atlanta judge's decision to let a
quadriplegic turn off machines keeping him alive affirms developing
legal doctrine that competent people should control their destinies,
say judges and ethics specialists.
   But those attending a bioethics conference Thursday said such
decisions are difficult for judges as medical technology advances
create dilemmas not covered by law.
   ``None of these issues are easy,'' said Judge James Pudlowski of
the Missouri Court of Appeals. ``I think these are the most
difficult types of decisions judges have to make. But someone has to
make them. That's why we're on the bench.''
   The Missouri appeals court in November overturned a lower court
opinion and ruled against the family of a brain-dead women who
wanted doctors to stop giving her nutrients and let her die. The
case is on appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court, which decided to review
it.
   Pudlowski distinguished between the Atlanta case of Larry James
McAfee, 33, who has been kept alive by machines since a 1985
motorcycle accident, and the brain-dead woman's situation. He said
she can breathe without the use of medical technology while the
quadriplegic's life is being sustained by machine.
   ``We can't say to someone ... you can't have any more food and
water,'' Pudlowski said. ``There is a distinction.''
   Earlier this week, Fulton County, Ga., Superior Court Judge
Edward Johnson ruled McAfee's right to refuse continued
life-sustaining medical treatment outweighs the state's interest in
preserving his life.
   Family members and friends testified that McAfee, an avid
sportsman paralyzed from the neck down, had repeatedly told them he
wanted to die rather than continued as he is.
   McAfee himself signed a shaky ``X'' with a pencil held in his
mouth to an affidavit stating, ``I understand turning off the
ventilator will result in my death.''
   In Atlanta, McAfee's lawyer said his client did not expect the
legal process to move as fast as it did, and he has yet to make
plans for returning to Georgia to fulfill his wish to die.
   Randall H. Davis said Thursday that McAfee, who is in an
Alabaster, Ala., nursing home, ``was very pleased to hear about the
details of the order. He was particularly touched by the judge's
sensitivity and demeanor as I explained it to him, but he was
surprised it moved forward so quickly.''
   Davis said it would take ``a week or two at the earliest'' before
McAfee returns to Atlanta. He said McAfee wanted to arrange the
transfer to make it convenient for his family.
   Julie Orr, one of McAfee's sisters, said her brother has not told
the family how he will handle the trip or his death.
   Ruth Putilo, the director of the ethics program at Massachusetts
General Hospital, said at the Reno conference that McAfee's case
``is an interesting moment in legal history, but not a radical
departure from developing law.''
   ``He was a competent man who decided enough was enough,'' she
said. ``I think we're just bringing the patient more fully into the
negotiating process, as it were, in the medical field.
   ``We've moved away from an era when the doctor made all the
decisions and sometimes didn't tell the patient everything. ...
Questions still exist, however, when that person has no way to
communicate his or her wants.''
   Ms. Putilo said these kinds of life-and-death ethical decisions
are difficult for judges, doctors, patients, families involved, and
sometimes the best decision is ``the one that hurts everybody the
least.''
   ``There is not right and wrong,'' she explained. ``There are
several rights and wrongs. A person just has to choose the most of
the right and the least of the wrong.''
   Ms. Putilo and Pudlowski are among an expected 150 physicians,
lawyers, ethicists and judges planning to participate in a
bioethical conference at the National Judicial College in Reno. The
conference runs through Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
