<FIRST>r a PM-CDC-Measles     09-08 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-Measles,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Measles Up Dramatically This Year After 1988 Decrease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More measles cases have been reported in the
United States already this year than in any since 1980, as a decline
in the childhood disease has come to an abrupt halt.
   The national Centers for Disease Control, in its weekly report
Thursday, said 10,115 cases of measles had been reported through
last week. That's nearly five times the 2,170 cases reported at the
same time last year and is the highest total since 1980's 13,430.
   Federal health officials coincidentally issued their final
measles report for 1988 on Thursday, showing that the disease
decreased by 7 percent last year, to 3,411.
   The Atlanta-based CDC said more than 90 measles outbreaks have
been reported this year, mostly at colleges and universities.
However, one outbreak among unvaccinated preschoolers in Houston
struck more than 1,700.
   In Chicago, where officials say school doors will remain shut to
thousands of public school students until they are properly
inoculated and examined for measles, more than 1,000 measles cases
had been reported in the city as of Aug. 23. More than 80 percent of
the cases reported have been among preschoolers.
   The CDC said unvaccinated young children, particularly in
outbreak-prone inner cities, are one of two major impediments to
wiping out measles in the United States. The CDC said the other is
the failure of vaccinations to protect some people, which has
allowed outbreaks in highly vaccinated school populations.
   The CDC this year recommended a second dose of measles vaccine
for children beginning kindergarten or first-grade.
   Everyone born since 1957, when measles was so widespread that
Americans had some natural immunity, is considered a potential
measles risk.
   Dr. Steve Wassilak, a CDC immunization specialist, said: ``It
would be an expensive, exhaustive undertaking to revaccinate
everybody born since 1957.'' But revaccinating children upon school
entry, he said, should ``start chipping away'' at the problem.
   The CDC also has recommended earlier vaccinations for inner-city
children _ as early as 9 months, rather than the standard 15 _ to
try to prevent large outbreaks. Additionally, in the case of school
measles outbreaks, the agency has recommended revaccinating certain
children.
   Specifically, the CDC recommended outbreak revaccinations for
students who were vaccinated before 1980 or vaccinated between ages
12 and 14 months. In both cases, the agency said, studies have shown
diminished vaccine effectiveness.
   ``The two-dose schedule and intensive efforts to raise ...
immunization levels should facilitate the goal of measles
elimination in the United States,'' the CDC said.
   But Wassilak cautioned that measles rises and falls in cycles, to
some degree, and ``even if next year is low, that's not
inconsistent. There's not going to be an immediate effect; it's
going to take awhile for the new policy to deter a significant
number of measles cases.''
   Federal health officials believed measles eradication was within
reach early this decade, when only a few remaining clusters of the
disease remained, but the disease increased between 1983 and 1986.
   Still, incidence of measles remains well below the prevaccine
levels of half a million or more cases a year.
</TEXT>
