<FIRST>r i PM-ArmsTalks     09-08 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Talks,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Proposal Stalled By Greece-Turkey Rivalry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debate within the Warsaw Pact has hindered
agreement on verification procedures as part of East-West arms
reductions, the Soviet ambassador said as talks on reducing
conventional forces resumed.
   Also Thursday, the longstanding rivalry between NATO allies
Greece and Turkey caused an impasse in efforts by the alliance to
limit military maneuvers as part of the negotiations, sources said.
   NATO diplomats in Vienna and Brussels Wednesday put the finishing
touches on the Western plan, described by senior officials as an
unprecedented effort to curb military exercises on the world's most
heavily armed continent.
   The East and West have said they will present proposals on
verifying reductions in conventional forces, but diplomats on both
sides have said privately that disagreements within their alliances
have been difficult to resolve.
   Soviet Ambassador Oleg A. Grinevsky said on West German
television Wednesday night his country would welcome hundreds of
North Atlantic Treaty Organization officers to monitor compliance.
   On Thursday, however, Grinevsky said differences arose within the
seven-nation Warsaw Pact at a meeting in Moscow last week, and he
would not say when the alliance would present its proposals.
   U.S. Ambassador Stephen J. Ledogar said differences on
verification within NATO, which has 16 members, were due to
``geographical reality.''
   With the alliance's European members, ``a thin sliver shaped like
a new moon around the Warsaw Pact,'' any proposal to remove troops
from heavily armed central Europe produces problems on the flanks,
he told a news conference.
   Diplomatic sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said after
the talks resumed that Greece believed NATO set the limits too high
when it proposed requiring military maneuvers be announced in
advance if 40,000 reservists were called up or 1,200 armored
personnel carriers used.
   Greece sought lower limits because of concern about neighboring
Turkey, said the sources, who characterized the matter as a
``psychological problem'' that could be overcome.
   Greek and Turkish relations worsened in 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded Cyprus after Greek-Cypriot officers, seeking to unite Cyprus
with Greece, staged a short-lived coup. The Mediterranean island has
been divided into Greek-Cypriot and Turkish-Cypriot zones since then.
   The West had hoped to begin this third, six-week round of talks
between NATO and the Warsaw Pact with proposals that would help
maintain what Ledogar called the ``breathtaking pace'' of the
23-nation negotiations, which began in March.
   Some diplomats say Norway and Turkey oppose the NATO plan for
reductions in central Europe because weapons withdrawn to Soviet
territory might be moved to their borders.
   Divisions also exist between the United States and Canada, which
want maximum verification, and European nations reluctant to have
inspectors from the Soviet bloc constantly touring their weapons
factories and military bases.
   Ledogar said he hoped proposals for curbing the number of weapons
in storage, armaments deployed during maneuvers and the number of
reservists called up could be presented next week. Verification
proposals should follow, he said.
   Grinevsky told reporters: ``The main thing now is not to declare
our positions; the main thing now is to agree on them. The time for
grand battles of words is over.''
   He and Ledogar expressed optimism about reaching agreement next
year and implementing a plan by 1992 or 1993.
   In proposals made July 13 at the end of the last round of talks,
NATO suggested limiting each alliance to 5,700 combat aircraft and
1,900 combat helicopters, with no nation having more than 3,420
combat aircraft and 1,140 combat helicopters.
   The West wants no more than 20,000 tanks, 16,500 artillery pieces
and 28,000 armored troop carriers for each alliance. In addition,
NATO proposes limiting the United States and Soviet Union to 275,000
soldiers each in Europe outside their national territory.
   In March the Warsaw Pact proposed reducing six kinds of weapons,
including aircraft, by 10 percent to 15 percent by 1994 and a
further 25 percent by 1997, with only defensive forces permitted by
2000.
</TEXT>
