<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollars Retreats, Gold in Tight Range</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar retreated in European trading this
morning, but traders said the outlook for the U.S. currency remained
bullish.
   Gold was trading in a tight range in a lackluster market.
   Major central banks in Europe intervened on Thursday to restrain
the dollar's surge, and the Bank of Japan intervened today.
   The dollar finished down 0.25 yen in Tokyo, closing at 146.62
yen. Later in London, the dollar traded at 146.45 yen.
   ``But the central banks can't go against the market sentiment
with interventions alone,'' said a trader in Frankfurt, West
Germany. The key to the dollar's rise against the mark, he said, was
the decision by the West German Central Bank not to raise key
interest rates this week.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
   _ 1.9828 West German marks, down from 1.9845
   _ 1.7100 Swiss francs, down from 1.7120
   _ 6.6785 French francs, down from 6.6880
   _ 2.2330 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2423
   _ 1,421.20 Italian lire, down 1,426.20
   _ 1.1865 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1842
   In London, the pound traded at $1.5475, compared to $1.5460 late
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $359.75 a troy ounce, up
25 cents from the price late Thursday. At mid morning the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $359.85.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $359.75 an ounce, unchanged from late
Thursday.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose 54 cents a troy ounce to close at $360.25.
   Silver traded at $5.13 a troy ounce, compared to $5.11 late
Thursday.
