<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-SouthAfrica     09-08 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-South Africa,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Raps ANC But Wants to Expand Contacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says it differs strongly
with the violent methods of the African National Congress but
intends to expand its contacts with the black group in an effort to
dismantle racial segregation in South Africa.
   ``As the oldest African nationalist movement in South Africa, the
ANC reflects the aspirations of many blacks for a just and
democratic system,'' the department said in a policy statement
released Thursday night.
   It also called for the release of ANC leader Nelson R. Mandela,
who has been imprisoned since the early 1960s, by the new government
of acting President F. W. de Klerk.
   ``The ANC is one of several organizations with substantial
political support in South Africa, particularly but not only among
blacks,'' the statement said. ``It is a political diverse
organization representing a range of views.''
   The Bush administration intends to expand its dialogue with the
ANC and other South Africans across the political spectrum, the
statement said.
   Earlier, the State Department called on South Africa to end the
state of emergency it imposed in 1986 and legalize the ANC and other
anti-apartheid groups.
   And yet, the department's statement said ``we strongly differ
with the ANC on some of its methods for pursuing these objectives.
We have condemned its use of violence, as we have all violence in
South Africa, whatever its source.''
   Department spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler called the election
of de Klerk ``a mandate for real change in South Africa.''
   The department press office said later that Secretary of State
James A. Baker III would like to meet with de Klerk ``at a mutually
convenient time.''
   Congratulating de Klerk on his election, Ms. Tutwiler said: ``We
are committed to working with all parties to bring the South African
government and black South Africans together in a substanial effort
to end apartheid.
   ``We therefore are prepared to work with the new government
toward this end. The most important first step in the process is
dialogue among South Africans.''
   She offered no hint as to what role the United States may play in
promoting an end to apartheid.
   U.S. influence in South Africa declined sharply after Congress
imposed sanctions against that country in 1986 over President
Reagan's veto. There has been little high-level contact between the
two governments since.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
