<DOCNO> AP890908-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1040EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     09-08 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Calls For U.S. Diplomats to Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Michel Aoun today called on
Washington to send back its diplomats, taking a conciliatory tone as
his besieged Christian forces battled Syrian troops outside Beirut
with tanks and mortars.
   War-weary residents of the capital got a respite today as the
fighting raged in rain-lashed mountains overlooking Beirut, center
of a 6-month-old confrontation between Aoun's Lebanese Christian
forces and the powerful Syrian army allied to Lebanese Moslem
militias. No injuries were reported.
   Aoun's three-man Cabinet issued a statement urging the United
States to ``reconsider the evacuation of its diplomats from Lebanon
in order to preserve bilateral relations.'' On Thursday, Aoun lashed
out at the United States, saying its decision to pull out was based
on half-truths and propaganda.
   U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy and 29 diplomats were airlifted
from their fortified embassy in Christian east Beirut on Wednesday
after Aoun accused Washington of siding with Syria and reportedly
threatened to seize Americans.
   The pullout heightened the Christians' sense of isolation at a
time when Aoun seeks to muster international support for his
campaign to drive the Syrians out of Lebanon. Syrian troops came to
Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate Aoun says they
betrayed by siding with the Moslems.
   Aoun's new conciliatory tone was adopted after he summoned his
chief aides to a meeting in his underground command bunker, two
floors below the shell-battered presidential palace in Christian
east Beirut, to assess the repercussions of the U.S. move. The
withdrawal marked the first time the U.S. mission in Beirut has
closed since the civil war began in April 1975.
   McCarthy and his staff were evacuated a few hours after 1,000
young Christians besieged the embassy compound, demanding U.S.
action to help them.
   The Christians believe Washington has not tried to rein in the
Syrians, who outnumber Aoun's forces by 3-1, for fear of harming
U.S. hostages held by in Lebanon by Iranian-backed Moslem
fundamentalists. Syria is Iran's closest ally.
   Eight Americans are among 16 Westerners missing in Lebanon. The
other captives are four Britons, two West Germans, an Italian and an
Irishman. Sunny Mann, the wife of one of the Britons, Jack Mann,
said today she believed he died in captivity, but the British
government did not confirm that.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads a Syrian-backed
Moslem Cabinet vying for power with Aoun's, expressed regret today
at the U.S. withdrawal.
   In a statement broadcast by the Moslem-run Voice of the Nation
radio, he said he ``hopes that all foreign diplomats would return to
Lebanon.''
   Aoun's appeal today made no reference to his previous statement
that he would welcome the American diplomats' return only if
Washington recognizes his Cabinet as Lebanon's ``legitimate
government.''
   McCarthy, who arrived in Lebanon a year ago, did not present his
credentials to either Aoun or Hoss.
   Lebanon's majority Moslems want a bigger share of power in
running the country traditionally dominated by Christians, who are a
minority.
   The current round of fighting broke out March 8 when Aoun
blockaded illegal ports south of Beirut run by Syrian-backed
militias in a vain bid to restore long-eroded government authority.
   A police spokesman said today's battles raged around Douar area,
12 miles northeast of Beirut. Douar controls one of the main routes
into the beleaguered Christian enclave north of the capital.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations,
said there was no immediate report of casualties. At least 830
people have been killed and 2,462 wounded since the artillery war
began in March.
   Ninety percent of Beirut's 1.5 million people have fled the
divided city, which is shelled almost daily by both sides.
</TEXT>
