<FIRST>r a PM-EthiopianTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0527 09-08 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopian Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0527,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopia, Eritrea Start Preliminary Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with talks resuming, comment from
Mayor Andrew Young. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `It makes...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of Ethiopia and a rebel Eritrean
group opened preliminary talks on ending the war they have waged
since 1961, meeting far from their African homeland with former
President Jimmy Carter acting as neutral observer.
   Delegations from the government and the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front met with reporters and issued opening statements
Thursday, then went behind closed doors at the Carter Center to try
to set an agenda for more substantive negotiations. They resumed
their talks this morning.
   ``When you consider that this is a 40-to-50-year struggle, the
fact that they're there is a great accomplishment,'' Mayor Andrew
Young said today after attending a breakfast meeting at the center.
``And the mood is, you know, friendly, but this is real difficult
for both sides.''
   During breakfast, Young said, there was ``still not a great deal
of interchange'' between the two sides.
   He said the talks were taking place not across a table but in ``a
kind of living room environment ... as though they were in the
Carters' home, talking.''
   No time limit was set for the preliminary talks. Young, who was
United Nations ambassador during the Carter administration, said
today that he thought they would go at least into the weekend.
   Carter had said earlier that giving progress reports before the
talks ended would be counterproductive.
   ``It makes it very difficult if both sides are giving their own
separate and sometimes conflicting reports about the process and
also revealing private statements made in the talks,'' said Carter,
who as president a decade ago helped bring about the Camp David
accords between Egypt and Israel.
   Ethiopia and Eritrean rebels have been fighting over the
independence of the province of Eritrea, a former Italian colony
that has Ethiopia's only direct access to the Red Sea. An estimated
1 million people have died in the war and related famine.
   The rebels considers the conflict to be a war for independence;
Ethiopia views it as a battle for secession.
   A U.N. agreement federated Eritrea with Ethiopia in 1952. Rebel
groups began forming in the early 1960s when they did not get
self-rule and Ethiopia unilaterally annexed the area.
   Leaders of both sides referred Thursday to the bitter divisions
between them.
   ``The search for peace ... should not be viewed as a subterfuge
to buy time, or, still worse, as part of military maneuvers and
tactics of war,'' said Alamin Mohamed Saiyed, the head of the
Eritrean delegation and a member of the Politburo of the Eritrean
People's Liberation Front.
   Ashegre Yigletu, head of the government delegation, said Ethiopia
has tried repeatedly during the past 15 years to end the conflict
peacefully.
   ``These peace talks should start off in an atmosphere that avoids
polemics and recrimination,'' he said.
   Alamin and Ashegre each sat with stern expressions as the other's
statement was read in Arabic then translated for the
English-speaking reporters. But, prodded by Carter, they rose at the
meeting's conclusion and shook hands.
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution quoted unidentified diplomats
Thursday as saying Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak would mediate
further talks if the Carter Center sessions were successful.
   The Atlanta talks are under the auspices of an informal group
called the International Negotiating Network, which includes
scholars and former diplomats and operates out of the Carter Center.
   The Carter Center, opened in 1986, houses the presidential
libaray, a museum, a think tank and organizations dedicated to
peace, public health and other issues.
</TEXT>
