<FIRST>r a PM-RivieraFire     09-08 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riviera Fire,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Forces Evacuation of Las Vegas Resort, Sprinklers Credited</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gamblers and guests safely evacuated a resort
hotel when a fire raced through a new casino wing under construction
and burned several dozen hotel rooms in an adjacent building.
   But within hours, guests in the Riviera Hotel were moved to
undamaged rooms, the existing casino reopened and only two minor
injuries were reported.
   ``The first thing we did was secure all of the money (in the
casino) and evacuate all the people,'' said hotel president Mark
Sterbens.
   ``Everything worked the way it was supposed to work,'' hotel
chairman Arthur Waltzman said of the Thursday morning fire.
   ``We went through some pretty dark smoke getting out of the
casino,'' said Dr. Paul Bender of Jefferson, Ind. ``The hotel people
should be given credit for getting people out in a non-panic way.''
   The blaze in the new wing licked up the exterior of the
nine-story original part of the hotel, breaking windows in 75 rooms.
Automatic sprinklers in the rooms quickly beat back the flames, but
the fire in the new casino wing took firefighters about two hours to
extinguish.
   Damage was estimated at $3.5 million.
   The sprinklers were installed in the early 1980s when tough new
state laws were enacted following blazes that killed 87 people at
the MGM Grand Hotel and eight people at the Las Vegas Hilton.
   ``This is a great example of the importance of sprinklers,'' said
Bob Leinbach, a Clark County Fire Department spokesman.
   Clark County Fire Department spokesman Bob Leinbach said the
blaze was touched off by welders working on the new wing.
   The fire also spread to the eaves of an existing casino area and
burned part of an outdoor sign on the casino. Embers from the blaze,
fanned by 25 mph wind, blew across the street and briefly set the
roof of a motel on fire.
   The existing casino reopened Thursday evening and a show with
singer Paul Anka went on an hour later in the hotel's showroom.
Hotel officials offered guests free tickets to the show and a free
prime rib buffet.
   Sterbens said the hotel's 2,200 rooms were sold out, but some
people with reservations had canceled, allowing hotel officials to
move guests from damaged rooms into other rooms.
</TEXT>
