<FIRST>r i PM-SecurityTalks     09-08 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Security Talks,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets May Soon Exchange Military Information</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arms Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, the Soviet Union and
their allies are moving toward their first exchange of military
doctrines and detailed information on armies and weapons, a senior
U.S. arms negotiator said today.
   John J. Maresca, the chief U.S. delegate to the 35-nation talks
on enhancing security in Europe, sounded a hopeful note, but
cautioned that the East and West are still far apart in a dispute
over whether to include naval and air forces in the negotiations.
   The participants at the talks include NATO and Warsaw Pact
nations and neutral European countries.
   ``I believe that these negotiations are now well positioned to
move forward. However, we must be realistic,'' Maresca told fellow
negotiatiors at the start of the third round of the negotiations.
   A copy of his speech was made available to The Associated Press.
   ``The common ground which has emerged over the first two rounds
can only lead to an early positive conclusion if proposals which are
unlikely to attract consensus are put aside. This will undoubtedly
be the most difficult task before us,'' he added.
   NATO and Warsaw Pact countries are holding separate talks in
Vienna on reducing conventional weapons. Both sets of talks are
scheduled to continue through Oct. 20.
   Maresca said an agreement in principle has been reached in some
areas at the 35-nation talks. One important agreement is on the
annual exchange of military information among East, West and neutral
nations on the world's most heavily armed continent.
   ``The principle of a regular exchange of information has now, I
believe, been broadly accepted in this forum,'' Maresca said of the
35-nation talks, which bring together the United States, Canada, the
Soviet Union and all European nations except Albania.
   Details on how these nations will set up a data bank and which
information they will share on troop deployments, weapons
procurements and a host of other military matters remain to be
worked out, Maresca noted.
   Neverthelesss, ``A breakthrough has been made with acceptance in
principle that there should be such an exchange,'' he said.
   ``This represents an important step forward which can only have a
positive effect on the range of arms control talks currently under
way,'' Maresca said.
   A major outstanding issue in the talks is the Soviet insistence
that naval and air forces be included in the talks.
   NATO insists they were never meant to be part of the negotiations
and would further complicate already complex talks. The West also
believes that land forces pose the greatest threat on the continent.
</TEXT>
