<FIRST>r a PM-NightTrials     09-08 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Trials,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Night Trials Planned To Ease Backlog of Felony Cases, Jail Overcrowding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Cook County courtrooms will be opened for
trials at night in a move to alleviate jail overcrowding and a
soaring backlog of pending felony cases.
   Chief Circuit Court Judge Harry Comerford said Thursday that
plans are being developed to use five Cook County courtrooms at the
Criminal Court complex, especially for trials of defendants charged
with drug offenses and related crimes who have been unable to post
bond.
   In addition, Comerford said six divorce courtrooms in one court
building will be converted to felony trial courtrooms.
   Comerford said the measures should increase the capacity of the
county's criminal court system by about 30 percent, raising the
number of felony courtrooms from 39 to 50.
   ``When we have a crisis like the jail overcrowding and burgeoning
criminal court calls, we have to take dramatic steps,'' Comerford
said. ``This may be a temporary but necessary move because we have
to do something drastic to alleviate the problems.''
   The latest figures show the inmate population at Cook County Jail
at more than 7,000 for the first time, and that more than 900
inmates are without beds.
   In February, a federal judge fined the county $1,000 each day
that the jail population exceeds the number of available beds. The
judge made the order retroactive to December 1988.
