<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1136EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   09-08 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0525,0827</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Dominates New Proposed Cabinet</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs UPDATE with Solidarity getting additional
post, raises time element. Pickup 8th, `One woman...'; subs 15th graf,
`Mazowiecki nominated ...,' with 1 graf to conform. Pickup 16th, `Solidarity
also...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity would have authority over
foreign affairs and the broadcast media in a proposed government
that would allow the Communist Party to retain control of the police
and military.
   Under the proposed government of former Solidarity activist
Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the first non-Communist prime minister in the
Soviet bloc, the trade union would have 12 Cabinet posts and the
Communists would have five.
   The Solidarity-allied United Peasant and Democratic parties would
have four and two Cabinet-level posts, respectively.
   Committees of the Sejm, or lower house of the National Assembly,
began hearings on Mazowiecki's nominees today and planned to vote
Tuesday on Mazowiecki's proposed government.
   No official list of nominees was released. The party newspaper
Trybuna Ludu, the pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza and the
state PAP news agency all published lists today and Thursday that
varied in some details. Government and parliamentary sources also
provided slightly varying accounts.
   But the general shape of the proposed government was known and
appeared likely to win approval in parliament, which is dominated by
a Solidarity-led coalition.
   According to an unofficial list of nominees compiled from
government and parliamentary sources, Solidarity will run six
government departments, or ministries. It also is to have at least
six Cabinent-level posts that are essentially ministers without
portfolio.
   One woman was among the 20 nominees: proposed Culture Minister
Izabella Cywinska, a prominent theater director.
   The prestigious post of foreign minister was denied the Communist
Party and given to Krzysztof Skubiszewski, a lawyer close to the
Roman Catholic Church.
   The relatively unknown Skubiszewski, an adviser to Polish church
leader Cardinal Jozef Glemp and specialist in German-Polish
relations, was considered a compromise in the fight between
Solidarity and the Communists for the post.
   The pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza called Skubiszewski
``neutral'' because he is not active in Solidarity, although
Mazowiecki was overheard by reporters telling lawmakers the nominee
had been a Solidarity member.
   The Communist Party, which had directed the government since
1948, will have just four ministries plus one member without
portfolio in the Cabinet, for a total of five posts on the Cabinet
council.
   However, it will retain control of the interior and defense
ministries, which run the military and security police.
   The United Peasant Party is to have four ministries and the
Democratic Party is to have two, according to the unofficial list.
Both parties are allied with Solidarity.
   
   Mazowiecki nominated Solidarity members to head the ministries of
finance, labor, planning, industry, building and housing, education
and culture.
   
   Solidarity also would receive the key chairmanship of the
committee that supervises state television and radio, which the
Communist Party has controlled since World War II.
   Besides the interior and defense ministries, the Communists would
have the transporation and foreign trade ministries and a secretary
of state post.
   The Peasant Party would have agriculture, health, environment and
justice ministries. The Democratic Party would head the technology
and domestic trade offices.
   Several nominees have been victims of government repression.
   Jacek Kuron, the Solidarity adviser nominated for labor minister,
has spent more than nine years in prison. Henryk Samsonowicz,
nominated as education minister, was dismissed as rector of Warsaw
University in 1982 because of his sympathy for Solidarity.
   At a news conference after the Solidarity caucus, Bronislaw
Geremek, the union's parliamentary leader, said it was ``very
favorable'' that Communists would not be in charge of most economic
ministries.
   He conceded there were disputes over some choices, however.
   Members of the independent farmers' union Rural Solidarity
objected to the strong role for the Peasant Party, previously allied
with the Communists. Rural Solidarity, which like Solidarity was
legalized in April after a seven-year ban, contends it is the
authentic voice of the countryside.
   Rural Solidarity activists ran for the parliament as part of
Solidarity's successful campaign and are an important faction in the
caucus.
   Jozef Slisz, the Rural Solidarity leader, was quoted by the
Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza on Thursday as saying his group
was offered only the Environment Ministry and ``it does not suit
us.''
   ``The Peasant Party, which has no say in the countryside, got
more, and we, who are the main force, got nothing,'' he said.
   Mazowiecki was named prime minister on Aug. 24 after the
Communists, weakened by elections in June, failed to form a
government. The elections were among reforms agreed on this spring
between Solidarity and the government after widespread strikes last
year.
   The new government will face an economy wracked by inflation, low
productivity and a foreign debt of $39 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
