<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SovietRefugees     09-08 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Refugees,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Urge Boost in Number of East European Immigrants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats are urging President Bush to
boost by 100,000 the number of East European refugees allowed to
enter the United States over the next 12 months.
   A letter to Bush signed by House Majority Leader Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., and Rep. William O. Lipinski, D-Ill., said that
while the Iron Curtain has begun to open to permit people to leave,
an American bureaucratic curtain keeps most of them from coming to
the United States.
   ``Unfortunately, the gates to America for those who have suffered
under communist regimes are closed,'' Gephardt and Lipinski said.
   While immigration policy favoring family reunification and job
skills is generally correct, ``it has prevented American policy from
reacting to the increase in emigration from Eastern Europe,'' they
said in the letter released Thursday.
   Restrictions on emigration are being eased by the Soviet Union
and other Eastern European nations, but immigration to the United
States from the region decreased from 27,480 in 1982 to 12,838 in
1987, they said.
   The Bush administration has resisted increasing refugee totals,
with some officials contending that the United States can no longer
accommodate the large numbers of people wishing to immigrate. The
1989 immigration ceiling for the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe is
31,500 and has been filled.
   ``Ongoing suppression and persecution in these communist
countries justifies America's acceptance of Eastern European and
Soviet refugees,'' the letter said.
   Ronald H. Brown, chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
endorsed the move to increase the flow of refugees from Eastern
Europe to the United States.
   ``The president ought to use his authority to help the thousands
of people that have already fled communist regimes in the Soviet
Union and Eastern Europe,'' Brown said in a statement. ``His
leadership on this initiative is critical.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
