<HEAD>Medieval Fortress Crumbles at Sound of Voices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The walls of the medieval castle of
Primda may have resisted many an invading knight centuries ago, but
in the 20th century, they crumble at the sound of a human voice.
   In July, debris from the crumbling castle in western Bohemia
killed one boy and injured two. In reporting Friday on the cause of
the accident, the state news agency CTK said chemical changes caused
by polluted rain water have resulted in the castle walls having
virtually no strength.
   ``When a group of young people spoke loudly inside the castle,
the vault started trembling and one part of it fell down,'' a team
of experts concluded, according to CTK.
   It said the castle had been closed.
</TEXT>
