<SECOND>AM-Norway-Racism,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugee Debate Hints of Racist Backlash Amid Election Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARENDAL, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tide of refugees is forcing this insular
country to cope with a backlash of racism as it heads toward a
national election. It is one of the hottest issues of the campaign,
but many candidates are reluctant to touch it.
   Anti-immigrant sentiment is partly credited for the rising
popularity of right-wing leader Carl I. Hagen, who has emerged as
the main challenger to Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland and her
Labor Party in the Sept. 11 vote.
   Polls predict his Party of Progress may jump from two seats in
the 157-seat Parliament to as many as 32 in the new 165-seat
legislature.
   Hagen says Norway cannot afford to support refugees, whose number
swelled 10-fold in two years, peaking in 1987 at about 8,600.
   In recent months, immigration centers and homes have been bombed
or shot at. Two Pakistani immigrants were stabbed to death in July.
   Those wanting to keep out refugees claim they burden the social
welfare system, take jobs, bring more crime and drugs, have
extremely large families and ``steal'' Norwegian women.
   At the opposite pole are Norwegians who have disrupted
anti-immigration rallies and sheltered refugees facing deportion.
   The dispute has soured the taste of Western liberty for some
newcomers.
   ``If we work, they sng a report
on how the public can be better informed about new health and
environmental risks.
