<FIRST>u a PM-StarvationTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0540 09-08 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Starvation Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0540,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts Cottams In Son's Starvation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to RECAST, add maximum sentence, appeal planned,
background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) _ A jury today convicted a couple of
third-degree murder in the starvation of their 14-year-old son while
the family went without food for six weeks though they had nearly
$4,000 they were saving for their church.
   The jury deliberated a half-hour today after considering the case
for little more than an hour Thursday night.
   The defendants, Larry and Leona Cottam, held hands but displayed
no emotion when jury foreman Maria Uitti read the verdict.
   Jurors also convicted the couple of two counts each of recklessly
endangering another person and endangering the welfare of children.
Son Eric died Jan. 3 after the family had not eaten since Nov. 22;
Cottam summoned police the day after the boy died.
   They could be sentenced to up to 28 years in prison on all
counts. No sentencing date was set.
   The family fasted despite $3,775 in savings set aside as a tithe,
or offering, for God. Cottam, a former Seventh-day Adventist
minister, believed spending the money would have amounted to
stealing.
   Their other child, 12-year-old Laura, has recovered from
malnourishment caused during the fast and has been placed in foster
care.
   In his instructions to the jury, Luzerne County Common Pleas
Court Judge Gifford S. Cappellini said malice in the case had a
legal definition, including a combination of a hardness of heart and
conscious disregard to a high risk of death or serious bodily harm.
   The jurors also could have convicted the couple of voluntary or
involuntary manslaughter if they found them innocent of third-degree
murder, which requires a finding of malice.
   Defense attorney Al Flora Jr., in his closing argument Thursday
afternoon, said Cottam, 39, and Mrs. Cottam, 38, feared losing their
children if they went to authorities for help during the six weeks
the family went without food.
   Flora said the Cottams mistakenly believed God would intervene to
save them during their fast, meaning they weren't legally
responsible for Eric's death.
   He said the couple distrusted society after Laura and Eric told
them they were sexually abused by several people including their
paternal grandparents _ who denied the charges _ as well as a
Seventh-day Adventist leader and officials at a church school near
their home in Nuangola in northeastern Pennsylvania.
   But prosecutor Thomas Marsilio, Luzerne County assistant district
attorney, said the Cottams, not society, were to blame for their
son's death.
   ``The parents watched him die, and they didn't lift a finger to
prevent his death,'' Marsilio said in his summation to the jury
before a packed courtroom.
   A Phladelphia jury heard testimony during the nine-day trial
after Cappellini decided pretrial publicity made picking an
impartial jury in Luzerne County impossible.
   Flora said the couple would appeal. They remained free on bond
today pending the appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
