<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Autonomy     09-08 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Autonomy,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Poles Want Autonomy Within Lithuania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As if the Soviet Union didn't have enough trouble
with republics demanding autonomy or outright sovereignty, now
40,000 ethnic Poles want their own piece of Lithuania.
   The demand by the Salcininkai district has put Lithuanian
officials, who complain of Moscow's authority over their Baltic
republic, in the uneasy position of hearing the same arguments about
their authority over Salcininkai.
   ``This is a cry from the soul, the desire of the people to say
what hurts,'' L. Yankelevich, chairman of the Salcininkai regional
council, told the official Tass news agency.
   Tass quoted V. Belskaya, a kindergarten teacher, as saying at the
council session that made the demand: ``We see autonomy as the only
way today to protect our people's interests.''
   The council voted 50-14 to declare the region autonomous and
residents carrying Polish flags rallied outside the council
building, the news agency reported Thursday. It did not say when the
vote was taken.
   Salcininkai, 30 miles south of the Lituanian capital of Vilnius
and near the border with Byelorussia, is a traditionally Polish
district, Tass reported. It said the population now is 81 percent
ethnic Polish and only 7 percent Lithuanian, while the republic as a
whole is 80 percent Lithuanian.
   Ethnic Poles fear the campaign for Lithuanian sovereignty
organized by the political movement Sajudis, which so far has
produced a law making Lithuanian the official language.
   A major complaint in Salcininkai is that the law requires
interoffice communications to be in Lithuanian by January 1991, even
if nearly all employees are Polish.
   Members of the district council complained of a case in which an
accountant four years short of retirement would have to leave early
because he could not learn Lithuanian well enough in the time
allowed, Tass said.
   Lithuania's language law took effect in February, before
resistance stiffened among ethnic minorities in small Soviet
republics that seek greater autonomy.
   The Soviet Union encompasses 100 ethnic groups, and animosities
exist between many of them.
   In the Moldavian republic on the Romanian border, Ukrainians,
Russians and other non-Moldavians are in the third week of a strike
to protest a law making Moldavian the official language. Ethnic
Moldavians make up 64 percent of that republic's 4.2 million people.
   A Christian Turkish people known as the Gagauz, a small minority
in Moldavia, are demanding an autonomous district.
   Many republics have passed laws making the tongue of the dominant
ethnic group the official language, and more are being prepared.
   In Salcininkai, the people appear inspired by Kremlin reaction to
the Baltic campaign for sovereignty rather than Poland's experiment
with democracy.
   Some banners carried by the crowd at the council building said
``Down with the Sajudis Dictatorship,'' and others expressed support
for a tough Kremlin statement that separatists were leading the
Baltics into an abyss, Tass reported.
   It said President Vytautus Astrauskas of Lithuania and S.
Gedraitus, a secretary of the republic's Communist Party, attended
council meetings and urged patience.
   Tass quoted Astrauskas as saying the council decision did not
make autonomy a fact and declaring: ``Earlier we worked together in
friendship and no problems arose. That's the way we'll search for a
solution.''
</TEXT>
