<FIRST>r i AM-SoccerViolence     09-08 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Violence,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Fears Force England to Cancel Holland Match</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   England on Friday canceled a soccer match against
Holland because of fears there would be an outbreak of fan violence.
   The Football Association said its executive committee voted
unanimously to accept the British government's plea to call off the
Dec. 13 match in Rotterdam.
   On Wednesday night, more than 100 English fans attending an
England-Sweden World Cup qualifying match were arrested after a
rampage through central Stockholm.
   This prompted Sports Minister Colin Moynihan to write to the
association Thursday seeking cancellation of the Dutch game ``in the
interests of the future of English football and of the country as a
whole.''
   Dutch soccer fans also have a reputation for violence and
Moynihan's letter warned that there was no way to stop English
hooligans from reaching Rotterdam.
   England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland play as separate
nationalities and there is no team for Britain.
   Hooliganism has become the scourge of England's most popular
sport, bringing denunciations from Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
and government promises to explore ways of preventing potential
hooligans from following the England team abroad.
   In 1985, 39 people died when Liverpool supporters stampeded at a
match in Belgium. Last year England canceled a match in Italy for
fear of violence.
</TEXT>
