<FIRST>r w AM-AirForce-Costs     09-08 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force-Costs,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Nominee Says Money May be Lacking for Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nominee for the new post of
assistant secretary of the Air Force for space conceded Friday it
may not be possible to pay for all the programs the administration
is seeking.
   ``There's no question that there's more to do than we'll have the
budget for,'' Martin C. Faga told the Senate Armed Services
Committee at his confirmation hearing.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., had asked Faga how the administration
could afford such programs as the National Aerospace Plane, the
hypersonic craft estimated at $3.3 billion, the Advanced Tactical
Fighter plane, and a manned mission to Mars, which with a planned
American base on the moon could cost about $400 billion, according
to some lawmakers.
   ``Reality is going to meet reason somewhere along the line,''
Exon said.
   During the confirmation session, Faga, who spent 12 years on
Capitol Hill as a staff member for the House Permanent Select
Committee on Intelligence, said the Air Force budget for space is
more than $9 billion, including the work the service does on Star
Wars.
