<FIRST>u a PM-RacialAttack     09-08 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Attack,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Young Man Indicted In New York City Racial Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fourth young man was indicted on murder charges
today in the fatal Bensonhurst racial attack, authorities said.
   The man, 19-year-old Joseph Serrano, had been arrested on assault
charges. But he was indicted by a grand jury on murder and other
charges, said Nancy Young, a spokeswoman for DBrooklyn istrict
Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman.
   The additional charges were not immediately released.
   Indicted earlier on murder charges in the Aug. 23 attack were the
suspected triggerman, 18-year-old Joseph Fama, and two others, Keith
Mondello, 18, and Pasquale Raucci, 19.
   Three other young white men have been arrested for allegedly
taking part in the attack on 16-year-old Yusuf Hawkins, but have not
been indicted. Police say they expect to pick up other suspects.
   Hawkins was shot to death after he and three friends, also black,
went to the predominantly white Brooklyn neighborhood of Bensonhurst
to look at a used car and were confronted by a gang of up to 30
whites, authorities said.
   Meanwhile, a top official for the state's court system says race
was not a factor in choosing a 70-year-old black judge to hear the
Bensonhurst racial murder case.
   Justice Thaddeus Owens was selected last week by a panel of
judges and court administrators who bypassed the normal selection
process.
   Matthew T. Crosson, chief administrator of the state court
system, said the need for an experienced judge with an ability to
handle cases receiving a lot of publicity led the panel to choose
Owens, not the fact that Owens is black.
   David DePetris, who represents Fama, said he might file a motion
to block the selection, not because of who was selected but because
the way he was chosen could be a violation of his client's rights.
   However, Albert C. Aronne, lawyer for Serrano, praised the
selection, saying he had tried cases before Owens and he was ``a
good man and a good judge. He's tough and we need someone tough who
calls it the way he sees it.''
