<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0613-a0580 09-08 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0613-a0580,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Drug Use Threatens Nation's `Very Soul'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; deletes last 9 grafs to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, trying to enlist new recruits
in his war on narcotics, declared today that a nation that consumes
as much illegal drugs as America ``cannot long preserve its very
soul.'
   ``Let me challenge you: get involved. There are so many that need
your help,'' Bush said in a speech to a convention of the U.S.
Hispanic Chamber of Commerce.
   Later, he was to deliver another address, with the same message,
before the predominantly black National Baptist Convention.
   Before an Hispanic business audience that cheered his statement
that the war on drugs can be waged without higher taxes, Bush struck
back at critics who say his $7.9 billion strategy is underfunded and
doesn't go far enough.
   ``Those who judge this stategy by a price tag alone don't
understand the problem,'' he said. ``Those critics are the same ones
who complain they don't know how we can fund the proposal'' without
higher taxes.
   ``To some, the first and only answer is to hit the working man or
woman with more taxes,'' Bush said. ``That is not the right answer.''
   Discussing drug use, the president said the government estimated
that 23 million Americans had used illegal drugs last year. He said
8 million Americans had tried cocaine, and that about 1 million used
it at least once a week.
   Beyond that, he said, hundreds of thousands of babies were born
to mothers who use drugs.
   ``A nation with those numbers cannot long preserve its very
soul,'' he said.
   Bush said ``America must take back its streets. We need more
jails and prisons and courts and prosecutors. And, indeed, in my
view, tougher sentences.''
   He called for the death penalty for ``the ultimate drug
violators, those that do the most to corrupt the kids in this
country and strip them of every chance of a meaningful life. I'm
talking about those drug kingpins or those that kill police
officers.''
   Bush's trip here came amid signs that Democrats are rethinking
their strategy of attacking the drug plan.
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph Biden, the Delaware
Democrat who originally said Bush's program was ``not tough enough,
bold enough or imaginative enough,'' said Thursday he wanted to put
the legislation ``on a fast track.''
   Bush's program, seeking $716 million more than already proposed
in his budget, emphasizes a crackdown on drug users and more money
for prisons, law enforcement and treatment centers, as well as more
money to attack the problem in drug-producing countries.
   White House chief of staff John Sununu, speaking with reporters
en route to New Orleans today, said the president did not want to
make the anti-drug package it so harsh that it would ``suspend
constitutional rights'' of citizens.
   He said however, he was pleased that ``Congress seems to be
getting into the swim of things.'' He said the Senate ``ought to be
complimented' for voting to cut their free mail privileges for the
drug war.
   Asked whether the administration would be amenable if Congress
voted more money for the drug war than the $7.9 million called for
by Bush, Sununu said it would be difficult to do that within the
boundaries of the budget compromise the administration has reached
with Congress.
   However, he said, ``if they can find an appropriate readjustment
of priorities'' in shuffling around money, ``we're not going to be
close-minded if there are good suggestions that come from Congress.''
   ``Criminals in this nation must understand that if they commit a
crime, they will be caught; and if caught, they will be prosecuted;
and if convicted, they will do time,'' Bush said Wednesday in a
speech in Baltimore before the annual convention of the American
Legion.
   Training his fire on his critics, Bush said: ``Some, incredibly,
say, well, it's not enough. This from the very people who oppose the
death penalty.
   ``It's that kind of thinking that's lost too many battles
already,'' the president said. ``So let's not let these critics lose
the war.''
</TEXT>
