<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1631EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees     09-08 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Expect East Germans to Leave for West in Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said Friday they expect
thousands of East German refugees to leave for the West within days
from tent camps, summer cabins and other makeshift lodgings where
many have spent weeks.
   One sign of an imminent diplomatic solution was the departure
from the West German mission in East Berlin, with promises of help
in attempts to emigrate, of 116 East Germans who had been inside
more than a month.
   An estimated 6,500 East Germans who fled their strict communist
homeland are in Hungary awaiting passage to West Germany, which
gives East Germans automatic citizenship and help in starting new
lives. More than 300 are in Bonn's embassy in Prague, capital of
Czechoslovakia.
   Another 6,000 East Germans escaped through Hungary this summer to
Austria. Officials of the Austrian Red Cross said Friday nearly 100
had arrived overnight, apparently unwilling to wait for the mass
migration.
   Flight through Hungary began after its liberal communist regime
decided in May to remove barbed wire and other barriers from the
border with Austria. Few East Germans are allowed to visit the West,
but trips to neighboring Hungary have been easy to arrange.
   Rezso Nyers, president of Hungary's Communist Party, said in
response to questions from reporters Friday the East Germans would
be able to leave ``in a short time.''
   ``I can't say what a short time is, whether two or three days or
a week,'' he said when pressed for a more precise response.
   Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the West German foreign minister, said in
a television interview: ``I have the deepest trust in the Hungarian
government that it will find a humanitarian solution. From what
we've heard, we can expect a solution within the next few days.''
   Wolfgang Wagner, a West German relief official in charge of the
Budapest camps, told reporters: ``We see light at the end of the
tunnel.''
   A few days ago, Hungarian officials indicated the refugees might
not leave for weeks.
   Hungary has appeared caught between the two Germanys, anxious to
prove to Bonn that it is committed to Western concepts of human
rights but worried about angering the orthodox leadership in East
Berlin.
   It has a long-standing agreement with its Soviet bloc ally to
return any East Germans caught trying to flee to the West.
   There has been no public explanation of the delay in what would
be the first case of an East bloc country helping citizens of
another escape the West.
   The 116 East Germans left the West German mission in East Berlin
after being promised ``extensive legal counsel'' in their quest to
leave the country, mission spokesman Eberhard Grashoff said.
   He said they were given no promises they could emigrate but left
after talks between a senior West German official and Wolfgang
Vogel, an East German lawyer who often has arranged for East Germans
to leave.
   In Budapest, East German diplomats continued efforts to woo back
some of the thousands of young workers, most of them skilled, who
fled their homeland.
   Dieter Grahmann of the East German Embassy claimed some had
expressed interest in returning in exchange for safe jobs and
guarantees of no reprisals, but he did not give figures.
   In his trailer-office outside the Zugliget refugee camp, Grahmann
listened to fellow East Germans explaining why they had left.
   ``The worst thing for us is that we cannot live the way we want
to, that the party always tells us what to do,'' said a man from
Leipzig.
   An angry woman cut in with: ``Who among the East German
leadership asks whether policies are made for us, the people, or for
the politicians?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890908-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1422EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica Bjt   09-08 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa, Bjt,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Says 29 Killed in Election Day Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid activists claimed
Friday that 29 people were killed during police action on election
day, and they produced grieving relatives to respond to government
charges they lied about the death toll.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok accused Anglican Archbishop
Desmond Tutu and the Rev. Allan Boesak, president of the World
Alliance of Reformed Churches, of lying when they blamed police
Thursday for more than 20 deaths during anti-election protests.
   The two activists held a news conference in which they said the
death toll had increased to 29 and the injuries to 200 in nine black
and mixed-race townships around Cape Town. Weeping women described
how police had shot their children.
   ``The evidence points to the fact that the violence in all these
areas was instigated by the police,'' said Boesak. He called on
Acting President F.W. de Klerk to fire Vlok.
   Tutu called for all Cape Town residents to gather at St. George's
Anglican Cathedral next Wednesday, the day the new Parliament
convenes, for a march into the city ``to express outrage at what is
happening.''
   ``You must condemn what the police have done and you must say to
our people you are sorry ... You must express your condolences to
those who have been bereaved,'' Tutu said in a statement addressed
to the acting president.
   De Klerk, expected to be chosen for a five-year term as president
by an electoral college Thursday, has yet to issue any public
statement about the Cape Town violence.
   Vlok said in a statement that 26 policemen were injured in unrest
late Wednesday and early Thursday following elections for the white,
mixed-race and Indian chambers of Parliament. Blacks are excluded
from Parliament, and militant leaders of all races urged a boycott
of the elections for the two non-white chambers.
   Vlok said Boesak and Tutu ``are deliberately misleading the world
about the true facts surrounding the events in the Western Cape.
They tried to allege that innocent and peaceful persons have been
shot dead by the police in cold blood.''
   Evette Otto and Jemima Miller, two mixed-race women, told the
news conference that is exactly what police did.
   Mrs. Miller said her son, Patrick, 13, was on his way to a shop
with a friend Wednesday and was two doors away from his house in
Bellville when a police van came around the corner. She said people
started running, but the boys didn't think it was necessary.
   Police started firing, Mrs. Miller alleged, and a bullet went
through Patrick's head. He is in unstable condition and doctors are
unable to operate because his brain is swelling, she said.
   Mrs. Otto said her 16-year-old daughter, five months pregnant,
was shot to death at point-blank range by a uniformed policeman as
she stood on a street in Kalksteenfontein.
   Mrs. Otto did not say she witnessed the shooting. But she said
her daughter's body showed she had been shot through the chest at
point-blank range and the ammunition had exited through her back.
   Tutu said he was deeply hurt ``that we should bring our people in
this way to seem to be making a display of our pain, just in order
for certain people to be made to believe that what we say happened
has in fact happened.''
   Vlok expressed his ``deepest condemnation about the lies and the
manner in which the two church leaders have attempted to make
political gains from the unrest.''
   According to Vlok, police are aware of 15 unrest deaths in the
Cape Town area Wednesday night, 10 of them attributed to factional
fighting between blacks in the township of Khayelitsha. He said the
other five deaths were being investigated.
   Cape Town attorney Essa Moosa gave a breakdown of the 29 deaths,
which he said was based on bodies in mortuaries and hospitals. Moosa
said a conservative figure for injuries was 200.
   ``Most deaths were caused by the police,'' Moosa said. He
acknowledged there had been factional fighting in Khayelitsha but
said there was reason to believe one faction ``came out of police
vans.''
   Iris Jantjies, a mixed-race woman, told the news conference she
had also seen policemen shooting ``without reason'' in Khayelitsha,
and they had taken her 25-year-old son Matthew away after he was
shot. She said she did not know whether he was alive and that police
would not tell her where he was taken.
</TEXT>
