<FIRST>r i AM-Walesa     09-08 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Leaves With List of Companies Interested in Investing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa ended a
four-day visit Friday with assurances of West German support for
Polish reform and a list of 26 companies that may invest in his
country.
   Walesa said he was confident the two countries would expand
business ties and improve political relations.
   ``We've taken care of much more here than I had hoped for,'' he
told reporters. ``We have found great understanding and proof that
we can indeed be good neighbors.''
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher pledged his government's
``support for the reform processes in Poland'' and said West Germany
would work to obtain aid from the European Economic Community.
   Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann said after meeting with
Walesa that he would lead a delegation of business representatives
on a visit to Poland.
   Walesa has pressed for aid and investment from West Germany and
other West European countries. The main priorities of the new Polish
government, led by Solidarity, are to revive the economy and improve
living conditions.
   When he arrived Tuesday, Walesa carried a list of 16 proposed
projects for investment by West German companies, all in the Gdansk
area of the Baltic coast.
   The projects, involving more than $90 million of foreign
investment, range from joint production of fiberboard to joint
ventures in shipbuilding.
   West Germany's Industry and Trade Federation, which represents
thousands of companies, gave Walesa a list Friday of 26 companies
interested in taking part, and he met with representatives of some.
   Industry leaders cautioned Walesa during the visit not to expect
large amounts of aid until the risks to foreign capital were reduced.
   He told reporters he knew it would take time to reach agreement
on any of the projects.
   ``It all depends on the companies,'' he said. ``It cannot be
forced. One cannot say in advance how many will be ready to do
business with us.''
   On Thursday, Walesa said he would present other project proposals
to Britain, France and other European countries.
   On a visit to Dortmund, the Soldarity leader told members of the
coal and energy workers union the ``curtain has been lifted between
East and West. We must work together to solve our problems.''
</TEXT>
