<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Dissidents     09-08 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Dissidents,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Raid Dissident Meeting, Seize Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak police raided the Prague
apartment of two prominent dissidents, temporarily detained eight
people and confiscated hundreds of documents, one of the activists
said Friday.
   Anna Sabatova, who with her husband Petr Uhl is a member of the
Charter 77 human rights movement, told The Associated Press in
Vienna by telephone that police also photographed the identity
papers of four French trade unionists who were visiting.
   Eight Czechs visiting the apartment had to go to the police
station, she said.
   Among those temporarily detained were Sasha Vondra, a Charter 77
spokesman who this week was ordered jailed two months but released
pending appeal, and prominent activist Jan Urban, Ms. Sabatova said.
   The police confiscated possessions that included a typewriter,
telephone and hundreds of documents, Ms. Sabatova said.
   ``They just want to make the work more difficult,'' she said,
referring to the dozens of calls the couple must make daily to other
activists.
   She said she believed the action was connected with a pending
case against fellow activist Petr Pospichal, who faces charges of
slander. He, Uhl, Urban and Ms. Sabatova are all active in a
dissident network that distributes information from the East bloc.
</TEXT>
