<FIRST>r i AM-LeipzigFair     09-08 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leipzig Fair,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-East German Trade Slow, Fraught With Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trade between the United States and
East Germany remains at a trickle and is fraught with obstacles and
restrictions, U.S. executives say.
   But many representatives of U.S. companies attending this
autumn's Leipzig international trade fair say business ties are on
the increase and that it is best to get an American foot in the door
of a market that some day may mushroom.
   More than 60 U.S. companies or their European affiliates are
represented at the eight-day trade fair that ends Sunday. Booths
manned by U.S. companies displayed a variety of products from grains
to medical supplies.
   Tom Praster, a U.S. Embassy economics adviser, said the major
problem in U.S.-East German trade is the communist country's lack of
hard currency.
   East Germans prefer to barter their own products for Western-made
goods, he said.
   ``Counter-trading is a big factor in many deals here. You've got
to take something in return, and that is often a problem because
it's sometimes hard to find markets for some of the counter-trade
things,'' Praster told the AP.
   U.S. trade officials say formidible government bureaucracy also
hampers larger deals.
   ``Often the products are purchased by the East German foreign
trade office and then turned over to the end user. When it's time to
service the machine they have to repeat that process,'' Praster said.
   ``The people who are using the equipment _ the hospitals, the
farms or road-building companies _ can't go directly to the
manufacturer and ask somebody to come in and repair it.''
   Despite the low volume of trade between the two countries, most
U.S. businesses say their presence at the fair is important.
   Tom Payne, a marketing consultant for California Raisins, says he
expects the small market for his product in East Germany and Eastern
Europe to grow.
   ``We're here because everybody expects change in the East bloc.
We want to get in on the ground floor.
   ``We believe in time this market can be as good as some of the
West European countries,'' Payne said.
   Although East Germans do sell cheaper raisins imported from
Turkey and Iran in regular grocery stores, they import high-quality
California raisins to make products for export or for sale in hard
currency stores at home, Payne explained.
   ``They use them to make Dresdener Stollen (fruit cakes), which
are exported mostly to Western Europe but also to the United
States,'' he said.
   But East Germany bought only 20 tons of California raisins at
about $1,400 a ton last year. ``It's only a small market so far,
it's still a development project,'' said Payne.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890908-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1752EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-08 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There aren't too many newspaper readers in
Selma who don't know about the engagement of Jeff Stumb and Patricia
Cavanaugh.
   Stumb, managing editor of The Selma Times-Joural, proposed in his
newspaper column on Wednesday. Miss Cavanaugh's acceptance came in
Friday's edition.
   Stumb slipped his proposal into Wednesday's paper after Miss
Cavanaugh had left the newsroom Tuesday night. When the paper hit
the street Wednesday morning, she was still in bed.
   ``The guy from the radio station called me at 7 a.m. to ask me
about it. I didn't know what he was talking about. I was still
asleep,'' she said.
   Stumb said he chose the newspaper proposal because ``I wanted to
do something different, something no one else has ever done.''
   ``It's not exactly the way I imagined being proposed to,'' Miss
Cavanaugh said, ``but I guess it's kind of romantic.''
   Miss Cavanaugh is from Bassfield, Miss., and Stumb is from
Birmingham. But they will be married in Selma because of the
community interest.
   ``I didn't know so many people read the newspaper or that there
would be so much interest,'' she said Thursday. ``The mayor called
to see what I was going to say. Everywhere he or I go, people ask
about it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ron Stetson is used to some pointed attacks,
but this week, he uncovered the big sting.
   A pest control expert, Stetson was called in to remove a 4-foot
wasps' nest teeming with as many as 5,000 wasps from Harriet and Bud
Morrissey's attic.
   Stetson and his technicians zapped the giant nest with five cans
of ``wasp freeze,'' which renders insects unable to fly, then
injected bug poison into the hive itself to kill the colony.
   They returned the next day to haul the nest away. But in the
process it broke, revealing still buzzing insects and larvae.
   ``I've never seen anything like it,'' said Stetson, who has been
in the pest control business for 7{ years. ``I couldn't begin to
guess how long it took to build.''
   Stetson applied a powder that kills larvae for six months,
provided a 30-day warranty, and told them to call back if there was
any more trouble.
   ``I thought how will I know if there's any more trouble?'' she
asked. ``I don't think I'm going to crawl up there.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rubber duck race has turned into a
floating fund-raiser because the original idea ran afoul of state
gambling laws.
   The organizers, Delta Gamma Lincoln Alumnae had planned for
people to pay to sponsor rubber ducks and for prizes to be awarded
to the sponsors of the first fake fowls to cross the finish line.
   But Deputy Tax Commissioner Roger Hirsch said the Star City Duck
Dash set for Sept. 24 would have violated state law on raffles and
lotteries.
   ``You can race all the ducks you want, but you can't gamble on
the outcome,'' Hirsch said.
   The only races Nebraskans can gamble on legally are run by horses
at licensed race tracks, he said.
   So, Hirsch and representatives of the alumnae agreed to a new
approach to the race of 4,000 rubber ducks in Salt Creek. Each duck
will wear a band with the name and serial number of the sponsoring
organization and a ticket number. People will pay $5 to sponsor a
duck.
   After the race is concluded, Hirsch said, ``some lucky person is
going to wade into Salt Creek and draw the lucky duck.''
   ``We will consider the widdle band around the widdle neck of the
widdle duck to be a ticket,'' Hirsch said.
</TEXT>
