<FIRST>b i PM-Denmark-Crash 7thLd-Writethru   09-08 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denmark-Crash, 7th Ld-Writethru,a0647,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>55 People Die in Plane Crash Off Denmark</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for 6th pvs, `There were...' to ADD background
on Lockerbie crash. Pickup 7th pvs, `Partnair did...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered passenger plane crashed in
the Skagerrak Strait north of Denmark's Jutland Peninsula today,
killing all 55 people aboard, rescue officials said.
   ``We have found 19 dead, and there are no survivors... The plane
disintegrated. We just found the main wheel floating and the nose
cone,'' said Kurt Rasmussin, an official at the Danish Sea Rescue
Center. There was no indication any of the wreckage came down on
land, officials said.
   The twin-engine Convair turboprop plane, belonging to the
Norwegian airline Partnair, was flying from Oslo, Norway, to
Hamburg, West Germany, a popular weekend destination for Norwegians
on holiday.
   ``There is no way of finding out the cause of the crash right
now, because we haven't found the black box,'' the plane's flight
recorder, said Rasmussin.
   The plane took of from Oslo's Fornebu Airport and was flying at
23,000 feet when air traffic controllers at Copenhagen's Kastrup
Airport lost contact with it, Sweden's national news agency TT
reported.
   Officials did not immediately raise the possibility of sabotage.
Nearly nine months ago, a bomb hidden in a cassette-recorder blew up
Pan Am Flight 103 as the Boeing 747 was flying at 31,000 feet over
Scotland. The crash killed all 259 people aboard the New York-bound
flight and 11 in Lockerbie, Scotland.
   There were 50 passengers and a crew of five aboard the plane that
crashed today, according to a Partnair official in Oslo, who would
not give his name. He and other officials said the plane was on a
charter flight.
   Partnair did not immediately release a passenger list or describe
the nationalities of those aboard. Its telephone lines were
constantly busy in the hours after the crash.
   The plane crashed 18.5 miles north of Hirtshals on Denark's
northern coast, according to the rescue center at Karup in central
Jutland Peninsula.
   The first ships arriving at the scene found no survivors. Norway,
Denmark and Sweden border the strait, a heavily traveled shipping
route.
   Rescue officials first reported the crash occurred at 6:30 p.m.,
but Rasmussin indicated that may have been wrong. He said the center
was alerted nearly two hours earlier at 4:49 p.m. when controllers
in Copenhagen, 190 miles to the southeast, lost contact with the
flight.
</TEXT>
