<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalClosure     09-08 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Closure,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broke County Hospital In Mississippi Delta Closes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNICA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-bed hospital $350,000 in debt has
closed, and the nearest emergency medical care for residents of
impoverished Tunica County is 36 miles away.
   ``That hospital is not a luxury. It's an absolute necessity given
the demography in that county,'' said Marilyn Farray, a lawyer for
several indigent residents who fought to keep Tunica County Hospital
open.
   ``We may be able to gauge it in the loss of lives,'' Farray said.
``Tunica County Hospital probably will reopen, but there'll be blood
on the floor.''
   A shortage of emergency-room physicians hastened the decision to
surrender the hospital's license and close Thursday, said Tharon
Lee, president of Tunica County Hospital Inc., which has operated
the county-owned hospital since June 1986.
   The hospital had treated few patients other than in the emergency
room since April, when the two physicians then living in the county
_ one of the poorest in the country _ resigned from the staff and
stopped admitting people.
   The Board of Supervisors of the county of about 10,000 people
will meet soon to discuss its options, said board President Paul
Battle. He said he expects the board to terminate its contract with
the non-profit hospital corporation.
   ``We don't have any choice,'' Battle said.
   The board then would be free to review proposals submitted by
others to manage the hospital, said Jim Cox, the board's special
counsel.
   Lee, however, said he informed the state Department of Health on
Wednesday that the corporation will try to get its license back when
physicians become insured for emergency care or when an outside
party provides funding.
   ``It would take a John D. Rockefeller to run just the ambulance
service and emergency room,'' Lee said. But he said four or five
parties are interested.
   Lee estimated the hospital's debt at $350,000, which accumulated
as patients in the county had trouble paying their bills and doctors
stopped sending patients there, fearing the quality of care had
dropped.
   ``When it becomes common knowledge you have financial problems,
every vendor that's involved gets nervous,'' Lee said.
   Cox said the hospital corporation, not the county, is responsible
for that debt.
   The county has a year to get the hospital reopened, said Steve
Egger, branch manager with the Health Department's licensure and
certification division.
   ``It will have to start from scratch again, like a new hospital
coming into the program,'' Egger said.
   The county has taken over the hospital's ambulance service.
Emergency calls are being routed to nursing director Billie
Russell's home. Patients usually are taken 36 miles south to
Clarksdale or 40 miles northeast to Memphis, Tenn.
   ``We're trying as hard as we can to set up some sort of emergency
service center,'' Russell said.
   Battle is confident the hospital will reopen.
   ``You can rest assured we'll have a hospital and an ambulance
service,'' Battle said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
