<FIRST>r w AM-US-Ethiopia     09-08 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Ethiopia,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Welcomes Reported Cuban Decision To Withdraw From Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department responded favorably Friday
to a Cuban government statement that the last of the remaining Cuban
troops in Ethiopia will be withdrawn starting on Saturday.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler estimated the Cuban presence there
at between 2,500 and 3,500 and said their withdrawal would be
``significant'' and ``positive.''
   Cuba dispatched more than 12,000 forces to Ethiopia in 1977 to
help the Marxist government put down a cross-border incursion from
Somalia. The dispute centered on conflicting claims to the Ogaden
region of Ethiopia.
   The Cuban action soured what had been a promising start toward a
more normal relationship between the United States and Cuba.
   The two countries opened diplomatic missions in each other's
capital in September 1977 but, with the dispatch of the troops to
Ethiopia, progress toward improved relations was halted.
   Ms. Tutwiler refused to speculate on what a complete withdrawal
of Cuban forces from Ethiopia would mean for U.S.-Cuban relations.
Late last year, Cuba agreed to withdraw its forces from Angola over
a 27-month time frame and has pulled out a significant number of
troops since then.
   On a related subject, Ms. Tutwiler said the administration was
encouraged by the start of peace talks in Atlanta between
representatives of the Ethiopian government and a rebel group which
has been seeking independence for the northern territory of Eritrea.
   The talks were arranged by former President Carter.
   ``We hope that the discussions that have begin in Atlanta will
lead to a just and durable settlement on terms acceptable to both
sides,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
</TEXT>
