<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearDiver     09-08 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Diver,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diver's Suit Settled With Terms Unknown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scuba diver who said he was sucked
1,650 feet through a pipe at the St. Lucie nuclear power plant has
settled his lawsuit against Florida Power and Light Co.
   ``Both parties jointly filed a stipulation that the case be
dismissed with prejudice, which means (Lamm) cannot refile,'' Robin
Blanton, an attorney for the utility, said.
   The parties agreed not to discuss terms of the settlement.
   But the diver, Bill Lamm of Vero Beach, said Thursday that
attorneys had told him he had a difficult case because he didn't
suffer damages.
   ``Almost everyone said that if I could get $5,000 or $10,000 I
should grab it,'' but he added that the settlement was ``nowhere''
near that amount.
   Several weeks after Lamm's ordeal, the utility announced
structural problems with the concrete slabs that cover the mouths of
two of the three pipes. The utility said holes had developed in the
slabs, creating a whirlpool at the mouth of the pipes.
   While utiltity officials maintained the slabs were intact June 5,
the day of Lamm's dive, an official with the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission later said the holes appeared to be caused by erosion _
and were probably open the day of Lamm's accident.
</TEXT>
