<FIRST>r a AM-Martinez-Lawyer     09-08 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Martinez-Lawyer,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Busy Atlanta Defense Lawyer Gets Perhaps His Biggest Case in Martinez</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Martinez Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer representing purported Colombian
cocaine cartel money-launderer Eduardo Martinez Romero is no
stranger to publicity. In fact, it appears to seek him out.
   Ed Garland, 48, said he was contacted by Martinez's family while
Martinez was on his way to Atlanta from Colombia this week aboard a
Drug Enforcement Agency plane. Apparently, Garland said, a lawyer
friend of his in Miami made the referral.
   ``I'm just a defense lawyer, and I've been practicing law here
for 25 years,'' he said Thursday. ``I had no prior contact with
him.''
   Garland was at Martinez's side when the Colombian appeared
Thursday before a U.S. magistrate to answer charges of
money-laundering and conspiracy to defraud the government. Martinez
is accused of being the ``finance minister'' of the Medellin cocaine
cartel, allegedly the largest cocaine distribution group in the
world.
   After the hearing, Garland wasted no time in setting the stage
for his defense of Martinez _ if he takes the case for the duration.
   ``I think it will be extremely difficult for him to get a fair
trial,'' Garland said. ``My understanding is that he wasn't afforded
any judicial process. He was just picked up and brought here.''
   Over the years, Garland has represented numerous people charged
with drug offenses, ranging from former Atlanta Falcons running back
and broadcaster Harmon Wages to John Paul Sr. and John Paul Jr., a
world-class auto racing team accused of conspiring to smuggle
marijuana.
   A few years ago, Garland was convicted of criminal contempt in
Albany after telling a newspaper reporter _ outside the courtroom _
that a judge was holding a ``sham proceeding'' against his client.
That cost him $500, but the conviction was eventually overturned by
the Georgia Supreme Court.
   Garland, who attended law school at the University of Georgia,
told an interviewer in 1982 that he doesn't mind taking on the
government.
   ``My belief is if it's just me against the U.S. government, it's
a fair fight,'' he said. ``The system is balanced in favor of the
state and against the accused.''
   Famed defense lawyer F. Lee Bailey once said Garland was ``in the
top 25 criminal defense attorneys in the nation.''
   Although many of his clients have been connected to drug money,
Garland says he doesn't accept fees tainted by drugs if he knows
about it.
   ``You have to be concerned that you are not dealing with drug
money or money that's been tainted,'' he said Thursday. ``There are
very set ethical rules on that, and I observe those rules.''
</TEXT>
