<FIRST>r w AM-Olson     09-08 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Olson,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Justice Official Wins $861,600 For Legal Fees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Friday awarded $861,600
in attorneys' fees to former Justice Department official Theodore
Olson, who was the focus of an independent counsel's investigation
in an Environmental Protection Agency case.
   Olson had sought $1.25 million for his lawyers, who successfully
defended him in a probe that began in January 1986 with a
preliminary investigation by the Justice Department.
   Independent counsel Alexia Morrison investigated Olson from April
1986 until last year to determine whether the former assistant
attorney general had testified falsely or obstructed Congress in
1983 when a congressional panel was seeking documents in the EPA
controversy.
   In awarding less than requested, an appeals court panel that
appoints independent counsels said the law firm of Jenner &amp; Block
billed Olson at its premium rate, but should have billed him at its
normal rate that is some $5 to $20 an hour lower. The court also
disallowed nearly $100,000 in requested fees for items such as the
preliminary probe by the Justice Department and the preparation of
the fee application to the court.
   Morrison concluded the Justice Department may have obstructed
congressional inquiries by withholding documents about the
toxic-waste cleanup Superfund, but that there was no evidence Olson
was a participant in any such obstruction.
</TEXT>
