<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LuxuryTrain     09-08 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Luxury Train,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Luxury Chicago-DC Train Venture Bets on America's Romantic Appetite</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven-course meals, a baby grand and original
artwork will greet travelers on a new luxury rail service between
Chicago and Washington, D.C.
   The American-European Express, combining elegance with
convenience, was modeled after the storied Orient Express, as
founder William F. Spann tries to recapture for Americans the
romance of railroad travel.
   ``It's not just a railroad era that's gone by, it's a luxury
era,'' Spann, of Panama City, Fla., said Friday. ``Basically, travel
has become a commodity and what we're trying to do is say ... part
of the American public wants something more than just
transportation.''
   Most of the travelers on today's Orient Express _ which travels
between London and Istanbul and between Paris and Tokyo _ are
Americans, Spann said.
   Passengers on the new stateside express are expected to include
``businessmen holding meetings, newlyweds, people having affairs,''
he said.
   ``We are really trying to say America can compete on a quality
basis with anybody in the world,'' he said. ``We're every bit as
sophisticated and we enjoy fine things as well.''
   The inaugural trip is scheduled to depart from Washington on Nov.
15.
   The express will run two shuttles, each with five renovated
Pullman cars added onto Amtrak's Capitol Limited. Overnight service
will be offered in both directions five days a week.
   Minumum one-way fare for the 17-hour trip is $695 _ $1,042 double
occupancy _ compared with $103 for the Amtrak coach or $356 per
person for the Amtrak sleeping car.
   The express ride includes a private bath, a shower compartment,
individually controlled air conditioning and heating, complimentary
robe and slippers, a facsimile machine and telephone.
   The dining cars are made from Honduran mahogany, decorated with
original artwork and outfitted with fine china and silver, he said.
   Seven-course dinners and full breakfasts are included in the
ticket price, he said.
   The luxury cars can hold 60 people and 13 staff, including the
piano player, said Spann, who organized the venture with European
businessmen.
   The company is spending $10 million to refurbish six sleeper, two
dining and two club cars _ all built in the 1940s. Amtrak does not
book reservations for the luxury cars. Passengers must contact
American-European Express directly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890908-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-IsraeliAttacks     09-08 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Israeli Attacks,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Deplores Rocket Attacks From Jordanian Territory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department deplored on Friday a
missile attack on Israel from Jordanian territory but said it could
not identify the perpetrators and did not plan to suspend its talks
with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The rockets slammed into fields in the northern Jordan valley and
caused no damage. The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
a Marxist group affiliated with the PLO, claimed responsibility.
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat renounced terrorism last year,
prompting the United States to begin talks that U.S. officials said
would be suspended if terrorism recurred.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the United
States holds the PLO to its commitment renouncing terorism and
``deplores the rocket attack'' against Israel.
   However, the U.S. official said she did not know who had launched
the attack and that ``our dialogue continues.''
   The PFLP, formed 22 years ago, is headed by George Habash.
According to the State Department publication ``Terrorist Group
Proflies,'' it ``established itself early as one of the most violent
Palestinian terrorist groups.''
   Among the hijackings the department attributed to the
organization was the hijacking of an Air France airliner to Entebbe,
Uganda, in 1976. Four civilians were killed before Israeli
paratroopers were able to rescue the other passengers and crew. The
paratroop commander, Jonathan Netanyahu, was also killed in the
operation.
</TEXT>
