<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0652 09-08 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0652,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth, Suspected Collaborators Killed in Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `In the ...,' to UPDATE number of wounded to
14; picks up 14th graf: The army ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers fatally shot a 13-year-old Palestinian
during a stone-throwing protest Friday, and three Arabs suspected of
collaborating with Israeli authorities were found dead in the
occupied territories.
   The army said it had arrested four Arabs in the slaying of one of
the alleged collaborators.
   Also Friday, a Syrian-backed Palestinian faction claimed
responsibility for firing rockets across the Jordanian border into
Israel a day earlier.
   In the Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis, troops clashed with
stone-throwers and Akran Zaki Hamdan, 13, was killed, the army and
hospital officials said.
   Hamdan's death brought to 560 the number of Palestinians killed
by Israeli soldiers or civilians since the start of the uprising
against Israeli occupation nearly 21 months ago. Thirty-nine
Israelis have been killed.
   The deaths of the suspected collaborators raised to 110 the
number of Palestinians killed by fellow Arabs. Most have been
accused of collaboration.
   The slayings came despite an appeal by underground uprising
leaders in their latest leaflet. They asked Palestinian activists
not to be too quick to kill suspected collaborators.
   Cocern about security on the usually quiet Israel-Jordan border
rose this week following the rocket attack Thursday and a guerrilla
attack five days earlier in which two Israeli soldiers were killed.
   Israel radios and newspapers said military officials believed
Syria was behind both attacks.
   The first attack was claimed by the Syrian-based Taalat Yakoub
faction of the Palestine Liberation Front. The rocket attack was
claimed Friday in Damascus by the Marxist Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, headed by George Habash.
   Zeev Schiff, a military analyst for the Haaretz daily, said Syria
may be using the border attacks to punish Jordan's King Hussein for
allowing Iraq to move weapons through Jordan to Christian forces in
Lebanon. The Christians are battling Syria's army.
   Schiff also said the Syrians ``are trying to stir up trouble''
between Israel and Jordan.
   In the occupied territories Friday, 14 Palestinians were shot and
wounded in stone-throwing clashes with Israeli troops, including an
11-year-old boy hit with a bullet in the head in the West Bank
village of Tubas, Arab reports said.
   The army announced a raid on the village of Beit Dajan, also in
the occupied West Bank, and said ``a great number'' of Palestinians
were arrested when Israel used helicopters to block suspects from
fleeing into surrounding hills.
   The army said last month it would begin using helicopters in
village raids aimed at rounding up activists in the uprising.
   Late Friday, 30-year-old Ahmed Izat Imran was found beaten and
stabbed to death under a tree near the village of Rujeib in the West
Bank, Arab sources said.
   Imran reportedly was abducted from his car Thursday night by
masked youths. A search was launched by relatives who later found
the body, reports said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, the two alleged collaborators who
were killed were identified as Niman Abu Hilal, 30, who was fatally
beaten at his home in Rafah by masked youths, and Jasser Al Krinawi,
24, whose body was found stuffed in a well in the Magazi refugee
camp.
   The army said four Arabs were taken into custody in connection
with the Krinawi case.
</TEXT>
