<FIRST>u i AM-SouthKorea 1stLd-Writethru   09-08 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0575,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Demand Release of Colleague Facing Death Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `Miss Im...' to add dropped word. Pickup 5th,
`At Yonsei...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students shouted
anti-government slogans and battled police with firebombs Friday to
protest the arrest of a student who made an illegal trip to
Communist North Korea to attend a youth festival.
   About 500 students at Dongguk University in Seoul fought police
with rocks and firebombs, demanding the release of the student, Im
Su-kyong. Police fired tear gas and broke up the protest in one hour.
   Five students were arrested but no injuries were reported.
   Miss Im was arrested on Aug 15 and faces the death penalty if
convicted of charges she consorted with North Korean intelligence
agents.
   At Yonsei University, also in Seoul, 200 students blocked traffic
on a main street in front of their school for an hour, shouting
``Release Miss Im!'' While riot police watched, students unfurled a
large banner reading ``Abolish national security laws.''
   In the southern city of Kwangju, about 1,000 students occupied a
section of a railway near Chosun University and delayed an outbound
passenger train for 35 minutes, the Yonhap News Agency said.
   Police fired volleys of tear gas to break up the crowd, the South
Korean news agency said. Two students were injured by fragments from
exploding tear gas canisters, it said.
   In Taegu, President Roh Tae-woo's hometown 175 miles southeast of
Seoul, 200 student radicals fought police with rocks and firebombs
for one hour before dispersing voluntarily. They also demanded Miss
Im's release.
   Friday's clashes followed a government announcement accusing
North Korea of manipulating dissident movements in South Korea
through its organizations in Europe, Australia and the United States.
   The Agency for National Security Planning, the main government
intelligence organization, said Miss Im's illegal trip to North
Korea in July resulted from the North's manipulation.
   North Korea, the agency said, mobilized several pro-communist
Korean organizations in the United States, West Germany and
Australia to get a South Korean radical student group to send a
delegate to the world youth festival in the North Korean capital of
Pyongyang in July.
   The festival was July 1-8.
   Miss Im was arrested when she returned to the South Aug. 15. She
is charged with other violations ranging from receiving money from
Communist agents to going to the North under Communist orders. If
found guilty on all charges, she could be sentenced to death.
   Radical students regard the South Korean government as a
dictatorship supported by the United States and are demanding the
withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in the South.
   South Korean bans unauthorized trips to North Korea, an enemy
country since the division of the Korean Peninsula in 1945. The
North invaded the South to start the 1950-53 Korean War, and a peace
treaty was never signed.
</TEXT>
