<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs New York-dated item to UPDATE with King's comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio and television talk show host Larry King
told a magazine interviewer he wouldn't mind meeting the right woman
and getting married again. And he did just that before the magazine
hit the stands.
   ``I don't think I'm suited to marriage,'' he said in an interview
published in Good Housekeeping's October issue. ``Sometimes I worry
I'm too selfish to have a relationship. I'm not really.''
   But that interview was conducted months before his engagement
last month to Philadelphia businesswoman Julie Alexander, whom he
plans to wed Oct. 7. They met July 11 and he proposed after their
first date Aug. 1.
   ``So anyone who reads the Good Housekeeping article, should know
that all that changed when I met Julie,'' he said by phone Friday
from his Virginia home. ``They should put a banner on the cover of
the magazine: that July 11 changed my world.''
   King, 55, has been married three times _ twice to the same woman.
   King, seen on the CNN television network and heard on the Mutual
radio network, told the magazine he thought he'd stay single for a
while.
   ``Still, I only know I would have loved to have fallen asleep and
then woken up this morning with my arms around a woman I love,'' he
said. ``I feel something is missing in my life ... some woman who
would keep me excited about her, about us, about life.
   ``Yes, I'd love to find a woman who can do all that and at the
same time still not bug me,'' he said with a laugh. ``I think I'm
going to be sleeping alone for a while, a long while.''
</TEXT>
