<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1909EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolSentence     09-08 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Sentence,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Youth To School, Not Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old reputed gang leader who pleaded
guilty to car theft and robbery has been sentenced to go to school
instead of jail.
   The alternative sentence a Suffolk Superior Court judge imposed
Thursday infuriated prosecutors, who said it would send the wrong
message to inner-city gangs. But a defense lawyer said it would give
the defendant, who dropped out of school in 10th grade, a chance to
turn his life around.
   Judge Cortland A. Mathers warned Christopher Chaney that if he
does not finish high school and go on to junior college, hold a job
after school and stay out of trouble for five years, he will be sent
to prison for four years.
   ``If you slip up, you will go to Concord (state prison),'' the
judge said. ``You would get absolutely no consideration from me if
you come in here before me again.''
   Police said Chaney was second-in-command of the Humboldt Street
Gang, one of the toughest groups in the city's crime-infested
Roxbury section. Chaney pleaded guilty to six charges of robbery,
car theft and receiving a stolen car. At the time of the crimes, he
was on probation for assault with a deadly weapon and receiving
stolen property, police said.
   ``In my opinion, this was the wrong person to give a break to. He
committed six crimes in six months,'' said Assistant District
Attorney Daniel Conley.
   The prosecution had recommended Chaney receive a 20-year prison
sentence and serve two years. Mathers gave Chaney a choice of
serving two years or accepting his proposal.
   ``That was a sentence? I think the judge is trying to be
innovative, but I don't think he's being realistic,'' said First
Assistant District Attorney Paul Leary.
   ``I think that the sentence imposed sends out the wrong message
to the decent people in the community who are being terrorized by
these gang members,'' Leary added.
   Chaney's court-appointed lawyer, Marjory German, argued that
Chaney, if given a chance, could become a role model for other young
black men.
   ``We have heard from police and prosecutors that the only way to
deal with these young black men is to lock them up,'' Ms. German
said. ``The black community is tired of this, tired of having young
black males taken away from them.
   ``The only way out of this vicious cycle for the community, for
all of us, is in education. We know that locking up young black men
has not worked. We've known that for years. It breaks up families,''
she said.
   Deborah A. Ramirez, a professor at Northeastern Law School in
Boston, said alternative sentences are becoming increasingly common
for people who have no prior criminal records, did not commit
violent crimes and are ``low-level (drug) users and victims, rather
than dealers and kingpins.''
   But she said Chaney did not fit those categories and would almost
certainly have received a jail term if he had been prosecuted in
federal rather than state court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
