<FIRST>r a AM-ArmoredCar     09-08 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armored Car,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armored Car Bandits Got Little, Authorities Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two masked bandits apparently got away with
nothing more than a certified mail pickup in a holdup in which an
armored car guard was slain and two other men were wounded,
authorities said Friday.
   Police and the FBI continued hunting for the robbers, who fled on
10-speed bicycles following Thursday's robbery at Bank of America's
world headquarters.
   The mail consisted of ``paperwork, possibly some negotiable bonds
and possibly a small amount of currency,'' said police spokesman
Dave Ambrose. ``It's not a major loss.''
   ``This was not a classic armored car robbery,'' said FBI
spokesman Chuck Latting. ``Everything I see, after 20 years as an
agent, says they made a grave mistake.''
   If caught and convicted of murder, the two men could receive the
death penalty.
   The bandits confronted and shot Brink's Inc. guards Joseph
Arriola, 53, and Clifford Spencer, 24, after they had made their
delivery Thursday morning to a bank on the lower level of the
52-story building, according to Ambrose.
   Arriola and Spencer were shot in the head at very close range
beyond the view of a video camera facing the bank lobby. Robert Gee,
a 57-year-old San Franciscan, was shot in the mouth as he tried to
help the felled guards. Arriola died.
   The robbers, described as two white men with muscular builds,
escaped into the city's crowded financial district on bicycles,
which police recovered about 10 blocks away five hours later.
   Some investigators, who had said the heist had been well planned
and well orchestrated, said Friday they were puzzled by the attack
that apparently netted so little.
   Latting pointed out that the bandits confronted the guards after
they delivered money to the bank, targeted a bank in the heart of
the city's chronically congested financial district and could not
have carried a large amount of cash away on bicycles.
   ``All that doesn't add up,'' he said, adding that authorities are
considering all potential motives.
   Brink's has offered a $100,000 reward for information leading to
the arrest and conviction of the suspects.
   Spencer was in serious but stable condition Friday at San
Francisco General Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Gloria
Rodriguez. The guard underwent surgery for paralysis to his left
side, but Rodriguez did not know if it had succeeded.
   Gee was in good condition with a fractured tooth and a cut
tongue, the spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
