<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Prepares Ethics Code for Housing Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp said Friday his
agency is developing a new code of ethics to prevent the type of
scandals that have plagued the Department of Housing and Urban
Development in recent months.
   ``My first order is to clean house, stem to stern,'' Kemp told a
committee of the National League of Cities.
   Federal and congressional investigators are looking at
allegations of fraud and mismanagement that may have cost the
government billions of dollars in HUD money.
   The actions occurred before Kemp took office earlier this year,
but much of his attention has been focused on cleaning up the
problem, he told the urban representatives.
   ``When I came to HUD, I didn't know about the problems I had,''
he said.
   Kemp said his agency is putting the final touches on ``a program
of ethics'' that is intended to prevent future scandals. He did not
spell out the details.
   But he said the investigation of alleged abuses during the Reagan
administration is hindering his ability to get his own programs off
the ground. His ideas for economic revitalization of the nation's
cities won't be put into practice unless future scandals can be
prevented.
   ``We won't get anything done on Capitol Hill unless we clean
house and get our house in order,'' he said.
   Noting that 1989 is the 25th anniversary of the late President
Lyndon Johnson's ``War on Poverty,'' Kemp said the nation's cities
have not gotten enough help.
   ``As a Republican, I've been disappointed over the years that my
party has not addressed the issues'' of urban America, he said,
adding, ``I'm not here to do a mea culpa.''
</TEXT>
