<HEAD>Irreverent Jester Gets Job Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The court jester suspended without pay for making
fun of the royal family was back on the job Friday after he agreed
to cut the offensive material.
   Royal Britain, the London museum that depicts history through
royalty, suspended James Lovell, 24, on Tuesday after he refused to
stop his jokes, saying at times the barbs were offensive.
   A meeting Thursday night between Lovell and the Earl of Bradford,
who is the chairman of Unicorn Heritage, which owns Royal Britain,
came up with a compromise, marketing director Kim Keble-White said.
   ``We have allowed James to continue with some of his contemporary
material but we must see it first and decide what is offensive,''
Keble-White said.
   Lovell, who worked as a clown and stage actor before taking the
role in January of Will Somers, Henry VIII's jester, was not
available for comment.
