<FIRST>r a AM-BankRobber     09-08 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Robber,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Band Director Arrested in Bank Robbery, Confesses to Four Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A popular high school band director
confessed to robbing four banks after his attempt to holdup a fifth
was stymied by bank employees who recognized him, authorities said.
   Donald R. Hershberger, band leader at George Washington High
School, was arrested Thursday and charged with aggravated robbery
and kidnapping after he attempted to rob the Second Avenue Bank in
South Charleston, Detective David Dunlap said.
   Hershberger, 54, then confessed to four robberies in West
Virginia since May, police said. It was not known how much money was
taken in the robberies.
   Hershberger will be suspended with pay while the charges are
pending, said Kanawha County Schools Superintendent Richard Trumble.
Hershberger's annual salary is $24,646.
   Colleagues on Friday described Hershberger as a personable man
who conducted his job with military efficiency.
   ``He was a task master with the students, he worked them
extremely hard,'' school principal Larry Lohan said.
   ``On the surface, everything appeared to be normal,'' Lohan said.
``He was a quick witted, personable guy. He'd zing you in a second.''
   The principal said students were shocked by Hershberger's arrest.
   ``I met with the band's group leaders this morning and I
explained to them that they were in for a rough time,'' Lohan said.
``I told them that they are going to hear all kinds of comments and
teasing. I'm kind of glad that we're going to be playing out of town
tonight.
   Some students reacted with disbelief.
   ``Are you serious,'' band member Elaine Harris said when
interviewed by WSAZ-TV. ``Wait a minute, this is a joke, right?''
   Police were called to the bank shortly before noon when bank
employees recognized Hershberger from photographs distributed after
the previous robberies, said Brenda Robertson, the bank's president.
   ``Believe it or not, I knew what he was going to do,'' said
Jennings Burch, an assistant bank vice president. ``Before he had a
chance to tell me we were being robbed ... I said, `Have a seat in
my office and I'll be with you in a second.' I went and told our
president, `The bank robber's here. Go call the police.'''
   Burch said the man tried to take him as a hostage, but he broke
free when police arrived. After his arrest, Hershberger admitted
robbing two banks in Charleston and one each in Buckhannon and
Bridgeport since May, Dunlap said.
   In all the robberies, police said, the suspect was described as
wearing a fishing hat, sunglasses and khaki pants.
   Hershberger, who was carrying a small-caliber pistol, is being
held without bail in the Kanawha County Jail pending a hearing Sept.
15.
   The telephone at Hershberger's home was repeatedly busy Friday.
Lohan said Hershberger's wife recently joined him in Charleston.
   Lohan said he hired Hershberger in the summer of 1988 after
receiving excellent references. Hershberger worked as a band
director in Phillipi, Elkins, Weirton; Christiansburg, Va., and
Zanesville, Ohio.
   ``He came highly recommended as a quality band instructor,''
Lohan said. ``I've had nothing other than that kind of performance
from him.''
   ``I really like the guy. He was no-nonsense,'' said John Van
Camp, a music teacher at George Washington. ``Whatever motivated
him, if he's done it, must have been some pretty heavy duty stuff.''
</TEXT>
