<FIRST>r a AM-HikerFound     09-08 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hiker Found,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safe After 15 Days in Mountains With a Broken Leg</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hiker from Great Britain
who was stranded for 15 days with a broken leg in a remote section
of Yosemite National Park was airlifted to safety Friday.
   John Edward Hebden of Cheshire, England, spent seven hours
crawling up a ravine Thursday to a trail where he was found by
hikers who gave him some candy bars, then went to a ranger station
for help.
   Hebden, 20, had failed several times to make it to the top f the
ravine since he slipped on loose gravel and broke his right leg on
Aug. 24, said park spokeswoman Lisa Dapprich.
   ``He's in excellent shape; it's just amazing,'' Dapprich said.
``He only had enough food for several nights.''
   Rangers hiked in to Hebden, near the 9,000-foot elevation
Thursday night, then directed a helicopter crew to the spot Friday
morning.
   Hebden's ordeal began the second day of his hike from Yosemite
Valley 150 miles southeast of San Francisco into the high country
along routes called Sunrise Trail and Cloud's Rest Trail. Hebden had
reached the summit of the Sierra Nevada and was on his way down the
eastern slope when he lost the trail and started down a ravine where
he thought it should be, Dapprich said.
   While trying to cross a section of bare rock, Hebden slipped and
fell on loose gravel and was knocked out. When he came to, he
managed to get into his sleeping bag despite severe pain in his
upper right leg.
   He spent two days in the bag fighting the pain, before managing
to put his tent up, Dapprich added. Hebden got drinking water from a
stream nearby.
   Hebden said he hollered constantly, but apparently no one heard
him.
</TEXT>
