   He said police had found no evidence the Israelis were involved
in Colombia's narcotics underworld.
   Police began the investigation Aug. 27, at the urging of Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, after reports filtered out of Colombia that
Israeli officers may have trained assassins for drug bosses.
   Rabin has said the men, from a private firm called Hod Hahanit,
or Spearhead, had no government license to sell their expertise
abroad.
   Yair Klein, a reserve lieutenant-colonel who heads the company,
has contended no license was required to train private individuals.
He denied training anyone linked to drug traffickers and said his
students were ranchers seeking to protect themselves from guerrillas.
