<FIRST>r w AM-CommoditiesProbe     09-08 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policing the Futures Markets: Computers, Yes; Shouting, Maybe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More automated record-keeping is needed to keep
futures markets honest _ but not at the expense of the traditional
trading methods of shouts and hand signals, a government watchdog
agency said Friday.
   The General Accounting Office said the systems used for keeping
track of trades on the nation's commodities markets are
``fundamentally inadequate'' to detect and deter wrongdoing.
   Last month, more than 40 traders and brokers on the Chicago Board
of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange were indicted on a
variety of charges that the had schemed to defraud customers.
   Among the schemes alleged were falsifying trading records to
conceal the execution of trades at non-competitive prices or ahead
of a customer's trade order.
   ``Most of the types of abuses alleged in the Justice Department
indictments could also have been detected and documented with
independent, precise and complete timing of trades,'' Richard L.
Fogel, an assistant comptroller general with the GAO, told the
Senate Agriculture Committee.
   At issue is the ``audit trail,'' a term describing the
reconstruction of any given transaction, or put more simply:
determining who bought what from whom and when they did it.
   The GAO, an investigative agency of Congress, visited the two
giant Chicago exchanges as well as the two largest in New York _ the
New York Mercantile Exchange and the Commodity Exchange.
   While all four try to track trading activities, ``in each system,
opportunities exist to manipulate the timing, and therefore the
sequencing, of trades,'' said Fogel.
   On three of the four exchanges, much of the record keeping is
left to traders and brokers themselves.
   Are the ``audit trail systems in place at the major U.S.
exchanges are fundamentally inadequate to police the trading floors
against abuses?'' asked Sen. Patrick Leahy.
   ``I think it is. Yes,'' said Fogel, noting that there is no
guarantee that information about the timing of when a broker gets an
order or executes it.
   But Fogel said computerization doesn't necessarily spell the end
of the hurly-burly method of trading in the exchange pits by shouts
and hand signals known as open outcry.
   ``I think that's a question the exchanges themselves need to
answer,'' he said, adding ``I don't personally believe that the
government should dictate how the exchanges want to trade.''
   The two Chicago futures exchanges, the largest in the world, have
been criticized for not keeping a closer watch on traders, while the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which oversees the futures
markets, has been accused of doing so with too light a touch.
   The CFTC, which is up for reauthorization at the end of the
month, has implemented rules requiring the exchanges to be able to
reconstruct a trade to within one minute of its occurence, but the
exchanges say their systems are effective between 84 percent and 90
percent of the time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
