<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-StudentsUnion     09-08 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Students Union,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Students Union Again Seeks Legal Status</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Independent Students Association
applied again on Friday for legal status with the right to strike,
but the provincial court delayed a decision until Sept. 23.
   Prosecutor Jan Szewczuk said he had no objection to the
registration and lawyers for the students noted that President
Wojciech Jaruzelski said conditions should be created to allow the
association to be legalized again.
   The free union movement Solidarity and the students association,
known by its Polish initials NZS, were recognized legally after
their formation in 1980 but were outlawed in 1982 under the martial
law crackdown.
   NZS was denied registration last May 23, although Solidarity and
Rural Solidarity, the independent farmers union, regained legal
status following April accords reached in ``round-table'' talks
between communist authorities and the then-opposition.
   Lawyer Piotr Andrzejewski, representing the students, said after
the hearing Friday, ``I think that the decision can be only one _
registration of NZS on the basis of the rights it possessed before
the introduction of martial law _ and it is going to put an end to
the results of martial law.
   ``But if the decision is negative it will be at the start of a
new academic year and it will be a conscious creation of political
instability in Poland.''
   The sticking point is the students' demand for the right to
strike.
   The court said Polish law had not been revised to permit
including a strike clause in the NZS charter, although there is a
proposal to do so.
   Szewczuk asked the three-judge panel to reverse its May decision,
recognizing a new legal initiative exists based on ``mutual trust''
between authorities and organizations.
   Poland's new prime minister, Tadeusz Mazowiecki, comes from
Solidarity.
   NZS, with a strong and vocal following among college and high
school students nationwide, responded to the May rejection with
strikes, including one at the 16,000-student Warsaw University.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa has asked for a moratorium on
strikes to give Mazowiecki's government time to organize an economic
recovery plan. It is the first government in the East bloc in four
decades not to be led by a communist.
   At a May congress, the students rejected dropping the strike
provision.
   Walesa has said that the communists broke a pledge by not making
NZS legal.
</TEXT>
