<FIRST>r w AM-Manufacturers-SovietTrade     09-08 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manufacturers-Soviet Trade,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manufacturers Call For Lifting Restrictions On Trade With Soviet
Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Manufacturers, one
of the nation's oldest and largest trade groups, called Friday for
Congress and the Bush administration to remove restrictions on trade
with the Soviet Union.
   Specifically, the group said the Soviet Union should be granted a
waiver under the 1974 Jackson-Vanik law, which imposed high tariffs
on imports from any nation that does not allow its citizens to
emigrate freely.
   The Soviet Union, because of its resistance to Jewish emigration,
has been among 15 nations on the restricted list, including Latvia,
Lithuania and Estonia, which are Soviet states.
   ``While ideological differences can be important, they should not
preclude mutually beneficial commercial relations,'' the
manufacturers said in a statement. ``Recent events suggest that
there is now genuine opportunity to improve U.S. economic relations
with the Soviet Union.''
   It said waiving Jackson-Vanik, named after the late Sen. Henry
Jackson, D-Wash., and former Rep. Charles Vanik, D-Ohio, would be a
first step to a new bilateral trade agreement granting the Soviet
Union most-favored-nation trade status.
   Several major Jewish organizations, including the World Jewish
Congress, have come out in favor of granting the waiver.
   Only 914 Jews were allowed to leave the Soviet Union in 1986,
according to the National Conference on Soviet Jewry, which has
tracked the emigration since 1968. However, the number shot up to
8,155 in 1987 and 18,965 in 1988. In the first eight months of this
year, 33,444 Jews have left, including a one-month record of 6,756
in August, the group said.
</TEXT>
