<HEAD>Israeli Defense Minister Says It Would Be A Mistake To Admit Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin sought
Friday to discourage the Bush administration from granting a visa to
Yasser Arafat, the chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Rabin, talking to reporters after a meeting with Secretary of
State James A. Baker III, accused the PLO of escalating violence
against Israel.
   Arafat would need a visa to attend the U.N. General Assembly that
opens Sept. 25 in New York. State Department officials have brushed
aside questions about U.S. intentions as hyothetical, saying the PLO
leader had not applied.
   ``Israel would see it very gravely,'' Rabin said after an
hour-long session with Baker. He had met earlier in the day with
Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Brent Scowcroft, the national
security adviser.
   Rabin and Cheney signed a memorandum expanding defense
cooperation between the United States and Israel.
   Arafat was denied a U.S. visa last year to attend a special U.N.
session on the Palestinian dispute with Israel. The session was
moved to Geneva, Switzerland, to accommodate him.
   Since then, the United States has begun diplomatic discussions
with the PLO and accepted a statement by Arafat renouncing terrorism.
   The State Department spokeswoman, Margaret D. Tutwiler, declined
to provide an account of Rabin's session with Baker. She said no
details were ever given about ``one-on-one'' meetings with foreign
visitors.
   Rabin's trip kicks off a series of visits by Israeli officials.
   He will be followed by Deputy Foreign Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, Finance Minister Shimon Peres and, in November, by Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir. Foreign Minister Moshe Arens will attend
the U.N. General Assembly session.
   The main topic in the talks with U.S. officials is the proposal
by Shamir to hold elections among Palestinians on the West Bank and
in Gaza. The United States, which endorses the plan as a step toward
peace talks, has been unable to sell the plan to the PLO.
   ``Without the coming out of a partner there is nothing more for
the initiaitve,'' Rabin said. ``Israel is going to stand on its
initiative.''
