<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Mengele     09-08 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Mengele,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mengele's Remains to be Sent to Germany for Genetic Exam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil will ship some of the bones of
Nazi war criminal Josef Mengele to West Germany to compare their
genetic code with that of Mengele's son, the head of Brazil's
federal police said Friday.
   Federal Police Chief Romeu Tuma said four teeth, three ribs and
several other bones taken from Mengele's remains would be submitted
to a deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) test in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   The genetic code contained in the DNA ``will be compared to that
of Mengele's son Rolf, who has agreed to submit himself to the test
by donating some of his blood,'' Tuma said.
   Tuma, who was to fly to Germany on Saturday with the bones, said
the DNA test was requested by Frankfurt's district attorney. The
test is considered positive proof of identity.
   Tuma said the test would confirm once and for all that the bones
are those of the infamous ``Angel of Death'' of the Auschwitz death
camp in Poland where hundreds of thousands of prisoners were killed
during World War II.
   ``That should put to rest any lingering doubts that anyone may
have that the remains are Mengele's,'' the police chief said.
   He said he did not know when the test would be completed.
   Mengele's remains were dug up on June 6, 1985, from a grave in
the cemetery at Embu, 17 miles from Sao Paulo.
   Witnesses said Mengele lived in Brazil for 18 years and drowned
on Feb. 7, 1979, while swimming at a beach resort near Sao Paulo.
   On June 21, 1985, an international forensic team concluded the
unearthed skeleton was Mengele's ``within a reasonable scientific
certainty.''
   On March 27, 1986, after Mengele's dental X-rays were discovered
in Sao Paulo, U.S. forensic scientist Lowell Levine said the remains
``may now be identified as belonging to Josef Mengele with absolute
certainty.''
   The bones have been kept at the Sao Paulo morgue since being
removed from the grave.
</TEXT>
