<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs     09-08 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett ``Agrees With Sentiment'' About Forcing Down Drug Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National drug policy director William Bennett
responded ``I agree with the sentiment'' when a senator told him
Friday that law enforcement officials should have the authority to
use force to bring down drug-carrying planes.
   Bennett, testifying before a Senate committee, also restated the
Bush administration's position that there are no plans to send U.S.
fighting troops to Colombia to fight the cocaine cartel and said
that was unlikely to change.
   He said that if there were a request from Colombia for U.S.
forces it would have to be considered but it appears unlikely that
will happen because Colombian President Virgilio Barco does not want
foreign fighting troops in his country.
   If there were a change in policy, the decision would be made by
President Bush in consultation with Congress, Bennett said in his
second day of appearances before lawmakers to promote the anti-drug
proposals Bush unveiled Tuesday.
   At one point in the hearing, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
provided a videotape of an airplane with packages being dumped out
of it. He said federal officials had identified it as air delivery
of cocaine from South America.
   McConnell said that demonstrated the need for legislation he has
sponsored to provide American law enforcement officials with
authority to use force as a last resort to bring down such aircraft.
   ``I agree with the sentiment expressed, Senator,'' Bennett said.
   ``It is analogous to, not identical to, but analogous to, it
seems to me, the authority we give a police officer in the inner
city in this country to stop someone from speeding away in a
four-by-four,'' Bennett said.
   ``Unless we are going to engage in some kind of class
discrimination, I don't know why the airplane is not subject to some
kind of rules as well as the recently purchased four-by-four in
southeast Washington,'' he said.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., told Bennett that if such a plane were
discovered and could not be stopped any other way, then as a last
resort, ``I think we should blow it out of the air.''
   Meanwhile, after Sen. John Kerry brought up the issue, the
Internal Revenue Service confirmed that there have been recent cuts
in a Miami-based program, ``Operation Greenback,'' designed to
ferret out money laundering by narcotics traffickers.
   Kerry, D-Mass., said he was disturbed by reports of a scaling
back in the program, operated by the IRS and the Justice Department.
``I have heard of it,'' said Bruce Karnes, an aide to Bennett. But
he said he had no details.
   ``Apparently there have been some cutbacks,'' Internal Revenue
Service spokesman John Hanlon said. He said details of the operation
would not be available immediately.
   As for sending troops to Colombia, Bennett said in response to
questions from Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., ``There is no thinking of
such actions at this time.''
   His comments to the Senate Foreign Relations Committee were in
line with earlier statements from the White House that the
possibility of such a move was remote.
   He said there was no certainty that military advisers, if sent,
would be able to stay clear of hostilities.
   Bennett also told senators the administration is looking at the
idea of a multinational strike force to combat drugs.
   Kerry asked why such a unit was not part of the drug-fighting
strategy made public by Bush. Bennett said it remained unclear that
the idea was a good one.
   ``Barco as you know doesn't want an American strike force,'' he
said. ``He doesn't want an international strike force. He doesn't
want any kind of strike force.''
   Bennett expanded on his testimony of Thursday that Colombian
cartel leaders will not face the death penalty if extradited here
and convicted of capital crimes. He said that was because the U.S.
extradition agreement with Colombia provides that those sent here
for trial will get no harsher penalty that the maximum sentence in
that nation, which is 30 years in prison.
   ``If the choices are no extradition to the United States or 30
years, then I think we should go with 30 years,'' Bennett said.
   He said he would like to change the extradition agreement to
remove the restriction against use of the death penalty.
</TEXT>
