<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1822EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Cambodia     09-08 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Calls on Moscow, Beijing To Show Restraint in Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 11 p.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top State Department official called on China
Friday to take steps that will prevent the Khmer Rouge rebels from
ever imposing it ``murderous rule'' on Cambodia again.
   Richard Solomon, the assistant secretary of state for East Asian
affairs, also said the Soviet Union must restrict its military aid
to Cambodia and use its influence to promote genuine national
reconciliation in that country.
   Solomon spoke to an international symposium on the future of
U.S.-Indochina relations in Los Angeles. Copies of his remarks were
made available by the State Department.
   Solomon rejected the argument of many analysts that the United
States should acquiesce in the continued rule of the
Vietnamese-backed Hun Sen government in Cambodia rather than press
for a comprehensive settlement among all contending factions.
   He called this approach ``seriously flawed'' on several counts.
   First, he said, ``a regime imposed and sustained by foreign force
of arms lacks legitimacy.''
   In addition, he said there is little basis for the assumption
that Hun Sen's unproven forces, absent their Vietnamese protectors
who are due to leave at the end of September, can eliminate the
Khmer Rouge. This, he said, is a goal that eluded Vietnam's powerful
army for a decade.
   Solomon said the United States has neither the political position
nor the resources to promote a peaceful settlement in Cambodia but
added that the same cannot be said for the Soviet Union and China.
   ``The Soviet Union, as the primary supporter of Vietnam and Hun
Sen, must restrict its increasing flow of arms into Cambodia, and
bring Hanoi to see that its own interests will not be served by
another cycle of warfare in Indochina _ which certainly will be the
case if it seeks full power for Hun Sen in the absence of a process
of political reconciliaiton,'' he said.
   ``In return, Hanoi and Hun Sen _ and the international community
_ have a right to expect China to equally restrict the supply of
arms to the Khmer Rouge.
   ``Indeed, Beijing has an obligation to take active measures that
will prevent the Khmer Rouge from again imposing a murderous rule on
the Cambodian people.''
   Solomon spoke against the background of a failed effort at an
international conference in Paris last month to achieve a political
settlement in Cambodia to coincide with the withdrawal of the
Vietnamese troops.
   He suggested that the key issue is whether the various Cambodian
factions can join together in a process of national reconciliation.
   He said the United States will use its influence to move events
in this direction and ``China and the Soviet Union must do the
same.''
   ``Moscow, in particular, must accept and act on the reality that
without some willingness by Vietnam and Hun Sen to compromise on
power-sharing, there can be no negotiated settlement, no respite
from armed conflict,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
