<FIRST>r w AM-Nofziger 1stLd-Writethru a0615 09-08 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nofziger, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Counsel Says He's Inclined To Seek High Court Review</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 5 grafs new with prosecutor saying he's inclined to seek
Supreme Court review; picks up 5th graf pvs, Edwards said; deletes now-outdated
last graf pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor said Friday he probably will seek
Supreme Court review of an appeals court ruling that overturned the
conviction of former White House political director Lyn Nofziger.
   All nine judges on the U.S. Court of Appeals this week rejected a
request by independent counsel James McKay for a rehearing of the
June 27 decision that set aside Nofziger's convictions for illegal
lobbying.
   Independent counsel James McKay said in a brief interview that
his office's ``present inclination'' is to ask the Supreme Court to
take the case.
   In its 2-1 opinion overturning Nofziger's conviction, the court
had said that for Nofziger to be found guilty of illegal lobbying,
prosecutors were required to prove he had known that what he was
doing was illegal.
   ``I think that the majority opinion in this case is clearly
wrong,'' appeals court judge Harry Edwards said in a statement
Tuesday with which three of his colleagues concurred.
   Edwards said, however, that the full appeals court wasn't the
proper place to hear the matter and that ``any further consideration
of this case must be'' by the Supreme Court. Concurring with Edwards
were Chief Judge Patricia Wald, Abner Mikva and Ruth B. Ginsburg.
All four judges are Carter administration appointees.
   The other five judges currently on the appeals court are Laurence
Silberman, James Buckley, Stephen Williams, Douglas Ginsburg and
David Sentelle. All are Reagan administration appointees.
   Edwards was the dissenting vote in the June 27 decision and said
at that time that his colleagues had twisted the meaning of the
Ethics in Government Act under which Nofziger was convicted.
   Nofziger was convicted on Feb. 11, 1988, of illegally lobbying
the White House on behalf of scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp., a
maritime workers union and Fairchild Corp. He lobbied for an Army
engine contract for Wedtech, for the placement of civilian sailors
on Navy vessels and for continued Air Force buying of an anti-tank
aircraft made by Fairchild.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
