<FIRST>u w AM-Baker-StarWars     09-08 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Star Wars,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Differs With Quayle On SDI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Friday that the goals of the Strategic Defense Initiative are sound
and should not be scaled back.
   His views were contained in a State Department statement issued
after a reporter's question prompted by a published interview with
Vice President Dan Quayle in which he said that then-President
Reagan, in making his original sales pitch for the ``Star Wars''
program in 1983, had resorted to ``political jargon'' and had
stretched ``the capability'' of the proposal.
   Baker, in the State Department statement, quoted President Bush
as saying:
   ``We are vigorouly pursuing SDI. Our goals for SDI and our
approach in the defense and space talks are sound and remain
unchanged.''
   Baker said the Soviets should understand ``our insistence on
investigating fully the feasibility of advanced strategic defenses.''
   Hours after the Quayle inteview, Bush's spokesman, Marlin
Fitzwater, said that Bush and Quayle were in step on SDI and that
Bush still has not given up the plan's goal of perfecting a space
shield against all incoming nuclear missiles.
   In the published interview, Quayle said Reagan had ``talked about
this impenetrable shield that was going to be completely leakproof.
   ``I believe that in the semantics of, let's say, political jargon
that that was acceptable. But it clearly was stretching the
capability of a strategic defense system.''
   Under Bush, Quayle said, the program has been ``redefined and put
into missions, requirements, doctrine and strategy much differently
than we did in the early 1980s.''
   Now, he said in the interview, the emphasis is on a program to
help protect the United States against the accidental launch of a
limited number of nuclear missiles, ``rather than an all-out,
bolt-out-of-the-blue attack.''
   The issue of arms control and the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty
of 1972, which banned most anti-missile defenses, are likely topics
for discussion when Baker meets with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze in Jackson Hole, Wyo., Sept. 22-23.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
