<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     09-08 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Claim to Close In on Border Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas said Friday they had
captured four security posts and three tanks in an advance on the
government-held garrison town of Khost, near the Pakistan border.
   The reports contradicted the Afghan government, which said
Thursday the Moslem guerrillas had lost a two-week fight to take
Khost.
   A spokesman for guerrilla commander Jalaluddin Haqqani, who is
reported to lead 3,000 of the U.S.-supported guerrillas, said
Thursday they had Khost and were within three miles of it.
   The guerrilla news agency MIDIA said the mujahedeen, as the
guerrillas are called, destroyed a Soviet-made Antonov-26 transport
plane in a rocket attack on the Khost's airport Wednesday.
   ``The Kabul regime can only supply by air,'' it said. ``All roads
leading to Khost have been cut off.''
   Haqqani's spokesman, who known only as Mohed, said: ``Fifteen
soldiers surrendered and handed over some heavy guns'' on Thursday.
``Three mujahedeen were killed and 14 were wounded, but we don't
know how many regime troops were killed.''
   He said the guerrillas captured three tanks as they overran four
posts, which he identified as Walim, Ghubao, Mirbao and Bak.
   There is no way to verify the contradictory claims often made by
Afghan officials and insurgents in the 11-year-old civil war.
   Lt. Gen. Abdul Haq Ulumi, secretary of the Soviet-backed
government's Supreme Defense Council, told reporters Thursday the
army had retaken all the positions it had lost since the guerrillas
began their Khost offensive Aug. 24 and the battle was ``completely
over.''
   The town in Paktia province is the government's easternmost
garrison, 12 miles from the Pakistan, where most of the guerrillas
are based. Its capture would clear the way for a guerrilla assault
on the provincial capital Gardez, 48 miles to the northwest.
   The guerrillas have not captured a city since the Soviet Union
withdrew its military forces Feb. 15 after nine years of involvement
in the war.
</TEXT>
