<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Lebanon     09-08 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Lebanon,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraqi Says Only Force Will Make Syria Leave Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iraqi official was quoted Friday
as saying the United States was providing cover for Syrian attempts
to partition Lebanon and only force would make the Syrians withdraw
from their war-racked neighbor.
   The London-based newsletter Mideast Mirror quoted First Deputy
Premier Taha Yassin Ramadan of Iraq as saying in an interview that
during Iraq's 8-year war with Iran ``Israel was in the background
and America providing cover.''
   ``The same thing is happening in Lebanon, where the leading role
is being played by Syria and Israel, but the American cover is much
clearer and more candid than it was in the war with Iraq.
   ``In Iraq, the aim was to partition the country, and in Lebanon
they have the same goal.''
   Ramadan was interviewed Thursday in Belgrade at the summit
conference of non-aligned nations. A copy was telexed to The
Associated Press in Bahrain.
   Lebanon has been torn by 14 years of civil war.
   Iraq has backed Gen. Michel Aoun in recent fighting in Lebanon
between his Christian forces and Moslem militias backed by Syria.
The Christian army is also fighting the estimated 40,000 troops
Syria has in Lebanon.
   Iraq and Syria are bitter political foes ruled by rival wings of
the Baath Party. Syria backed Iran in the Iran-Iraq war, which was
halted by a cease-fire in August 1988.
   The newsletter quoted Ramadan as saying: ``We in Iraq say that
neither an Arab resolution nor an international resolution will get
Hafez Assad out of Lebanon. Only force can get him out, crawling on
his knees.''
   Assad is the president of Syria.
   Ramadan was quoted as saying Iraq supported peacemaking efforts
in Lebanon by an Arab League committee, but doubted it would make
headway in ending the war since Syria refused to agree to a
timetable for withdrawing its troops.
   ``Let them try. We are confident that Hafez Assad will not leave
Lebanon as a result of a resolution. He merely wants to play for
time.''
   The foreign ministers of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria are to
meet in Jiddah, Saudi Arabia, next Wednesday. They will appraise the
chances of their three leaders' trying once more to end the fighting
in Lebanon and outline a plan for national reconciliation to avert
the threat of partition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
