<DOCNO> AP890908-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Economy     09-08 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Economy,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Government Campaigns For Public Ownership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Economic Daily newspaper denounced
former party chief Zhao Ziyang on Friday for encouraging a market
economy and emphasized that China will not abandon the communist
system of public ownership.
   On the same subject, hard-line Premier Li Peng stressed Friday
that public ownership always will dominate China's economy. But Li
said private entrepreneurs will continue to supplement the
public-owned economy and provide jobs.
   A commentary in the Economic Daily said Zhao put too much
emphasis on privatization.
   It said some Chinese supporters of Western ideas gradually are
trying to convert China's economic structure to capitalism.
   They aim to ``disintegrate public ownership, pushing
privatization to be a major aspect of China's economy step by step
until the whole economy is privatized,'' the article said.
   Zhao advocated gradually reducing state controls over the economy
and encouraged private enterprise. He was ousted after the June
military crackdown on a pro-democracy movement, .
   Zhao also backed agricultural reforms allowing families to
contract land and sell crops on the free market after fulfilling
state quotas for grain.
   Farmers also have been free to start their own businesses.
   Rapid growth of private enterprise has produced a moneyed class
and increased income gaps.
   The latest issue of the weekly magazine Beijing Review said
private ownership would polarize the rich and the poor ``while the
overwhelming majority of people would again be plunged into the
plight of being exploited and oppressed.''
   The Economic Daily and China Daily approved of capitalism's
advanced management systems, but denounced such elements as
exploitation of workers and unequal distribution of wealth.
   Capitalists are more interested in profiteering than adjusting
production to economic laws, they said.
   Public ownership supporters argue that collectivism can integrate
market demand with centralized plans, respond to consumer needs,
improve production quality and enable the government to regulate the
economy.
   The Beijing Review cited the 100,000-worker Capital Iron and
Steel Co. as a successful example of a large state-run enterprise
because it registered 20 percent increases in annual profits and tax
payments in recent years.
   Chinese economists have stressed no campaign will be undertaken
against the nation's 19.4 million private entrepreneurs, although
officials have announced stronger measures to combat tax evasion and
illegal selling practices.
   China Daily in July said privatization would cause a widening gap
in different regions and that surplus labor has become a serious
social problem.
   Millions of migrant workers have descended on southern Canton and
other urban centers, hoping for jobs but ending up straining social
facilities.
</TEXT>
