<FIRST>u w AM-DrugTesting     09-08 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Testing,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds DOT Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Friday upheld the
Transportation Department's random, mandatory drug testing program
covering 30,000 employees, including air traffic controllers.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia said in a unanimous opinion the ``extraordinary
... sensitivity of the bulk'' of the employees in the program
justifies ``the invasions of privacy entailed by conducting'' random
drug testing.
   The American Federation of Government Employees had appealed a
U.S. District Court dismissal of its court challenge to the program.
   The union had filed suit in an attempt to block testing not based
on suspicion of drug use, saying such a practice violated the
prohibitions of the Fourth and Fifth Amendments against searches
without probable cause and self-incrimination.
   The union attacked drug testing of motor vehicle operators,
hazardous material inspectors and aircraft mechanics at the Federal
Aviation Administration, appeals court judge David Sentelle noted.
   All three job categories should be included because of their
importance to public safety.
   ``We have found the privacy interests of employees occupying the
three specifically challenged positions outweighed by the
Department's compelling interests in preventing drug use among such
personnel,'' said the judges.
   The FAA's 12,000 air traffic controllers belong to a different
union, the National Air Traffic Controllers Association, and were
not a party to the case.
   Also subject to the random drug testing are electronic
technicians, aviation and railroad safety inspectors and civil
aviation security specialists.
   The appeals court decision ``represents a great victory for the
department,'' Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said in a
statement. The public ``expects and deserves a drug-free and safe
transportation system,'' Skinner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
