<FIRST>u a AM-RapeOrdeal     09-08 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape Ordeal,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rape Victim Describes Ordeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was raped, slashed and left to die in
her burning home with her head swathed in tape says she snatched a
knife from her assailant and lunged at him, screaming, ``I want to
live! I've got two babies!''
   The woman, whose next-door neighbor was arrested in the attack
after she wrote his name in her own blood, described her ordeal in a
telephone interview with The Denver Post from her Denver General
Hospital room.
   The attack occurred Wednesday in the woman's home in a
middle-class neighborhood of northeast Denver. She was tied up,
beaten and left in a basement crawlspace and her home was set
ablaze, but she managed to escape.
   A neighbor, Donnie Russell, 18, was arrested Thursday in Oklahoma
City and faces extradition to Colorado.
   The 30-year-old victim described her assailant as a ``nice, quiet
kid'' who once baby-sat her children and often spent time with her
husband waxing cars.
   The victim said the ordeal began when her assailant asked to use
her telephone Wednesday morning.
   After making a call, he allegedly pulled out a handgun, pointed
it at her and demanded all her money and jewelry.
   ``I kept saying, `Oh, come on,' and thought he was kidding,'' the
woman told The Post. ``Then he put the gun to my head and I knew he
wasn't playing.''
   The woman gave him all her cash _ $3 _ and a credit card.
   She said the little cash angered him and he wrapped her head in
duct tape, leaving only her nose exposed.
   ``I'm going to kill you,'' she remembered him repeating.
   The assailant then guided her into the basement, raped her and
pushed her into a dark crawl space.
   ``I waited until it was quiet,'' she said. ``When it was, I
thought he was gone. I couldn't get the tape off. I couldn't find
the end. So I couldn't see.''
   She said she felt her way to the crawlspace entrance and realized
the man was standing just a few feet away. He hit her on the head
with a hammer, and she collapsed and played dead.
   ``That's when he slashed my arms and legs with a knife. I guess
he thought I would bleed to death,'' she said. ``I acted like I was
out cold.
   ``He came back five minutes later, and put the knife on my chest.
It was like he was trying to find where my heart was.''
   She said she snatched the knife away from the man, telling him,
``I'm going to kill you,'' and swinging the knife blindly.
   ``He kept on saying, `Give me the knife.'
   ``I said, `No, I want to live! I've got two babies!''
   The attacker closed the door to the crawlspace and barricaded it
with furniture. She said she also heard him set a couch on fire just
outside the door.
   The woman said cut the tape away from her eyes and ripped her
shirt to shreds to stop the bleeding from knife wounds on her arms,
legs and hands, while choking on the smoke from the fire.
   ``When I was lying on the ground, I just figured I was going to
die whether I wanted to or not, but I thought he's not going to get
out of this scot-free.''
   She wrote ``Donnie next door'' with her blood-smeared finger on
the floor, the wall and on a cardboard box.
   Then, she put her shoulder to the door, wedging it open far
enough to squeeze out.
   She used the knife to break a basement window, climbed out and
scaled a 6-foot fence. A neighbor called police and firefighters.
   The woman underwent surgery for severed tendons in her hand. She
said she has regained the use of some fingers and the prognosis for
her recovery is good.
   ``But I feel safe in here,'' she said. ``I don't think I'd ever
want to go back to the neighborhood.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
