<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NationalService     09-08 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-National Service,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friedman Attacks Bush's National Service Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative economist Milton Friedman on
Friday attacked President Bush's ``thousand points of light'' idea
of national service as ``utterly unnecessary'' and compared it to
one of Adolf Hitler's programs.
   The Nobel Prize-winning economist, in an interview before a forum
of scholars and politicians at the Hoover Institution at Stanford
University, said the idea of universal national service is ``more
wasteful government spending.''
   Friedman said Bush's proposal and several other bills introduced
in Congress this year are smaller versions of universal national
service plans that have been suggested before and which he claimed
bear an ``uncanny resemblance'' to the Hitler youth corps.
   ``Strictly voluntary programs, like the Red Cross or Boy Scouts,
are splendid, but these national service proposals aren't voluntary
as far as the people paying for it,'' Friedman said.
   Rep. Dave McCurdy, D-Okla., chief sponsor in the House of the
Nunn-McCurdy plan for national service, defended the concept of
young Americans devoting time to working for others.
   ``The proposal is based on the premise that our young people must
move beyond the decade of `me first' attitudes of the Reagan era and
the lingering aftereffects of Vietnam, which led many to ask what
their country could do for them,'' McCurdy said.
   The Nunn-McCurdy plan, which seeks to make federal aid for
college students conditional on national service in the military or
in civilian work programs, is among several national service bills
introduced in Congress this year.
   Friedman said the president is proposing a much more modest
program than Nunn and McCurdy, but said, ``I still think it's a
misguided proposal. The fact that you do something bad on a small
scale doesn't make it good.''
   President Bush proposed creating an agency called Youth Engaged
in Service to America and has set up an Office of National Service
in the White House with 14 full-time staffers. Bush proposed funding
that office with $25 million a year for the next four years, and
hopes to match that amount with private funds.
   Bush also has called for a Points of Light Initiative Foundation
and named New Jersey Gov. Tom Kean to head a committee to advise on
how the foundation should be set up.
   ``The president hopes all Americans and all American institutions
will become involved with some kind of community service,'' said
Tracey Taylor, staff assistant for the Office of National Service at
the White House.
   Williamson Evers, a national fellow at Hoover and conference
chairman, said the two-day forum is meant ``to air and thrash out
the issues.''
   Among the other speakers were former Rep. Pete McCloskey,
R.-Calif., Lutheran theologian Richard John Neuhas, political
scientist Benjamin Barber, and Cato Institute senior fellow and
former Reagan administration adviser Doug Bandow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
