<FIRST>u i AM-India-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0632 09-08 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Says Indian Troops Will Be Withdrawn From Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with Gandhi quotes. Picks up
graf 5 pvs, `The government ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi on Friday
said his government has reached agreement with Sri Lanka to withdraw
42,000 Indian soldiers sent to that island nation to end ethnic
violence.
   The accord was reached with Sri Lankan officials during this
week's meeting of non-aligned nations in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, Press
Trust of India reported.
   The news agency quoted Gandhi as saying the accord is a ``good
agreement'' covering all aspects of the withdrawal of Indian troops
in northeast Sri Lanka.
   India has withdrawn about 3,000 troops since June 29 following
appeals by Sri Lankan President Ranasinghe Premadasa. Gandhi
initially rejected Premadasa's demands for a troop pullout, saying a
rapid withdrawal would worsen the ethnic violence.
   A clash was averted when India agreed to a token withdrawal June
29, but the countries had failed to agree on a timetable for a
complete pullout. Gandhi did not elaborate on what had been
negotiated.
   ``Sri Lankan officials have gone back to Colombo with the points
of agreement for consultation with President Ranasinghe Premadasa,''
Gandhi was quoted as saying by United News of India.
   ``India and Sri Lanka agreed on major issues,'' he said without
elaborating, UNI reported.
   The government says 17,000 people have been killed in a
secessionist war by Tamil rebels and a backlash by Sinhalese
radicals protesting the government's peace overtures to the Tamils.
   India deployed its first troops in Sri Lanka on June 30, 1987, to
disarm Tamil rebels who had agreed to surrender under an
Indian-brokered peace accord. But the domimant rebel group, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, reneged and began attacking Indian
soldiers.
   More troops were sent as the fighting escalated. Premadasa asked
for a withdrawal to appease Sinhalese radicals after the Tigers
agreed to peace talks.
   Extremist Sinhalese launched a campaign of assassinations and
terror to protest the Indian presence, which they say compromises
Sri Lanka's sovereignty.
   India got involved because of pressures from its own Tamil
minority.
   Authorities in Sri Lanka said Friday that 19 people had died in
ethnic violence since Wednesday.
   Cpl. Tissa Rupasinghe opened fire on his fellow soldiers Thursday
night while they slept at the Deraniyagala camp, 35 miles east of
Colombo, said the officials.
   They said three soldiers were killed and two injured in the
attack and the 26-year-old corporal fled with an automatic rifle.
   They said the soldier was suspected of being a member of the
People's Liberation Front, an anti-government guerrilla group trying
to overthrow the government.
   Officials blamed the Sinhalese militants for most of the other 16
deaths reported.
   They said the victims included a government official, who was not
identified, and four children who died when a bomb exploded in a
house in Diganhena village, about 85 miles south of Colombo.
   They said one of the victims, a 16-year-old, was suspected of
being a member of the People's Liberation Front and had brought the
bomb home when it accidentally went off.
</TEXT>
