<FIRST>u i AM-Armenia-Earthquake     09-08 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armenia-Earthquake,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Rattles Soviet Armenia, No Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An early morning earthquake Friday rattled the
Armenian cities that were wrecked in December by a quake that killed
25,000 people.
   Authorities reported no injuries or damage to buildings from the
quake, which was centered between Spitak and Kirovakan.
   ``This is an area where there is nothing left to destroy,'' said
an editor of Armenia's official Armenpress news agency in a
telephone interview.
   She said the quake, which registered six on the 12-point Soviet
scale, was followed 40 minutes later by a quake that registered four.
   The tremors were not felt in the Armenian capital, Yerevan, 45
miles to the south, said the editor who would not identify herself.
   On the 12-point Soviet scale, a quake of six is considered
strong, capable of shaking pictures from walls and damaging
buildings.
   The earthquake that completely destroyed Spitak and heavily
damaged Kirovakan and Leninakan was estimated to have a force of at
least 10 on the Soviet scale.
