<FIRST>u w AM-Reagan-Treatment 2ndLd-Writethru a0726 09-08 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Treatment, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0726,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Say Such Procedures `Routine,' Usually With Full Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to include fact surgery completed, details
of procedure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The surgery that removed a small puddle of old
blood from the brain cavity of former President Reagan was among the
simplest of the procedures that could have been used according to
surgeons familiar with brain operations.
   A spokesman for the former president said doctors at St. Marys
Hospital removed a subdural hematoma after drilling a single burr
hole in Reagan's skull.
   Dr. Henry Brem, an associate professor of neurosurgery at Johns
Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, said before the surgery that if
doctors in the course of the procedure were able to find and drain
the fluid from a single hole then the operation could be
accomplished quickly and easily.
   He said that typically the patient would be placed under general
or local anesthestia and that an incision would be made through the
scalp to the skull. Then a hole would be drilled, giving surgeons a
view of the dura, a tough membrane that covers the brain.
   ``They'll open up the dura and let the fluid out and that would
be the end of it,'' the surgeon predicted just hours before the
operation. Based on a statement released by Reagan's spokesman,
that, apparently, is what happened.
   Brem was not involved in the care and treatment of Reagan, but
did describe how such surgery is accomplished on most patients.
   ``He should do extremely well,'' he said. ``Patients usually do
beautifully in something like this.''
   Doctors at the Mayo Clinic discovered the subdural hematoma
during a routine examination of the 78-year-old former president.
They attributed the collection of fluid on the top, right side of
the brain to a riding accident last July. Reagan was visiting a
ranch in Mexico when a bucking horse threw him to the ground. He was
examined at an Army hospital, but declined to remain overnight after
treatment for bruises and scrapes. The following day, Reagan was
reported to be sore, but in excellent condition.
   Brem said that a collection of fluid in the brain cavity is
``plausible'' after such an accident, even though there was no
obvious head injury.
   Dr. Edward Laws, chairman of neurosurgery at George Washington
University Hospital in Washington, said it would not be surprising
if the jolt from a fall, particularly with an elderly person, would
cause a collection of fluid on the brain.
   ``This is usually because a little blood vessel gets torn and
causes some blood to leak into the space over the surface of the
brain,'' he said. ``As it dissolves, it collects more fluid and
expands.''
   He said it is common practice to remove such fluid collections,
even if they are causing no problems.
   ``They usually continue to enlarge and could ultimately cause
symptoms,'' said Laws. He called the surgical procedure ``routine.''
   Laws said that when blood leaks in the brain cavity it can remain
there and slowly change from a bright red to a black or even yellow
fluid.
   If left untreated, the fluid pool could cause further bleeding
and pressure, which could begin to damage brain cells.
   Neither Brem nor Laws personally knew any details of the Reagan's
medical treatment, and they could not be reached for comment after
the former president's surgery.
   Earlier, Laws, who once worked at Mayo, predicted that the
simplest procedure possible would be used.
   ``My guess is that they will just make a couple of small openings
in the skull and allow the fluid to drain out,'' he said before the
operation. ``That'll take about an hour and a half.''
   According to the spokesman's statement, the surgeons actually
used only one drill hole and completed the procedure ``without
complications'' in just over an hour.
   The statement said ``no further treatment is anticipated,''
suggesting, as Laws had predicted before the operation, that Reagan
``should be good as new.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890908-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0750 09-08 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0750,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearings Begin on Solidarity-led Government's Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with foreign minister-nominee's
remarks, details. Picks up praf 15 pvs, `Skubiszewski is ...' Minor editing
thereafter to trim and conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki's nominee
for foreign minister told a hearing committee Friday that Poles
forced to remain in the Soviet Union after World War II should be
able to return, the government news agency PAP said.
   Two other Cabinet nominees were rejected but most nominees were
approved on the first day of hearings of a Solidarity-led government
that will end four decades of communist control of foreign affairs,
the news media and economy.
   Eight committees of the Sejm, or lower house of parliament, held
hearings all day. Further sessions were planned through the weekend
to get ready for the vote Tuesday on Mazowiecki's proposed
government.
   PAP said that Krzysztof Skubiszewski, a little-known independent
named to be foreign minister, said Poland's foreign policy must not
depend on any one political party, and also that it was necessary to
make possible the return of Poles kept in the Soviet Union after the
war.
   He made the remarks to the committee responsible for contacts
with Poles living abroad, which along with the Foreign Affairs
Committee approved his nomination, PAP said.
   PAP said Mazowiecki, elected Aug. 24, nominated 19 people
Thursday and four Friday. Mazowiecki is expected to outline his
government's program in a speech Tuesday. He also plans on having a
final list of nominees then.
   It appeared Solidarity would control 13 posts, including prime
minister, on the 24-member Council of Ministers, or Cabinet.
   The Communist Party would have four, the United Peasant Party
four and the Democratic Party three.
   But government and legislative sources said more posts could be
added.
   Late Friday, the parliamentary commission for food and
agriculture voted against the nominations of Czeslaw Janicki of the
Peasant Party and of Artur Balazs of Solidarity, television news
said.
   Janicki, an agriculture professor, was nominated for the combined
post of deputy prime minister and agriculture and Balazs as minister
without portfolio for rural and civic issues.
   TV said voting was secret and gave no reasons for the rejections.
   But a Peasant Party statement had supported Kazimierz Olesiak,
the incumbent agriculture minister and a Peasant Party leader.
Balazs' nomination involved a power struggle between Rural
Solidarity and the Peasant Party.
   The committee votes do not oblige Mazowiecki to withdraw
candidates.
   Besides not getting the Foreign Ministry, the Communist Party was
denied the powerful post of chairman of the radio-TV committee. That
will go to a Solidarity supporter not been named.
   Skubiszewski, an adviser to Roman Catholic church leader Cardinal
Jozef Glemp, was considered a compromise between Solidarity and the
Communists, both of whom wanted the post.
   The pro-Solidarity daily Gazeta Wyborcza called Skubiszewski a
neutral, but Mazowiecki was overheard telling lawmakers the nominee
had been a Solidarity member.
   Skubiszewski told the hearing any disputes between Poland and its
Warsaw Pact neighbors had to be solved peacefully and relations
among pact countries must be based on mutual obligations.
   Among the candidates questioned Friday were:
   Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, Mazowiecki's predecessor and candidate to
remain head of the Interior Ministry and a deputy prime minister.
Solidarity activist Jacek Kuron, the minister of labor nominee.
Aleksander Bentkowski, the Peasant Party parliamentary floor leader
nominated to head the Justice Ministry.
   Leszek Balcerowicz, a Solidarity candidate for deputy prime
minister and nominee for the Finance Ministry.
   The delay in providing the list caused confusion as the Communist
Party newspaper Trybuna Ludu, Gazeta Wyborcza and PAP all published
different lists.
   According to PAP, Solidarity will run six government ministries
and Solidarity members were nominated to five other cabinet-rank
positions.
   Jerzy Osiatynski, a Solidarity legislator nominated as head of
the Central Planning Office, and Balazs joined nine other Solidarity
members nominated Thursday.
   That list gives Solidarity 12 votes on the Council of Ministers,
counting Mazowiecki. If Skubiszewski votes with Solidarity, as seems
likely in crucial matters, Solidarity would command a 13-11 edge on
the council.
   Only one woman was among the nominees _ Soliarity's Izabella
Cywinska, a theater director, as culture minister.
   The Communists' Polish United Workers Party, which had directed
the government since 1948, has received nominees for four ministries.
   Besides Kiszczak, Minister of Defense Gen. Florian Siwicki would
retain his job and Communists would receive the Transportation
Ministry and Foreign Trade Ministry.
   Several nominees have been victims of government repression.
Kuron spent nine years in jail and Henryk Samsonowicz, the nominee
for minister of education, was fired as Warsaw University rector
because of his Solidarity sympathies.
   As soon as it is approved the government will face an economy
ravaged by inflation, a chronic shortage of basic goods, low
productivity and a foreign debt of $39 billion.
</TEXT>
