<FIRST>r a AM-RamblingRabbit 1stLd-Writethru a0623 09-08 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rambling Rabbit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stolen Wooden Rabbit Returns Home With Photos Of Cross Country Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Schmoke did ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
comment by Schmoke's press secretary; picks up 11th graf, `In one ...'
ADDS 3 grafs with background on kidnapped lawn dwarf; no pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves with a penchant for travel recently
returned a wooden rabbit used as lawn ornament along with 48 photos
showing the rambling rabbit in such far-off locales as Reno, Nev.,
and the Virgin Islands.
   The rabbit was taken last December from the lawn of Harry and
Louise West's Reistertown home. It reappeared in August, propped on
the windshield of the couple's car next to a bag of photographs.
   ``There are all kinds of pictures. One where he's building a sand
castle. One where he's looking at the bus station. One at the
airport,'' said Louise West, 68. ``It was gone about a year and just
about two weeks ago my husband went out to get the Sunday paper and
it was sitting on the car.''
   ``We were angry for a while, but then we just forgot about the
missing rabbit,'' said West, 67. ``The rabbit really got around in
those eight months and even had been given a name by its
kidnappers.''
   Mrs. West said the location where the photograph was take was
written on the back of each picture and the initials S.B.R. _
presumably for Stolen Bunny Rabbit _ were written in the margin of
one.
   The rabbit went west to Utah, Kansas City, Mo., and Reno, then
back east to sample the big-city life of New York, Philadelphia and
Atlantic City, N.J.
   Photographs were also taken at the Wright Brother's Museum in
Kitty Hawk, N.C., Florida's Disney World, Annapolis, Md., Bermuda,
and St. Thomas.
   The well-traveled hare was even photographed with Baltimore Mayor
Kurt Schmoke, who is shown holding it in his right hand.
   ``How in the world the person got the mayor to pose with the
rabbit, I can't imagine,'' West told the Carroll County Times.
   But Schmoke never saw or touched the rabbit, his press secretary,
Clinton Coleman, said Friday.
   ``The mayor has never seen the rabbit. He's never held onto that
rabbit before,'' Coleman said. ``Apparently it's somebody's idea of
a joke.''
   In one photograph a woman wearing sunglasses is holding the
rabbit, but Mrs. West said she did not recognize her.
   ``Two of them are a photograph with a girl in it and another is a
scuba diver, a girl,'' Mrs. West said. ``But we don't know who did
it really. ... It's not anybody that I recognize.''
   The rabbit's rambles were similar to the ``journey'' earlier this
year of Grumpy, one of seven lawn dwarfs, who disappeared from the
front of a Saugerties, N.Y., couple's home on March 16.
   The 80-pound lawn ornament returned April 26, with an
accompanying envelope containing 35 photographs of his travels,
which included visits to New York's Yankee Stadium, Colorado, the
Carolinas, Texas and St. Louis.
   A sign dangling from Grumpy's shoulders said, ``I'm home.''
</TEXT>
