<FIRST>u a AM-HurricaneGabrielle 1stLd-Writethru a0757 09-08 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane Gabrielle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0757,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weaker Gabrielle Pushes Toward Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to UPDATE with Gabrielle's 10:30 p.m. position.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gabrielle churned north toward Canada's
Maritime Provinces with 100-mph winds Friday after brushing by
Bermuda, and Tropical Storm Felix was expected to be gobbled up by
the bigger storm.
   Swells of 20 feet hit the eastern tip of Bermuda, causing damage
to a house Thursday as winds on the fringes of Gabrielle gusted to
35 mph, said the National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables.
   ``They were right on the edge of the hurricane so they really
didn't get very much, at least in terms of wind and rain,'' said
meteorologist Jack Beven, ``The seas and waves are something else
entirely.''
   Marine traffic was idled in Bermuda as the storm stirred up
10-foot swells even in harbors. Heavy surf from New England to
central Florida also was blamed on Gabrielle.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the center of Gabrielle, the second hurricane
of the season to approach Bermuda, was located near 37.8 north
latitude and 59.7 west longitude, or about 425 miles south of Sable
Island, Nova Scotia.
   ``The center is already east of the easternmost longitude of Nova
Scotia,'' which should keep hurricane-strength winds away from
Canada, Beven said. ``It may come closer to Newfoundland than Nova
Scotia, although at this time we're not predicting it to go over
either one.''
   The hurricane was moving north at 12 mph, but forecasters
expected a turn to the north-northeast in the next day.
   A gradual decrease in strength and forward speed is projected in
the next day or two. But Gabrielle, which peaked at 135 mph, should
keep hurricane-strength winds of at least 74 mph for at least three
days, Beven said.
   Meanwhile, Felix, which has rumbled around the Atlantic as both a
storm and a weak hurricane, was expected to rapidly weaken in the
next 12 to 24 hours as Gabrielle cuts into it.
   Felix also was expected to lose all tropical characteristics. The
hurricane center said it would issue no more advisories on the
system.
   At 6 p.m. EDT, Felix was located near 45 degrees north latitude
and 43 degrees west longitude, or about 500 miles east southeast of
Cape Race, Newfoundland, and moving to the northeast at 15 mph.
   Five hurricanes have formed in the current Atlantic hurricane
season, which began June 1 and lasts until Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
