<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki's Cabinet
nominees sailed through the first day of hearings Friday for the new
Solidarity-led government, which will break Communist control of
foreign affairs, media, and the economy.
   Eight committees of the Sejm, or lower house of parliament, held
hearings all day and further sessions were planned through the
weekend to prepare for a vote Tuesday on Mazowiecki's proposed
government.
   Mazowiecki, elected Aug. 24, is expected to outline his
government's program in a speech Tuesday.
   It appeared Solidarity would have 13 of the posts, counting
Mazowiecki, on the 26-member Council of Ministers, or Cabinet.
However, government and legislative sources have cautioned that the
list is not final.
