<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1748EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Contras-Prosperity Adv14   09-08 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contras-Prosperity, Adv 14,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs. Sept. 14, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Contras Bring Prosperity to Honduran Townspeople</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPIRE, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Hondurans in this isolated valley
where a Nicaraguan Contra army has been camped, the last
year-and-a-half has meant prosperity.
   ``Business is good. We'll sell it all,'' Krystela Rodriguez
exulted. She runs a shop crammed with everything from cologne and
shampoo to powdered fruit drinks and baby shoes.
   Perhaps most remarkable for her 10- by 20-foot shack 80 miles
from the nearest paved road is the refrigerator, which runs on
electricity from a diesel generator that also provides power for a
nearby Contra encampment.
   A cloud is on her horizon, however: the accord reached by Central
American leaders Aug. 7 calling for the Contra army to disband by
Dec. 8. She still has a lot of shampoo to sell and is concerned
about being overstocked.
   ``There's no future here after the Contras leave,'' said Vladimir
Valenzuela, who runs a bustling restaurant in Danli, 80 miles to the
west.
   Eastern Honduras has always been poor and sparsely populated. The
average agricultural worker earned 3 lempiras a day _ less than $1
at the black market exchange rate. Farms were few. Small ranchers
had no way to get their products to market.
   The Yamales area, which has no more than a few hundred residents
in normal times, was almost completely abandoned in the mid-1980s,
at the height of the Contra campaign to topple the Sandinista
government in Nicaragua.
   The Nicaraguan border is less than 10 miles away, and the
Sandinista army swept through more than once in search of Contras.
   But when thousands of Contra fighters began moving out of
Nicaragua after the United States cut off military aid early in
1988, the impact was immediate on Yamales.
   The United States has kept up non-lethal aid, Contra fighters and
their families began to find work, and there was a market for
practically everything.
   The people of eastern Honduras went to work.
   Las Trojes, 18 miles to the west, and Danli, 60 miles away,
became boomtowns where many fighters' relatives settled. Cheap
hotels and restaurants served truck drivers, and Las Trojes even had
a small casino with rudimentary versions of craps and roulette.
   ``A lot of them are doing real well. They've got a road now,''
noted Israel Galeano, the Contra chief of staff known as ``Commander
Franklin.''
   The Contras built and maintain the road in from Las Trojes. Now
more roads branch off that one. Many ranchers in the area are
building wood corrals to replace old barbed wire ones.
   ``The corral started getting too full and the animals starting
cutting themselves on the wire,'' said Mercedes Martinez. She and
her husband, Mario, have cattle and chickens and sell milk, meat and
eggs to the Contras.
   Nicaraguans have established small businesses and farms of their
own as well, especially in the roadless mountains that stretch 100
miles northeast along the Nicaragua-Honduras border to Bocay. Jungle
has been cleared for cattle or corn crops.
   Paula Zentena, whose husband is a Contra soldier, found she could
make money by altering U.S.-provided fatigue uniforms for the Contra
soldiers.
   ``They're usually too baggy for the boys,'' she said as she ran
off a seam on her new, treadle-powered sewing machine. She rents
space in a Honduran house and has two Nicaraguan fighters working
for her, charging 3 lempiras to alter a pair of pants.
   Balancio Blandon, a Honduran who started out with a small shop,
has been able to build a new, brick store and home for himself, his
wife and their five children. He also bought a Canon camera and now
runs a photo service.
   He doesn't see the boom coming to an end soon, especially with
U.S. aid continuing until February _ and probably longer for Contra
families and wounded fighters in the area.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs AMs, Sept. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
