<FIRST>a e BC-Emmys Adv00   09-08 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Emmys, Adv 00,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>Emmy Salutes TV's 50th Years With Look At Present and Past</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Emmy broadcast is Sept. 17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after they celebrated their 40th
birthday, the Emmy awards salute television's 50th anniversary
Sunday with an affectionate look at the past and honors for
present-day excellence.
   From Ralph Kramden to Heathcliff Huxtable, from Ed Sullivan to
Arsenio Hall, from ``The Growing Paynes'' to ``Growing Pains,'' the
41st Annual Emmy Awards will span the years.
   The Prime-Time Emmy show, to be televised live Sunday, Sept. 17
(8-11 p.m. EDT), from the Pasadena Civic Auditorium by Fox
Broadcasting Co., will also be notable for what it doesn't contain.
For the first time, no clips will be shown from nominated shows. And
it will have no production numbers _ no song medleys, no
high-kicking chorus line.
   The CBS miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' leads the nominations with
18. Other multiple nominations went to NBC's ``L.A. Law'' with 17,
the ABC miniseries ``War and Remembrance'' with 15, ABC's ``The
Wonder Years'' with 14, ABC's ``thirtysomething'' with 13, and NBC's
``The Golden Girls'' and Fox's ``The Tracey Ullman Show'' with 10
each.
   ``We're going to reach back and present some of the wonderful
images, memories, faces, pictures and words that we've forgotten or
that we remember well and want to see again,'' said John Moffitt,
co-executive producer with Pat Tourk Lee for the Academy of
Television Arts &amp; Sciences.
   ``Everyone seems to like the clips of the old shows. And everyone
complains about the production numbers. We'll be able to take a long
look at the past and still keep it to about three hours by
eliminating the numbers and the clips of the nominated shows.
Nobody'll miss those clips and it will speed up the show.''
   Lucille Ball, who died in April at age 77, will be posthumously
honored with the Governors Award. She will be remembered with a
five-to-seven-minute retrospective, including a clip from the pilot
of ``I Love Lucy.'' Bob Hope, her frequent co-star, will present the
award to her husband, Gary Morton.
   ``She was doing films when other people were doing live TV, so
there's an enormous record of her work,'' said Moffitt. ``We have
some shows that are fresh because they never went into syndication.
We want to run the clips pretty full so that we don't lose her
wonderful sense of timing.
   ``Her face was her greatest asset, but she could be outrageously
funny even when you couldn't see her face. There's one scene with
Richard Burton and Elizabeth Taylor in which you see only her arm
and it's very funny. We want to show her at her best when she's
entertaining people. It won't be maudlin or sentimental.''
   Instead of a production number, the Emmy show will open with a
comedy spot showing what the world would be like without television.
   ``We'll have a few surprises, too,'' said Moffitt, who with Lee
also produces ``Not Necessarily the News'' for Home Box Office.
   ``This is the year of the dramatization. It caused a controversy
on ABC News. We'll have our own dramatization of what could happen
if a winner isn't there to accept his award.''
   The clips will feature some fascinating duos: Ethel Merman and
Mary Martin, Frank Sinatra and Elvis Presley, Candice Bergen and
Groucho Marx, Judy Garland and Barbra Streisand, David Bowie and
Bing Crosby, and Flip Wilson and Ed Sullivan.
   There'll also be some unlikely couples on the stage. For
instance, Robert Reid and Florence Henderson of ``The Brady Bunch''
will get together with Ed O'Neill and Katey Sagal of ``Married ...
With Children'' to talk about changing attitudes in comedy.
   Robert Duvall of ``Lonesome Dove'' is a presenter; he is also
nominated as best lead actor in a miniseries or special, along with
co-star Tommy Lee Jones.
   Other presenters include Arsenio Hall, the hot new late-night
talk show host, teen-age heart throb Johnny Depp of Fox's ``21 Jump
Street'' and Fred Savage of ABC's ``The Wonder Years,'' at 12 the
youngest person ever nominated in a lead actor category.
   Announcers from the past will be represented by Andre Baruch of
``Your Hit Parade.'' He will be in an ``announcer competition'' with
Shadoe Stevens, host of a current program of top music favorites.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
