<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     09-08 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0886</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses plan to increase their plant and
equipment spending by 7.7 percent this year, the government said in
a report that analysts said shows no sign that industry fears an
imminent recession.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday that responses to a
survey completed last month show that businesses expect to spend
$463.95 billion on expansion and modernization this year despite
earlier concern about a significant economic slowdown.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An admitted penny stock scam artist, wearing a
hood to hide his features, has told a House subcommittee that penny
stocks traded over the counter are often controlled by organized
crime.
   Lorenzo Formato, a former penny stock broker and promoter now in
the federal Witness Protection Program, told the subcommittee on
telecommunications and finance Thursday that while there are
legitimate companies offering their stocks over-the-counter they are
often manipulated by brokers, promoters or salesmen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House economic adviser Michael J. Boskin
is reinforcing the Bush administration's call on the Federal Reserve
Board to lower interest rates.
   Boskin, chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers, told the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce on Thursday that ``if there are signs of
softness in the economy from where we are now, that further easing
would probably be appropriate,''
   His comments came three weeks after White House budget director
Richard Darman complained that the central bank was keeping interest
rates too high and would have to bear the blame if the country
toppled into a recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal Superfund program has
been ``superslow'' in cleaning toxic waste dumps and in making
polluters pay for the work, according to a study.
   In the program's first eight years ending last September, the
Environmental Protection Agency finished cleaning only 34 dumps out
of 1,175 on a priority list, according to the Rand Corp. study, to
be released Friday. The list represents only the worst of 30,000
dumps where waste ultimately may need to be treated or removed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. is selling the fresh fruit
operations of its Del Monte unit to the British conglomerate Polly
Peck International PLC for $875 million in another major step toward
reducing debt from its record buyout.
   The cash sale of Del Monte Tropical Fruit Co., announced
Thursday, moves RJR past the halfway mark in its efforts to sell
about $5.5 billion in assets to reduce the debt accumulated in the
$25 billion buyout of the food and tobacco giant by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co.
   Del Monte is the world's largest supplier of fresh pineapples and
No. 3 in bananas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate tax-writers, yielding to loud complaints
from many older Americans, are indicating they would join their
House counterparts and go along with major changes in Medicare
insurance covering the costs of a catastrophic illness.
   Several members of the Senate Finance Committee, however, on
Thursday rejected a revision approved by the House Ways and Means
Committee to cut costs for the higher-income elderly but raise them
for older people with lower incomes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Italy's largest bank has resigned
over a scandal involving unauthorized export credits to Iraq granted
by the Italian bank's branch in Atlanta, Ga.
   Nerio Nesi, chairman of the state-owned Banca Nazionale del
Lavoro (BNL), and the bank's director-general, Giacomo Pedde,
stepped down at an extraordinary meeting of the bank's board
Thursday night, the bank said in a statement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Donald Trump has received government
clearance to purchase more than $15 million of the jewelry firm
Tiffany &amp; Co.'s stock, a Trump spokeswoman said.
   Tiffany issued a news release Thursday in which Tiffany Chairman
William R. Chaney said Trump had advised him that a filing was made
to the government so that Trump might acquire and hold more than $15
million of Tiffany's stock ``as an investment and not as part of a
takeover effort.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas Attorney General's office has sued
the Quaker Oats Co. saying the nation's biggest seller of hot cereal
misled consumers in advertising that its product can help reduce the
risk of heart disease.
   But spokesmen for Chicago-based Quaker Oats said they feel the
advertising is truthful and is supported by valid scientific
evidence.
   In the lawsuit, filed Thursday on behalf of the Texas Department
of Health in a Dallas state district court, the state said Quaker
Oats' ads as ``replete with exaggerations, half-truths, and
misinformation.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices showed spotty declines after a modest early rally
failed to attract much support. The Dow Jones industrials average,
up about eight points in the early going, was down 12.91 at 2,706.88
by the close.
   The dollar rose against foreign currencies despite central bank
intervention.
   Bond prices were little changed in uneventful trading.
   Futures prices for frozen pork bellies soared the 2-cents-a-pound
daily limit on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. On other markets,
soybean futures posted strong gains while energy futures and
precious metals futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
