<FIRST>r f PM-MidwestMen Bjt   09-08 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midwest Men, Bjt,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Singles Out Men From the Heartland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They're called rugged individualists, not subject
to the trends of the East or West coasts. And for about a dime a
guy, women can find these heartland hunks in the new Midwest Men
magazine.
   David Osstyn, a blue-eyed, 6-foot-3, 28-year-old clinical
technician from the Detroit area, is the cover man for the first
issue of Midwest Men, a quarterly based in suburban Downer's Grove,
which offers women a chance to meet the men of their dreams.
   Richard Needham, one of Midwest Men's three publishers, said the
magazine features 60 single men from eight states. He said they're
more sincere and less materialistic than their coastal counterparts.
   ``Midwest men are not as apt to be as far-out, let's say, as
people from the West Coast, or as fast-paced as people from the East
Coast,'' Needham said in a telephone interview recently.
   Osstyn agreed.
   ``I've been out West ... It's all me, me, me and nobody else. The
people from the East are the same way,'' he said.
   ``I'm just as happy sitting at home watching a movie as I am
going out dancing all night,'' said the dark-haired Osstyn, who is
described in the magazine's centerfold report as quiet, shy,
headstrong and creative.
   He said he has received more than 200 letters since the magazine
hit the newsstands nationwide in July, and so many phone calls that
he got an unlisted number.
   Initial reports indicate the $100,000 venture is going well, said
Charles Bowgren, another publisher. And women don't seem to be
deterred by the magazine's $5.95 cover price.
   Midwest Men features a few pages devoted to things like recipes
and a brief article or two.
   But the big attraction is the men, page after page of them,
looking for Ms. Right. There are photographs of the subjects, short
descriptions and their addresses for those who want to learn more.
   There's also a centerfold _ fully-clothed _ of a tanned Osstyn
showing off his biceps in a red and black cyclist outfit in the
first issue.
   Then there's Richard G. of Palatine, Ill., a Libra who's made
more than 600 free-fall parachute jumps; James D., a ``blond-haired,
blue-eyed hunk'' of German descent from King, Wis.; and Bill T. of
Brighton, Mich., who likes fast cars and golfing.
   ``I don't know if there are a lot of desperate women out there or
what,'' said Michael Catlin, manager of a Walgreens store in the
heart of neighborhood populated largely by singles. ``But for
nothing else than the novelty's sake, it's selling.''
   The idea of promoting men through a magazine is not new. Alaska
Men is already a smash throughout the country, and has generated
three weddings and numerous engagements, said Susie Carter, its
publisher.
   Ms. Carter, a former homemaker from Anchorage, sold concept
rights to the three Chicago-area publishers. She says the magazines
help women by eliminating much of the awkward singles scene.
   She also offers tips on how to respond to Midwest men in the
magazine's first issue.
   ``If you use perfume, use a very light touch on the letter,'' and
use nice stationery, Ms. Carter writes.
   Don't lie about your looks or move too fast for the guy.
   ``Keep writing, even if you don't get a reply; there are always
more men coming up.''
</TEXT>
