<HEAD>Report: Laventhol &amp; Horwath in Merger Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philadelphia-based accounting firm Laventhol
&amp; Horwath is in preliminary merger talks with a medium-sized
competitor, according to a confidential memo.
   The disclosure, first reported in an accounting trade journal and
repeated in Friday's New York Times, comes a month after Laventhol
began a national advertising campaign that stresses it has not
joined the merger fever of its larger competitors.
   Recently, several Big Eight accounting firms have disclosed plans
to merge.
   Laventhol, a second-tier firm, is in talks over a possible merger
with Spicer &amp; Oppenheim of New York, according to the memo,
disclosed in a special Sept. 7 issue of the International Accounting
Bulletin.
   ``If a merger is consummated, it will have a very positive effect
on our domestic and international market positions,'' George L.
Bernstein, Laventhol's executive partner, said in the memo,
according to the Times.
   A Laventhol-Spicer combination would have $928 million in
worldwide annual revenue.
   Spicer has been known to have been seeking a merger partner due
to financial troubles, the Times said.
