<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe     09-08 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Traders Plead Guilty, One Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more commodities traders have pleaded guilty
and another has pleaded innocent to federal charges that they
cheated customers while executing orders in the soybean pit at the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   The three traders who entered their pleas Thursday were among 45
traders and a clerk from the Board of Trade and Chicago Mercantile
Exchange who were indicted on charges stemming from the government's
probe of alleged fraud at the world's largest futures exchange.
   John Ryan, 49, of Winnetka, Ill., pleaded innocent before U.S.
District Judge William T. Hart to charges of mail and wire fraud and
violating federal commodities law.
   Kenneth Gillen, 29, of Naperville, Ill., pleaded guilty to one
misdemeanor count of pre-arranged trading that cost a customer $250.
   Harry O. Patten III, 39, of Western Springs, Ill., pleaded guilty
to two counts of commodity fraud _ one a misdemeanor, the other a
fellony. Patten admitted to carrying out an illegal pre-arranged
``curb trade'' with another trader after the closing bell and making
a $250 profit. He also admitted assisting in a pre-arranged trade
with two other brokers.
   Gillen and Patten agreed to testify at the trial of other
traders, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Rotert.
   A federal grand jury returned the indictments last month after
the 2{-year investigation by FBI agents, disguised as traders, at
the Board of Trade and Merc.
   So far, 10 traders and the clerk have pleaded guilty and agreed
to cooperate with the government in the prosecution of at least 13
traders who have pleaded innocent and plan to fight the charges.
   No sentencing date has been set for any of those who pleaded
guilty.
   Gillen faces up to four months in prison under federal sentencing
guidelines, said his attorney David Schippers.
   Schippers said his client was the lone person indicted on only
one misdemeanor count, and that he believed curb trading ``was going
on as a daily affair'' at the CBOT.
</TEXT>
