<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0950EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Italy-BankScandal 1stLd-Writethru f0036 09-08 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Bank Scandal, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0036,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman of Italy's Largest Bank Resigns Over Unauthorized Credits
to Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf pvs `No successors' with 2 new grafs to UPDATE
with government replacing two officials; picks ups 5th graf pvs, `Nesi,
64,...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Italy's largest bank has resigned
over a scandal involving unauthorized export credits to Iraq granted
by the Italian bank's branch in Atlanta, Ga.
   Nerio Nesi, chairman of the state-owned Banca Nazionale del
Lavoro (BNL), and the bank's director-general, Giacomo Pedde,
stepped down at an extraordinary meeting of the bank's board
Thursday night, the bank said in a brief statement.
   The communique said that ``the board, faced with the resignations
of Chairman Nerio Nesi and Director-General Giacomo Pedde, expresses
to them its most ample and full recognition for the sensibility
demonstrated in the interest of the bank and confirms its highest
appreciation for the activity carried out in the fulfillment of
their respective responsibilities in the service of the
institution.''
   Treasury Minister Guido Carli today quickly named replacements
for the two top officials. Giampiero Cantoni was named chairman of
the state-owned Banca Nazionale del Lavoro and Paolo Savona will be
director-general, the government said.
   The nominations require Parliamentary approval. BNL is 74-percent
owned by the Treasury.
   Nesi, 64, had been chairman of the bank since 1978. He previously
held executive positions with Olivetti and the state-run RAI
broadcasting network.
   Pedde, 62, had been director-general since 1987.
   BNL said Thursday its Atlanta branch had extended at least $1.7
billion in unauthorized export credits to Iraq.
   The board meeting came three weeks after BNL announced it had
uncovered transactions by its Atlanta branch that were not
authorized by either the bank's North American management or its
Rome headquarters.
   BNL said the 2,500 transactions consisted of the confirmation of
letters of credit covering exports of agricultural products,
industrial machinery and plants to Iraq. BNL has said no arms
shipments were involved.
   It is the biggest banking scandal in Italy since Banco
Ambrosiano, Italy's largest private bank, collapsed in 1982 after
failure to collect $1.4 billion in loans to dummy companies in Latin
America.
   BNL said in the communique that its board ``unanimously expressed
complete faith in the patrimonial solidity of the institution.''
   The statement said the board felt obligated to take whatever
actions deemed necessary to defend the strength of the bank and
would ``eliminate the shortcomings in the control procedures, which
have emerged in these circumstances.''
   Earlier Thursday, in its first statement giving concrete details
of the affair, BNL said that the Atlanta branch had executed $1.72
billion in export credits to Iraq. The bank promised an additional
$920 million in credits, and BNL is investigating whether this
obligation was legally binding, the statement said.
   Of the $1.72 billion already disbursed, about $700 million are 98
percent guaranteed by the U.S. Commodity Credit Corp. and the
remaining $1.020 billion by the Iraqi central bank, BNL said.
   The bank has said the letters of credit, while correct
technically, exceeded the credit ceiling that BNL set for the
Atlanta branch.
   The transactions were conducted by the Atlanta bank manager,
Christopher Drogoul, who has since been suspended. BNL filed a
complaing against Drogoul with Italian justice authorities in Rome
on Wednesay.
   The transactions, which are believed to cover a period of three
years, were never reported on the official books by the branch
management, but were reportedly kept on a personal computer at
Drogoul's home.
   BNL has been under investigation by the U.S. Federal Reserve
Board and Georgia state banking authorities since the beginning of
August. The Bank of Italy, the central bank, is collaborating in the
probe.
   There have been reports the irregularities weren't limited to the
Atlanta branch but also involved BNL branches in Italy.
   BNL is 76-percent owned by the Italian Treasury, while the rest
of its voting capital is in the hands of state entities. It has
non-voting shares quoted on the Milan stock exchange.
   The securities industry watchdog committee Consob suspended
trading in BNL shares Tuesday after they dropped 9.7 percent to
14,900 lire, or $10.50 a share, on Monday, down from 16,500 lire, or
$11.80 a share, on Friday.
   The bank has said it doesn't expect to incur any losses from the
affair. But fears have been raised that Iraq, whose economy was
crippled by its war with Iraq, may be unable to meet its debt.
Analysts said the bank may have to set aside reserves to make
special provisions for the Iraqi credit.
   BNL had total assets of $88 billion at the end of 1988, and
ranked 44th in the world, according to IBCA Banking Analysis Ltd., a
London credit rating agency.
   Banking analysts have said the scandal won't have a major impact
on the bank's balance sheet or economic results. They say the main
damage is to BNL's image at home and abroad.
   Numerous politicians, both from the opposition and the governing
parties, have presented in Parliament scores of questions about the
scandal.
   ``It's a particularly delicate matter that involves the
functioning of the entire banking system,'' Arnaldo Forlani, head of
the dominant Christian Democrats, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
