<DOCNO> AP890908-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-UAL     09-08 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Big Texas Investor, Buyout Specialist Kohlberg Kravis Might Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire investor Robert Bass and takeover
firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. have contacted United Airlines'
Machinists union about bidding for parent company UAL Corp., the
Wall Street Journal reported today.
   Overtures from Bass and Kohlberg suggested a pilot-led $6.75
billion offer backed by management could face unexpected competition
in the bidding struggle for UAL, one of the nation's leading
airlines and a prime takeover target.
   United's Machinist union has not supported the pilot-management
proposal.
   UAL's board also is considering a $6.19 billion offer from Los
Angeles investor Marvin Davis, but there have been rumors that he
has started selling his stake in the company, an indication he might
scrap his takeover effort.
   UAL stock, which fell $5.12{ a share on the Davis rumor Thursday,
was up $2.75 a share to $284.50 in early New York Stock Exchange
trading today.
   The Journal quoted Machinists union vice president John Peterpaul
as saying a Bass-led group is seeking a meeting to discuss whether
the machinists would be interesting in supporting a bid.
   Peterpaul also was quoted as saying Kohlberg Kravis has expressed
interest as well. Both contacts were described as preliminary and no
possible purchase amount was disclosed.
   The bidding for Chicago-based UAL began several weeks ago with an
offer by Davis and quickly escalated into one of the biggest
takeover sagas of 1989, driving up the company's stock price on
speculation that higher offers would emerge.
   Bass is a leading corporate dealmaker from Texas with interests
in oil, financial services, real estate, publishing and investments
in several well-known companies.
   Kohlberg is a New York-based investment house that helped pioneer
the takeover strategy known as the leveraged buyout, in which
companies are bought with borrowed money repaid through earnings or
asset sales of the target company. Kohlberg paid nearly $25 billion
in mostly borrowed money to buy RJR Nabisco Inc. earlier this year,
the biggest takeover in history.
</TEXT>
