<FIRST>r f PM-BPChairman     09-08 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BP Chairman,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Horton Named British Petroleum Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Standard Oil Co. chairman Robert Horton
has been appointed chairman of British Petroleum Co. PLC effective
next March.
   Horton, chairman of Cleveland-based Standard Oil from 1986 to
1988, will succeed Sir Peter Walters as chairman of the parent of BP
America Inc., British Petroleum's U.S. subsidiary and the company
that took over Standard Oil two years ago.
   Horton, 50, returned to London last year to become a managing
director of BP and in March was named deputy chairman.
   ``I think the company is going in a pretty good direction as it
is,'' Horton said Thursday after the announcement. ``I don't plan to
make any fundamental changes.''
   Walters, 58, announced Thursday he would retire after 35 years
with BP. He had been managing director of the oil giant for 17 years
and chairman since 1981. His retirement is effective March 10, 1990,
the company said.
   Horton said BP would focus on three key businesses: oil,
petroleum-based chemicals and nutrition.
   The British-born Horton joined BP in 1957 and has held a variety
of oil supply, marketing, finance and planning positions with the
company, which was partially owned by the British government until
two years ago.
   He was named general manager of the BP Tanker Co. in 1975 and one
year later was named head of BP Group's corporate planning
department. Horton became chief executive officer of BP Chemicals
International in 1980.
</TEXT>
