<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AgBanks     09-08 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ag Banks,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA Survey: Fewer Agricultural Banks Own Farmland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer agricultural banks owned repossessed
farmland last year than in 1987, a survey by the American Bankers
Association indicates.
   A new report, based on an October 1988 survey, indicated that
35.6 percent of the banks polled owned repossessed land, the bankers
association said. That's down from 46 percent in a similar survey a
year earlier.
   Of five regions listed in the study, banks in the Corn Belt
states of North Dakota, South Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, Oklahoma and
Texas were most likely to own farmland, the study said.
   In those six states, 41.2 percent of the farm banks surveyed said
they owned repossessed land, the ABA said.
   Plains states _ Iowa, Missouri, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio _ also
had above-average rates of land ownership with 40.5 percent, the
survey indicated.
   Other regional ownership rates were 36.8 percent in the
Northeast, 26.5 percent in the South and 34.4 percent in the West,
according to the survey.
   Nationwide, the average agricultural bank owned 634 acres of
repossessed farmland worth $620,000, the survey said.
   Banks in the Corn Belt states averaged 264 acres of repossessed
land worth $207,000, the smallest average among the five regions.
   Banks in the western Region, all states west of the Corn Belt,
reported the highest averages, with 2,841 acres worth $5.3 million,
the study said.
   The report was based on survey forms returned by 749 banks that
either have $2.5 million or more in farm production loans or have
more than 50 percent of their loan portfolio in farm loans, the ABA
said.
   The association sent survey forms to 2,273 banks randomly
selected from the 4,547 that met the agricultural bank requirements.
   The report said small and medium-sized banks are more likely to
own famrland.
   Of the small banks, those with assets of $50 million or less,
38.2 percent owned farmland. Of the medium-sized banks, with assets
of $50 million to $100 million, 37.4 percent owned agricultural
land. About 28 percent of larger banks owned land, the study said.
   The report also said the number of farm borrowers who had reached
their credit limit was down slightly, decreasing from 25.3 percent
in June 1987 to 22.6 percent in June 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890908-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv11   09-08 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 11,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Sept. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>TVA May Be Penalized for Returning to Public Debt Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a parent scolding an ungrateful child, a
federal financing agency has warned the Tennessee Valley Authority
that if it sells bonds to the public, it can never come back home.
   The TVA, the federal agency that supplies electricity to many
parts of the South, is debating whether to float bonds in the public
market for the first time in 15 years.
   But if it goes ahead with its plan to sell a huge, $6.5 billion
issue on Wall Street to refinance old, high-interest notes, the
Federal Financing Bank says it never again will loan TVA its
low-cost funds.
   The Federal Financing Bank is an arm of the Treasury Department
that loans money to federal agencies such as the U.S. Postal
Service, the Export-Import Bank and the Rural Electrification
Administration by buying bonds that they issue.
   The bond purchases are like a private loan to the agencies since
the financing bank keeps the bonds and receives all the interest
paid on them. Their advantage is lower interest rates than those of
bonds sold on the public market.
   TVA wants to pay off bonds from the financing bank that carry
interest rates averaging about 12.25 percent. It says it should be
able to float new public-market bonds at about 9 percent or lower,
reflecting how much interest rates have dropped since the bonds were
bought.
   The refinancing should save TVA about $100 million a year for the
next 20 years, said William F. Malec, chief financial officer of the
Knoxville, Tenn.-based agency, which is the nation's largest power
company.
   That, in turn, should help TVA hold down its electric rates. TVA,
established by Congress in 1933 to help develop the rural South,
sells power at wholesale rates to municipal and cooperative power
companies in seven states that serve about 3 million households.
   TVA has borrowed exclusively from the financing bank since that
agency's creation in 1974, and it owes it about $16.5 billion. TVA
also has about $1.5 billion in public debt outstanding that was sold
before 1974.
   TVA's Malec decided to go to the public market for refinancing
after the Federal Financing Bank declined to loan it fresh money at
lower rates ahead of the call dates of the existing bonds, which are
several years away.
   But the financing bank made clear late last month in a letter to
TVA that it no longer would loan TVA money should it go that route.
   ``We're in a situation where the FFB is under no requirement to
lend to us,'' Malec said.
   However, Malec said last week, the decision over floating public
bonds may not be that tough because the cost of the financing
agency's funds is not substantially lower than the rate the TVA
could get in the public market.
   Another factor in favor of public borrowing is that it would
allow the TVA to structure bonds in more favorable terms, such as
allowing them to be called earlier than the federal bonds should
interest rates drop.
   Malec said the TVA expects to make its decision in a few weeks.
In the meantime, U.S. Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., and other
members of the Tennessee congressional delegation say they will try
to persuade the financing bank to change its stance.
   There's little question TVA bonds would receive a warm welcome
from the credit market. TVA's old public debt holds the top rating
from the major credit-rating agencies. Also, 17 investment houses
submitted proposals to help bring new notes to market, Malec said.
Of these, five were selected, with First Boston Corp. chosen as lead
underwriter.
   Ralph Horn, an executive vice president of First Tennessee Bank,
which helped underwrite past TVA public bond issues, said TVA notes
were always a hit.
   ``The bidding was always extremely strong. They got extremely
competitive rates,'' he said.
   Should TVA be cut off from federal funding, ``I think the demand
for their securities in the public market would suffice,'' Horn said.
   However, a large part of TVA's sterling credit rating is based on
its ability to tap the financing bank, said Amelie L. Wogan, an
analyst at Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. Should that link be severed,
TVA's rating would be reevaluated, she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Sept. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
