<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1057EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AshlandSettlement     09-08 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ashland Settlement,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ashland Oil Agrees To Pay $325 Million To Iran's National Oil Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GINA HOLLAND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's state oil company has settled out of
court for less than half of the $768 million it sought from Ashland
Oil Inc.
   Ashland said Thursday it had agreed to pay $325 million to
National Iranian Oil Co. to settle a 10-year dispute over crude oil
purchases from Iran.
   The dispute began when National Iranian Oil Co. said a subsidiary
of Ashland refused to pay for crude oil in 1979. A jury trial in the
case was scheduled to begin Monday in U.S. District Court in Jackson.
   ``Both sides were ready to settle at a certain number. But there
was a lot of discrepancy between those numbers until the last few
days,'' said Dan Lacy, vice president of corporate communications
for the Ashland, Ky., company. ``We are pleased.''
   Ashland representatives said Ashland Overseas Trading Limited
refused to pay for the oil because the Iranian company renegged on
the contract, forcing the company to buy higher-priced oil on the
open market. Ashland officials did not say why the Middle Eastern
firm backed out of the contract but said the deal was broken during
the Iranian hostage crisis in 1979.
   National Iranian has said it stopped sending oil to Ashland
because the American firm didn't pay its bill.
   The Jackson-based attorney for National Iranian could not be
reached for comment Thursday.
   The three-day court-monitored negotiations for the settlement
ended Thursday afternoon, Lacy said. Court officials in Biloxi could
not be reached for comment Thursday.
   ``We've had negotiations for years. This is our first
court-supervised negotiation,'' Lacy said.
   National Iranian filed a complaint in 1985 in Mississippi, which
is served by Ashland Oil, Lacy said. The case, which had been in
courts in England, Bermuda and the United States since 1980, was
brought to Mississippi, where the deadline for a court appearance
has not run out.
   The Iranian firm had asked for $768 million, which included
interest on the price of the oil, according to Ashland reports.
   ``Ashland never disputed receiving the crude oil or that it was
obligated to pay a reasonable price for it,'' said Ashland Chairman
John Hall. Hall, who was in Mississippi overseeing the settlement,
termed it fair and best for both sides.
   Ashland officials said there was no government pressure to settle
the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
