<HEAD>Most Crop Futures Retreat; Profit-Taking Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
some profit-taking after the previous session's rally.
   Soybean futures had risen to a two-week high of $6 a bushel
Thursday on perceptions of increased foreign demand for soybean oil.
   Traders were disappointed late Thursday to learn that the Soviet
Union would not make an immediate purchase of U.S. soybean oil,
although the Soviets indicated they were interested in buying soy
oil if prices drop.
   Today's early losses were limited by forecasts for a rainy
weekend in the Midwest, where the corn and soybean crops are rapidly
maturing.
   The forecasts are feeding fears of corn and soybean harvest
delays and of winter-wheat planting delays.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.95\ a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower \ cent higher with September at $2.36} a bushel; oats
were { cent to } cent lower with September at $1.35} a bushel;
soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 2\ cents higher with September at
$5.99 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .50 cent lower with October at 72.35
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .40 cent lower with
October at 81.70 cents a pound; hogs were .47 cent to .65 cent lower
with October at 39.12 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .65
cent to 1 cent lower with February at 46.10 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures advanced Thursday, with pork bellies
up the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit on speculation that some of
America's surplus bellies will be shipped to Poland as part of a
food-aid package.
