<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SmithKline-Hepatitis 2ndLd-Writethru   09-08 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SmithKline-Hepatitis, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>SmithKline Beecham To Announce FDA Approval For Hepatitis Vaccine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, Engerix-B, to UPDATE with
comment from Merck; picks up 5th graf pvs, The vaccine .... ^By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beecham PLC has received the
federal government's permission to sell a hepatitis B vaccine the
company hopes will give it a foothold in the $80 million to $85
million market now dominated by Merck &amp; Co., officials said.
   SmithKline officials would not disclose sales estimates for the
vaccine, Engerix-B, which was approved for sale in Europe in 1986
and is now distributed in about 80 countries, including Canada and
Australia.
   Catherine Sohn, director of vaccine marketing, said the vaccine
is $20 cheaper than Rahway, N.J.-based Merck's Recombivax, its sole
competitor in this country, and is about four months faster in
taking effect.
   Engerix-B, which will cost $149, involves three doses
administered over two months, Sohn said.
   But Merck spokesman said Gary Bruell said Recombivax costs
between $128 and $148, ``and thus our price is comparable.'' He said
Recombivax is administered in three doses over six months.
   ``It is important that there is another weapon in the fight
against this infectious disease,'' Bruell said.
   The vaccine received U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval
Aug. 28 and shipments to wholesalers began immediately. The vaccine
should reach doctors by Monday, Sohn said.
   Hepatitis B strikes an estimated 300,000 people in this country
each year, killing at least 5,000. Chronic carriers of hepatitis B
are prone to develop liver cancer and cirrhosis.
   Hepatitis B is transmitted sexually or through blood-to-blood
contact. High-risk groups include homosexual males, intravenous drug
abusers, health-care workers and Southeast Asians.
   The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration has
recommended requiring employers to offer hepatitis B vaccinations
free to any workers who risk contracting the disease through their
jobs.
   OSHA's recommendations also include protective clothing and
education about hepatitis.
   Work place exposure results in 6,000 to 7,400 hepatitis B
infections each year in the United States, causing up to 400
hospitalizations and 130 to 165 deaths.
   The vaccine approval comes just more than a month after
SmithKline Beckman Corp. stockholders approved a merger with Beecham
Group PLC, creating the world's second-largest pharmaceutical firm
with estimated sales of $6 billion a year.
   SmithKline officials agreed to the merger after a tumultuous year
that saw the company go through a reorganization as a result of
declining sales of Tagamet, its ulcer drug, and Dyazide, a popular
high blood-pressure medicine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
