<DOCNO> AP890908-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1414EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Plessey 1stLd-Writethru f0082 09-08 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Plessey, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0082,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plessey Backs GEC, Siemens Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 7 new grafs with Plessey recommending acceptance of
takeover bid. Picks up 7th graf pvs, During the ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plessey Co. PLC gave up its nine-month fight Friday
against a $3.14 billion takeover bid by General Electric Co. PLC and
Siemens AG of West Germany, and advised its shareholders to accept
the offer.
   The recommendation came after GEC and Siemens said earlier in the
day that they controlled 50.4 percent of Plessey, a British
electronics concern.
   The bidders said that with the majority stake and clearance on
all regulatory matters, they were able to make their offer
unconditional.
   ``Under the circumstances, it is in (Plessey) shareholders best
interests to realize their investment,'' a Plessey statement said.
   Plessey said it will now enter into discussion with GEC and
Siemens to help ensure ``an orderly transition.''
   Last month, the bidding consortium raised its hostile offer to
270 pence, or $4.16, a share, valuing Plessey at 2.04 billion
pounds, or $3.14 billion.
   In announcing earlier Friday they had won control of a majority
of Plessey stock, GEC and Siemens extended their bid until Sept. 28
which will allow for further acceptances of the offer.
   During the bitter nine-month takeover battle, Plessey argued that
the bid was inadequate.
   Plessey's earlier offer, made last year, was 225 pence per share.
That offer automatically lapsed in January following the British
government's decision to investigate the impact of the proposed
merger on the defense electronics industry.
   In August, the Department of Trade and Industry cleared the
companies' bid for Plessey after it agreed to several conditions
designed mainly to preserve competition in the defense electronics
business.
   GEC agreed that it will not take any interest in the Plessey
radar, military communications and traffic control businesses.
Originally, the companies had planned for GEC to take a 35 percent
interest in Siemens' defense interest.
   The companies also agreed that Siemens, as the potential owner of
the Plessey defense companies, would name only British citizens
directors of the units and that Siemens employees given access to
sensitive Plessey defense contract work would undergo U.K. security
clearance procedures.
   Also, GEC and Siemens have agreed to make available the
technology of the Joint Tactical Information Distribution System, a
project on which Plessey and GEC were competing, to other British
companies.
   Apart from the defense-related areas, GEC and Siemens are taking
equal shares in Plessey's electronic components and other
businesses. GEC is also making Siemens a minority partner in its
existing telecommunications joint venture with Plessey, GEC Plessey
Telecommunications.
   As expected, the bid also received final clearance by the
European Commission last week.
   An earlier 1.2 billion pound takeover bid by GEC for Plessey, in
1986, failed after the British Monopolies and Mergers Commission
ruled that the combined group would have too large a slice of the
defense electronics business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
