<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2119EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Saatchi     09-08 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Saatchi,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Investment Firm Buys Stake In Saatchi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shares in the advertising giant Saatchi and Saatchi
Co. traded slightly lower Friday on the London Stock Exchange, a day
after rising sharply on news that a U.S. investment firm had
acquired 9.4 percent of the company's stock.
   Memphis-based Southeastern Asset Management is now the biggest
shareholder in Saatchi, which has performed poorly the last few
years.
   Southeastern, which manages $2.3 billion in assets for its U.S.
investors, said in a statement the purchase is for investment only
and was ``not being made with a view toward changing or influencing
control of Saatchi.''
   Saatchi shares were off 2 pence to 319 pence Friday compared with
an 11 pence rise Thursday.
   A spokesman at Saatchi said the company knew about Southeastern's
interest but had not known the stake was so high until Thursday when
it was announced.
   Under British investment regulations, share blocks of more than
five percent must be reported to the stock exchange.
   Analysts in the City, London's financial district, said the stake
is almost three times as large as the 3.3 percent held by the
Saatchi brothers, Maurice and Charles, who founded the company.
   ``I was surprised by the size of the chunk,'' said Mark Astaire,
media analyst at Hoare Govett. ``I was not surprised it was an
American institution though, because they have not had the bad
experiences with Saatchi that U.K. firms have had, so they are less
jaundiced.''
   Analysts said Southeastern is buying at the right time since the
outlook for the world's largest advertising group has been expected
to improve since June when Saatchi announced it would sell its
consulting group.
   ``They have been weak because of the quick acquisitions of some
large New York advertising agencies like Ted Bates, Backer
Spielvogel and Dancer Fitzgerald,'' said David Forster, media
analyst at Kleinwort Benson. ``The quick growth has brought slack
financial control.''
   But Forster sees the company's finances improving.
   ``By selling their consulting division they will be able to pay
off their debt and have an improved cash flow,'' Forster said.
   Although Southeastern's announcement rekindled takeover
speculation that accompanied Saatchi's disappointing 1988 profit
figures released last spring, Forster said a hostile takeover is
very unlikely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
