<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-08 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rally On Export Talk, Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices burst through the
$6-a-bushel barrier Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, buoyed by
rumors of new Soviet interest in buying U.S. soybean meal and rising
fears of a rain-delayed harvest.
   Corn and oat futures also finished higher while wheat futures
were slightly lower.
   Soybeans for September delivery had traded as high as $6 a bushel
Thursday for the first time in nearly two weeks. The market pushed
beyond that psychological barrier late in Friday's session on rumors
that the Soviet Union was considering buying up to 2 million metric
tons of U.S. or South American soybean meal for shipment this fall.
   The soybean and corn markets also were supported by forecasts for
a rainy weekend in the Midwest, where corn and soybean crops are
rapidly maturing.
   The forecasts are feeding fears of corn and soybean harvest
delays and of winter-wheat planting delays.
   Although the crops needed rain earlier in the growing season,
``there's a feeling that too much rain now will be a detriment,''
said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York.
   At the close, wheat futures were \ cent to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.95 a bushel; corn was \
cent to 3 cents higher with September at $2.39{ a bushel; oats were
1 cent to 1} cents higher with September at $1.38 a bushel; and
soybeans were 1\ cents to 11\ cents higher with September at $6.08 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
