<DOCNO> AP890908-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Cocoa     09-08 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Cocoa,0515</SECOND>
<UNK>Key Producers Plan Price Pact Initiative</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ivory Coast, Brazil, Ghana and other major
cocoa producers said Friday they plan to ask the International Cocoa
Organization next week to revive a price-support system that would
raise world prices.
   Word of the proposal came at the end of three days of meetings
among representatives of the 13-member Cocoa Producers' Alliance.
   The proposal will be presented to the ICO meeting of cocoa
producers and consumers starting Monday in London.
   The powers of the 41-nation ICO to intervene in the market to
support a minimum price have been paralyzed since February 1988
because of a dispute between its producer and consumer members over
the minimum price a proposed new stockpiling scheme should defend
and a lack of cash to finance it. World cocoa prices have been
depressed by five consecutive years of surplus crops and earlier
this year prices hit a 13-year low. The surplus has hurt the
economies of major cocoa-producing nations such as the Ivory Coast.
On the New York Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange, the spot price of a
metric ton of cocoa traded this week at $1,077, near the decade low
of $1,048, said exchange economist Vic DeMayo. In 1983, a metric ton
of cocoa sold for $2,800, he said.
   The Ivory Coast, the world's biggest producer whose international
debts total more than $14 billion, is spearheading efforts to revive
the cocoa organization. Cocoa is the source of 30 percent of the
foreign exchange earnings of Ivory Coast and is an even more
important earner for Ghana.
   World production in the 1988-89 season is put at a record 2.4
million tons, thanks to record crops in the Ivory Coast and Malaysia
and a big recovery in Ghana's harvest.
   Traders have put the surplus over consumption at an all-time high
of 300,000 tons, which would lift season-end stocks above one
million tons for the first time ever.
   Introduction of a proposed new stockpiling scheme, under which
producers would receive financial help from the organization to
store up to 120,000 metric tons of surplus beans, has been blocked
by lack of cash and a dispute over the minimum target price.
   The cocoa organization is owed about $115 million by its producer
members, with the Ivory Coast's debt _ $70 million _ the biggest,
followed by Brazil, with $17 million.
   ``I cannot say that we will guarantee to pay all our debts, but
something will be offered on that,'' said one producer.
   Traders said if the pact's control function is revived at next
week's meeting this would boost the chances of a decision to extend
the accord with its regulatory power intact for one or two more
years.
   If there is no extension, the 250,000-ton stockpile already held
by the cocoa organization will have to be liquidated under current
rules within 4 1@2 years from September 1990.
   Delegates said that if next week's talks fail, prices would come
under renewed pressure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
