<FIRST>r f AM-WingContract     09-08 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wing Contract,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulfstream Aerospace Signs $85 Million Wing Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulfstream Aerospace Technologies announced
Friday that it has signed an $85 million contract to manufacture
wings for a new 29-seat British Aerospace aircraft.
   Gulfstream President Robert N. Buckley said the initial contract
calls for Gulfstream, a Chrysler Corp. subsidiary based in Oklahoma,
to manufacture 200 wing seats for the Jetstream 41 to be delivered
over a 10-year period.
   He said production is to begin with five wing sets in 1990 and
will increase to 35 sets by 1994. He said about 80 employees will be
required to start production.
   The Jetstream 41 is the latest addition to British Aerospace's
family of regional commuter airliners.
   The Jetstream 41 wing is the first major assembly contract
awarded to Gulfstream Aerospace Technologies, which employs about
960 in Oklahoma City.
   The plant is primarily engaged in parts subcontrcting for firms
like McDonnell Douglas Corp., Boeing Co. and Rohr Industries Inc.,
as well as for government agencies.
