<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern Bjt   09-08 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, Bjt,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Pilots Choose New Leader; Eastern Seeks Delay on Filing Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' pilots said Friday they have
chosen ``a gladiator'' to lead them after ousting the union leader
who a month ago suggested they end their strike.
   Skip Copeland, an Eastern captain based in New York, was chosen
by acclamation Friday to take over the union leadership. On
Thursday, the pilots' executive council voted to recall Chairman
Jack Bavis.
   Copeland, a 27-year Eastern veteran and a union activist, is
considered a hard-liner on the strike and far less conciliatory than
Bavis.
   ``It was meant to be a positive move,'' said Raymond Wright, the
Eastern pilots union's vice chairman. ``It's been a long, hard and
tedious fight. With a new guy, you can have vim and vigor.
   ``I believe the body is under the clear impression that over the
next few weeks we're on a backstretch,'' Wright said by telephone
from Washington, where the executive council met. ``They wanted a
gladiator, a hard-charger.''
   Eastern, meanwhile, asked the U.S. Bankruptcy Court to extend by
60 days the Sept. 15 deadline for Eastern to file a disclosure
statement for its bankruptcy reorganization plan. The disclosure
statement will contain details on Eastern's financial position,
including 5-year projections, the company said Friday.
   Miami-based Eastern has been under Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection since March 9, five days after the start of the strike by
pilots, Machinists and flight attendants. The airline filed a
proposed reorganization plan on July 21. The disclosure statement
will describe how Eastern intends to emerge from bankruptcy.
   The rank-and-file pilots' sentiment turned against Bavis after he
proposed Aug. 6 that they consider ending the strike. Local chapter
straw votes showed overwhelming opposition to halting the strike,
now in its seventh month.
   Bavis, an Eastern pilot since 1966 and official for years with
the national Air Line Pilots Association, became the Eastern pilots
union leader in 1986.
   Bavis didn't immediately return telephone messages left at his
Virginia home.
   Eastern Machinists union leader Charles Bryan declined comment,
saying he didn't want to discuss another union's internal politics.
Bryan and Bavis had been on cool terms for years.
   Earlier, pilots union and management officials said they have
scheduled negotiations for Monday, their first talks in six weeks.
   The pilots requested the talks before the National Mediation
Board in June, while the airline made a similar request in July.
Pilots union officials believe the company is trying to rush through
the federally mandated bargaining process so it can put aside the
pilots' contract.
   Jack Mogus of the Eastern pilots' executive council said the
talks in Washington, D.C., will probably end in an impasse and that
Eastern will ask the National Mediation Board to set a 30-day
cooling-off period, after which Eastern could impose its own
conditions on pilots who have crossed picket lines.
   The pilots who crossed picket lines are still covered by the ALPA
contract with Eastern.
   But Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said, ``We look at this as an
opportunity to resolve our differences with the pilots union.''
   Eastern previously dropped an attempt to have the pilots'
contract terminated in bankruptcy court.
   More than 300 pilots crossed picket lines in the week after Bavis
and other union officials urged ending the strike. Other local union
officials have been replaced since then.
   The pilots union, along with the Machinists and flight
attendants, says Eastern's management is dismantling the airline and
a change in ownership is needed.
   Eastern is trying to rebuild without its unions. More than 650 of
3,600 ALPA pilots at Eastern have crossed picket lines since the
strike began, joining some 1,000 newly hired pilots. Eastern
recently announced it had stopped hiring new pilots.
   Eastern on Thursday boosted its daily schedule to 601 flights and
reported a 75.4 percent average load factor for August.
   Company spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said the load factor was a
record for Eastern in the month of August. She said percentage of
capacity filled for August 1988 flights was 68.2 percent.
   Eastern had nearly 1,100 daily flights before the strike. Eastern
added about 200 flights Thursday, as announced earlier, with most
additional flights out of the Atlanta hub that has been the focus of
Eastern's rebuilding efforts.
   Eastern says it will be up to 700 daily flights on Oct. 1 and 800
flights by year's end, when it hopes to emerge from bankruptcy at
two-thirds its pre-strike size.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
