<DOCNO> AP890908-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 0742EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-SellingSkiing Adv11   09-08 0940</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Selling Skiing, Adv 11,0966</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Sept. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ski Businesses Undertake Big New Promotion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto planned; Graphic in AP Access Under SKISELL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ski industry businesses have joined forces
for the first time to promote the sport among the estimated 35
million Americans who like the outdoors but never have donned skis.
   The campaign will include network television advertisements and
efforts by the country's 450 ski areas to make skiing a more
comfortable experience, from squeezing on boots to swishing down the
bunny hill.
   ``For every 100 people who learn to ski there's probably a pretty
high percentage, probably at least a third, who never return. Maybe
it's as high as 50 percent. Now why aren't they returning?'' said
Bill Stenger, general manager of Jay Peak ski area in Vermont and
chairman of the national campaign task force.
   The anxiety some beginners feel when staring up a ski slope may
be one reason for the dropout rate. So is money.
   The average daily expense for an out-of-state skier in Vermont,
for example, including a lift ticket, food, lodging and equipment
rental, averaged almost $70 a day this past season, a state survey
shows.
   Ski gear can cost hundreds of dollars _ a pair of skis can easily
exceed $500 _ and lessons can range from about $25 an hour for a
group class to about $45 for individual instruction in many areas.
   But industry officials are hoping to help would-be skiers
overcome their reluctance by presenting skiing as fun and more
affordable than they might think.
   ``It's an image campaign designed to show skiing is for families,
individuals, for young, for old, full of fun and enthusiasm, that
people should give it a try,'' Stenger said.
   The `Ski It To Believe It' campaign is sponsored by the National
Ski Areas Association, which represents 450 ski areas in the U.S.
and Canada, and Ski Industries America, which represents 600
manufacturers and distributors of skiwear, skis, bindings, boots,
poles and ski accessories.
   The groups plan to merge, creating one large organization called
the United Ski Industries Association.
   The campaign was inspired partly by the golf industry, which
estimates 400 new courses will have to be built each year for the
next 10 years to meet growing demand. That industry contracted with
McKinsey &amp; Co., a New York management consulting firm, to prepare a
long-term plan for such growth.
   The ski industry has enough facilities; it just wants more
customers. Figures compiled by the NSAA show the number of skier
visits has grown less than 6 percent over 10 seasons to about 53.34
million this past year. One skier visit represents one person
visiting a ski area for any part of a day.
   ``Golf is on a tremendous roll, and there's no reason skiing
shouldn't be,'' Stenger said.
   The ski industry also used McKinsey to determine the potential
market.
   ``They defined an estimated 35 million people whose lifestyles
matched up to current skiers,'' said Kathe Dillmann of the
Springfield, Mass.-based NSAA. ``So our target is this 35 million
Americans who should have some propensity for skiing. If they're
active and like the outdoor arena, we think they should consider
skiing, and we just haven't approached them correctly.''
   The campaign, a first for the industry, began in September with
some preliminary promotion. The TV ad will air on the major networks
Nov. 2-22 and Jan. 8-28 at a cost of $5.5 million.
   Shot last year at Vail, Colo., it will feature ski scenes and a
theme song.
   ``It shows moderate skiers and good action shots and
learn-to-skiers. There are some high mountains but not many. Mostly
it's just close-ups of a lot of fun-looking, average people having a
good time,'' Dillmann said.
   Another $1.5 million will be spent on print and radio ads, as
well as public relations and special promotions. The campaign also
may include newspaper ads to promote a national learn-to-ski day on
Jan. 19, when beginners can rent equipment, take lessons and ski for
free at participating areas.
   Ski businesses have been asked to give a percentage of last
year's sales to finance the campaign. Dillman said most of the money
has been raised.
   State ski associations will pick up the ball with local campaigns
tailored to their areas. At the same time, ski areas will try to
make the ski experience less frightening for the newcomer.
   ``If we are successful in getting the attention of the 25 to 30
million Americans who have the potential to ski, we're going to have
to be more sensitive in our rental shops, our ski school,'' Stenger
said.
   ``All resorts are looking very hard to make sure they're making
it less confusing, easy, fun for a person to reach what I call the
comfort zone of skiing, where they know where they are and are not
confused,'' said Bobby Foster, director of marketing for the
Waterville Valley slope in New Hampshire's White Mountains.
   Stenger said the ski areas in North America still have room for
more participants, especially if skiers try some of the less popular
resorts.
   ``In Vermont, if you get outside the top few resorts, there's
lots of availability in terms of space, except for Christmas week,''
he said. ``I would hope that with increased volume we would be able
to see rates stabilizing. That's a double-edged sword for me because
I know that price is one of the major deterrents to people skiing,
and we need to find ways of making skiing affordable. We hope
stabilized rates are a part of that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday Sept. 11</NOTE>
