<SECOND>BC-Ford Plants,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Cuts Production at 3 Truck Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will stop production at
three truck assembly plants for one week because of a shortage of
dealer orders and a strike at a supplier plant, the automaker said
Friday.
   The Louisville, Ky., assembly plant and the Kentucky truck plant,
both in Louisville, will be closed the week of Sept. 11 because of
an order shortage, affecting about 5,100 workers.
   The plants make the Bronco II and Ranger light trucks and medium-
and heavy-duty trucks.
   The company also said it would stop production at its Wayne,
Mich., truck plant for the week of Sept. 18 because of the strike.
That plant, which employs about 1,660 hourly workers, makes F-series
and Bronco trucks.
   The United Auto Workers union struck the Borg-Warner transmission
plant in Muncie, Ind., on Thursday.
