<FIRST>d f AM-Chrysler-Jeep     09-08 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler-Jeep,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Output of Grand Wagoneer to Halt for Four Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 Jeep workers will be temporarily
laid off when Chrysler Corp. suspends production of the Grand
Wagoneer's 1990 model for four weeks because of slumping sales.
   Sales of the 1989 Grand Wagoneer are off 15 percent from a year
ago and Jeep dealers still have a three-month supply of the vehicle
in stock, Douglas Nicholl, a spokesman for Chrysler Corp., Jeep's
parent, said Thursday.
   As of Aug 30, sales totaled 11,387, compared with 13,442 for the
corresponding period a year ago.
   Employees who make Grand Wagoneers at the Jeep assembly plant in
Toledo will begin a two-week furlough on Monday, return for a week
to work starting Sept. 25, then be laid off for two more weeks
beginning Oct. 2.
   The temporary shutdown comes after a two-week furlough in the
last two weeks of August, also because of slow Grand Wagoneer sales.
   The 1990 Grand Wagoneer, which sells for $25,000, is Jeep's most
expensive model. Jeep is a division of Chrysler Corp.
</TEXT>
