<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-08 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar on Friday approached the peaks reached
in its June rally as a comment by a Swiss national banker gave fresh
confidence to bullish dealers in a thin market.
   Gold edged down.
   Jean Zwahlen, a member of the Swiss National Bank's governing
board, was quoted as saying that the dollar is likely to rise in the
immediate future based on the strength of the U.S. economy.
   Zwahlen also was quoted as saying that the ability of central
banks to restrain the dollar's rise depends on the strength of
market sentiment toward the U.S. currency.
   The dollar was given another boost by a rumor, later denied by
the Soviet embassy in Washington, that Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev had died, said Lynn Tierney, a vice president at Shawmut
Bank of Boston.
   Trading was light to moderate, so price movements were
exaggerated, said Jack Adkins, a currency analyst at Refco Group
Ltd. in Chicago.
   ``It didn't take a whole lot to get things going,'' Adkins said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell to 146.62 yen from 146.87 yen late Thursday. Later,
in London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 146.45 yen. In New York
the dollar moved up to 147.20 yen from 146.65 on Thursday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5505 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5460 late Thursday.
In New York, the dollar gained ground as the pound fell to $1.5380
from $1.5520.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.9950 West German marks, up from 1.9798; 1.7245
Swiss francs, up from 1.7075; 1.1875 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1859; 6.7195 French francs, up from 6.6680; and 1,493 Italian
lire, up from 1,419.3.
   In June the dollar got as high as 159 yen and 2.02 marks, levels
not seen in roughly two years.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.9795 West German marks, down from 1.9845;
1.7080 Swiss francs, down from 1.7120; 6.6710 French francs, down
from 6.6880; 2.2320 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2423; 1,421.70
Italian lire, down from 1,426.20; and 1.1877 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1842.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $360.00 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $359.50. In Zurich, gold rose to
$360.00 an ounce compared with $359.75 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 54 cents to close at a $360.25
an ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $359.40 a troy ounce from $360.20. Later, Republic
National Bank of New York fell to $358.75 from $359.70.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to $5.12 a troy ounce,
compared with $5.11 late Thursday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.053 an ounce from $5.117.
</TEXT>
