<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1736EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Avon-Perfume 1stLd-Writethru   09-08 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Perfume, 1st Ld-Writethru,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Exploring Possibility of Selling Perfume Businesses</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 17th graf pvs to UPDATE with closing stock price; PICKS
UP 18th graf pvs, `Jack L. ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. disclosed on Friday it may
sell its Giorgio Beverly Hills and Parfums Stern fragrance
businesses, suppliers of some of the country's hottest selling
scents.
   No final decision on whether to divest the subsidiaries has been
reached, said James E. Preston, the big cosmetic company's chairman
and chief executive officer. But Avon has hired the investment
banking firm Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. to help it explore the possibility
of a sale and evaluate alternatives.
   Proceeds from a possible sale would go toward reducing Avon's
debt, which at mid-year totaled about $1 billion, Preston said in a
statement.
   Giorgio and Stern, acquired by Avon in 1987 for a total of about
$345 million, comprise the big beauty products company's retail
division. The division sells fragrances at department store counters
and through other retail vendors instead of through Avon sales
representatives.
   In the first half of this year, Giorgio and Stern contributed
four of the 10 best selling fragrances in the United States: Giorgio
Beverly Hills, Red, Oscar de la Renta, and Uninhibited by Cher,
according to Avon.
   Avon estimates that sales of its retail fragrance companies will
exceed $300 million this year, which would be less than 10 percent
of Avon's total revenue. Giorgio has about 280 employees and is
based in Santa Monica, Calif. and New York-based Stern has about 480
employees.
   Selling its retail fragrance business has long been seen as one
of several things Avon could do in its effort to enhance
profitability.
   As one element in that strategy, the company has been in the
process of selling off its health care services businesses to
concentrate on its core beauty and personal care direct-selling
operation.
   In the second quarter, Avon earned $39.5 million on sales of $778
million compared with a loss of $82.5 million and sales of $704
million a year earlier.
   Avon, the world's biggest direct sales company, was motivated to
speed up its financial turnaround earlier this year when it received
unwanted attention from several suitors.
   The most recent pursuer was Minneapolis-based investor Irwin L.
Jacobs. On Aug. 3, Avon's board rejected Jacobs' proposed
$41-a-share, or $2.85 billion, bid.
   Earlier, in May, Avon had doled out a rejection to direct-sales
rival Amway Corp., which had offered $2.1 billion. Avon also brushed
off tentative advances from Mary Kay Corp., parent of the
door-to-door cosmetics company.
   Both Jacobs and Amway had said that if they prevailed in
acquiring Avon, they would sell off Avon's retail fragrance
operations.
   Jacobs, who holds about a 10 percent stake in Avon, met with
Preston in August and after the meeting Avon said the two discussed
business plans.
   Andrew Shore, an analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said
Jacobs' interest in Avon probably helped persuade the company to
seriously consider selling its retail perfume lines to bolster its
balance sheet.
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if this was a decision that was helped
by Mr. Jacobs' and Mr. Preston's meeting a few weeks ago,'' said
Shore.
   Analysts said selling the holdings would be a smart move for
Avon. The announcement failed to spark enthusiasm in the stock
market, however. Avon closed unchanged at $36.25 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Jack L. Salzman, analyst at Goldman Sachs &amp; Co., said: ``I think
it's a positive'' move for Avon.
   Wall Street estimates of how much Avon might hope to get for
Giorgio and Stern ranged from $350 million to more than $450 million.
   One analyst said it would be reasonable for a buyer to pay 50
percent above this year's projected sales of $300 million for the
subsidiaries, meaning the price of Giorgio and Stern would be at
least $450 million.
   Names mentioned as potential buyers included Unilever, the
British-Dutch consumer products giant, and Shiseido Cosmetics
America Ltd., the U.S. arm of the big Japanese beauty and personal
products company.
   Unilever, which over the summer completed the acquisition of the
Faberge and Elizabeth Arden fragrance, toiletries and cosmetics
lines for $1.55 billion, is known to be interested in building its
presence in the prestige end of the perfume business.
   Avon's chief Preston said in an interview in the spring that
several parties had approached him expressing interest in buying
Giorgio and Stern. On Friday, an Avon spokesman refused to comment
on who might be interested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
