<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-08 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Extend Rally On Talk Of Soviet Meal Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices staged a strong rally Friday, bursting
through the $6-a-bushel barrier on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
rumors of Soviet demand for soybean meal and rising fears of a
rain-delayed harvest.
   On other markets, coffee and energy futures rose while livestock,
meat and precious metals retreated.
   Soybean futures settled 1\ cents to 10} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $6.07{ a bushel, the highest
settlement for a near-month soybean contract since Aug. 21.
   Wheat futures settled } cent to 1{ cents lower with September at
$3.95{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to 3 cents higher with September at
$2.39{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1} cents higher with September
at $1.38 a bushel.
   September soybeans had bumped into strong resistance at $6 a
bushel Thursday but pushed beyond that psychological barrier late in
Friday's session on rumors that the Soviet Union was looking to buy
up to 2 million metric tons of U.S. or South American soybean meal
for shipment this fall.
   Soybean meal futures also rose sharply, with the Sepember
contract settling $4.40 higher at $202.80 a ton.
   The soybean and corn markets were further supported by forecasts
for a rainy weekend in the Midwest, where corn and soybean crops are
rapidly maturing.
   The crops needed rain earlier in the growing season buy ``there's
a feeling that too much rain now will be a detriment,'' slowing the
corn and soybean harvests and delaying the planting of winter wheat,
said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York.
   The soybean market got a boost earlier in the week from a sale of
200,000 metric tons of soybeans to unknown destinations _ possibly
the Soviet Union, China or Japan _ and a government grant of 150,000
metric tons of soybean oil to Pakistan.
   Coffee futures rallied for the third straight day on speculation
that the United States may support Colombia's call for a return to
coffee export quotas among producer members of the International
Coffee Organization.
   The 74-nation cartel abandoned quotas July 3, partly due to U.S.
complaints that the quota allocations unreasonably limited the
availability of high-quality coffee to consumer members of the
cartel.
   Coffee futures settled 1.87 cents to 2.5 cents higher on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange, with September at 88.25 cents
a pound.
   Energy futures prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
paced by refined products in a technically inspired rally.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents to 34 cents
higher with October at $19.75 a barrel; heating oil was .84 cent to
1.24 cents higher with October at 56.74 cents a gallon; and unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent to 1.57 cents higher with October at 57.09
cents a gallon.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, livestock and meat futures
prices fell sharply after two days of gains linked to hopes that the
United States will send some of its surplus pork bellies to Poland
as part of a food aid package.
   Live cattle finished .05 cent to .90 cent lower with October at
71.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .60 cent lower
with September at 82.17 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .75
cent lower with October at 39.17 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .92 cent to 1.30 cents lower with February at 45.90
cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell on New York's Commodity
Exchange in reaction to the stronger dollar.
   Gold settled $1 lower across the board with October at $361.30 a
troy ounce; silver was 6.4 cents to 7.4 cents lower with September
at $5.053 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
