<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 2334EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PPGClosings     09-08 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PPG Closings,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>PPG Closing Plants In Minnesota, Illinois</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PPG Industries said Friday it will close plants
in Lincoln, Ill., and Marshall, Minn., due to a decrease in demand
for the glass insulation products made there.
   Production of a new generation of glass-edge insulation units was
suspended in August because of slumping sales, the company said.
   Insulating units for residential windows were produced by PPG at
Lincoln since 1953 and at Marshall since 1975, the company said.
   Production will cease at the Lincoln plant, which employed about
180 people in 1988, in the next two weeks, the company said. The
plant will be shut down by the end of the year.
   Ninety-four employees already have been laid off at the Marshall
plant, and most of the remaining 74 workers will be laid off when
production ceases by mid-October, the company said. The plant should
be shut down by early 1990.
</TEXT>
