<FIRST>r f AM-MortgageRefinancing     09-08 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mortgage Refinancing,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Mortgage Refinancing Rose This Summer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home owners took advantage of lower mortgage
rates to refinance their loans this summer, a trade group said
Friday.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America, which surveyed 30 of
the nation's largest mortgage bankers, said all but one firm
reported an increase in refinancing.
   The median rise in refinancing was 25 percent from early June to
late August and firms reported overall mortgage business up a median
29 percent, the group said.
   Fixed-rate mortgages, hit a peak of 11.22 percent in March, fell
to below 9.82 percent in mid-July and have risen since, averaging
10.17 percent this week, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp.
   The mortgage bankers said the lenders in their survey make loans
in all 50 states, and accounted for about $25 billion in mortgages
last year.
</TEXT>
