<FIRST>r f AM-Vitro-Anchor     09-08 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vitro-Anchor,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Company Extends Tender Offer Until Sept. 14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vitro S.A. extended its $280 million takeover
bid for Anchor Glass Container Corp. Friday, but the Tampa glass
maker said it still recommends that stockholders reject the $20 per
share tender offer.
   Anchor also said in a statment that it was involved in
preliminary discussions with ``a number of third parties interested
in a possible transaction with the company.''
   Vitro extended its offer until 5 p.m. EDT Sept. 14. The previous
deadline was 12:01 a.m. Friday.
   Vitro made the takeover offer Aug. 9 for Anchor, one of the
nation's leading bottle makers. It was one of the first unsolicited
bids by a Mexican company for a major U.S. manufacturer.
   Anchor's board of directors asked shareholders Aug. 22 not to
sell stock to Vitro and repeated its recommendation Friday after
Vitro pushed back the deadline.
   Anchor also announced prices for returnable beverage bottles and
liquor bottles will be hiked by 8 percent Oct. 1. The company is
increasing consumer glassware items by 6 percent.
   Anchor attributed the increase to accumulated cost increases not
covered by previous price hikes and for productivity improvement
programs.
