<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1853EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Campeau 1stLd-Writethru   09-08 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campeau, 1st Ld-Writethru,0860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloomies on the Block: Campeau Reveals Plan to Lighten Debt Load</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with comment from Bloomingdale's chief Traub, SUBS
2nd graf, `Bloomingdale's Chairman ...,' and SUBS 2 grafs for 11th graf
pvs, `An announcement, ...' Stands for TORONTO-dated story on AM-Business
News Digest.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp., the debt-laden Canadian developer
and owner of numerous retail businesses, Friday proposed a major
financial overhaul that includes the sale of Bloomingdale's, one of
the best known store chains.
   Bloomingdale's Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Marvin S.
Traub said he is in the preliminary stages of putting together a
buyout proposal.
   Wall Street analysts said Campeau's willingness to part with
Bloomingdale's underscored the severity of the financial
difficulties facing the company.
   The decision to sell Bloomingdale's also was viewed as a bitter
irony for Campeau Chairman Robert Campeau who about 18 months ago
gained control of Bloomingdale's parent, Federated Department Stores
Inc., after a prolonged takeover battle that included skirmishes
with retailer R.H. Macy &amp; Co. Inc.
   Bloomingdale's, a unit of Federated, was widely assumed to be the
top prize that Campeau sought. The $6.7 billion Campeau paid for
Federated left the company deeply in debt and hobbled it
financially, analysts say.
   In announcing the restructuring proposal Friday, Campeau said the
plan was designed to ``begin the process of significantly reducing
the company's indebtedness and addressing certain of the company's
working capital needs.''
   The plan will be brought before Campeau's board of directors at a
meeting Sept. 12 at the company's Toronto headquarters.
   Among elements of the plan the board will consider is a possible
infusion of funds from Toronto-based Olympia &amp; York Developments
Ltd., which currently holds an 11.8 percent stake in Campeau.
   Olympia &amp; York has discussed lending $250 million to Campeau to
meet cash needs at Federated and Campeau's Allied Stores Corp.
division, Campeau said.
   The investment banking firm First Boston Corp. has been hired to
seek possible buyers for Bloomingdale's, Campeau said.
   Bloomingdale's chief Traub is interested in a buyout of the
well-known chain he has headed since 1978. He said in an interview
Friday that he began making arrangements with merchant bankers and
lawyers after discussing the idea with Robert Campeau and other
Campeau executives at a dinner meeting in London about a week and a
half ago.
   ``It's in the early stages,'' said Traub, adding that a change in
Bloomingdale's ownership isn't likely to occur before the end of
this year.
   Traub, highly regarded in retail circles for his merchandising
expertise, helped give Bloomingdale's a special cachet that has
turned it into a prized property.
   This value was cited as a reason why Campeau chose to put it on
the block.
   ``As a highly valued franchise that promises to yield significant
proceeds, Bloomingdale's offers the best opportunity to most
effectively reduce the company's leverage with a single
transaction,'' Federated said.
   Walter Loeb, an analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. Inc., said:
``Obviously they're trying to expeditiously sell one of the assets.
Bloomingdale's is the most saleable.''
   ``Bloomingdale's would be the last thing he (Robert Campeau)
would want to sell,'' said Loeb, ``but he's selling it first because
he no longer has the kind of options'' he was expected to have.
   David Poneman, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co., said
selling Bloomingdale's isn't surprising because it fits into a
pattern Campeau has followed.
   The company divested two premier properties that, like
Bloomingdale's, had attractive intangible features, making them more
valuable that they would be just judging by their cash flows, said
Poneman. The two were Brooks Brothers and Ann Taylor clothing chains.
   Some analysts had speculated that Campeau eventually might run
into trouble trying to cope with the debt it accumulated in taking
over Federated and Allied. Campeau bought Allied in December 1986
for $3.4 billion.
   Moving to counter the criticism in January, Campeau took out
prominent advertisements saying ``Nothing Succeeds Like Success''
and touting the company's achievements. ``Because we have achieved
so much in this last year, it has been difficult for some to track
and monitor our progress,'' the ad said.
   In late April, Campeau announced a corporate realignment and the
replacement of several executives. At the time, retail analysts
described the changes as housekeeping matters and said Campeau
seemed to be coping with the debts accumulated over the past few
years.
   But, in an intensely competitive retail environment, Campeau's
stores apparently couldn't generate adequate amounts of cash to meet
their parent's debt-servicing requirements, analysts said.
   With Bloomingdale's now on the block, several long established
retail names are for sale. Earlier this summer, the U.S. division of
Australia's Hooker Corp. filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Code and put its B. Altman &amp;
Co. and Bonwit Teller department store chains up for sale.
   Bloomingdale's, founded in Manhattan in 1872, operates 17 stores
in New York, New Jersey, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Virginia,
Maryland, Pennsylvania, Florida, Illinois and Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
