</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. has disclosed it may sell its
Giorgio Beverly Hills and Parfums Stern fragrance businesses,
suppliers of some of the country's hottest selling scents.
   No final decision on whether to divest the subsidiaries has been
reached, said James E. Preston, the big cosmetic company's chairman
and chief executive officer. Avon has hired the investment banking
firm Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. to help it explore the possibility of a
sale and evaluate alternatives.
   Proceeds from a possible sale would go toward reducing Avon's
debt, which at mid-year totaled about $1 billion, Preston said in a
statement Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp., the debt-laden Canadian developer
and owner of numerous retail businesses, proposed a major financial
overhaul that includes the sale of Bloomingdale's, one of the best
known store chains.
   Bloomingdale's Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Marvin S.
Traub has indicated Friday he would like to participate in a
possible management buyout.
   Wall Street analysts said Campeau's willingness to part with
Bloomingdale's underscored the severity of the financial
difficulties facing the company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has cleared the way for
giant automaker Daimler-Benz to buy a major arms maker in what will
create one of Europe's largest companies, overriding an antitrust
panel veto of the merger that's been dubbed the ``elephants'
wedding.''
   Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann told a news conference Friday
he had agreed to endorse Daimler's $859 million bid to take over the
Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm aerospace and technology firm with
certain conditions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government quickly replaced the two top officials
of Italy's largest bank who resigned in a scandal involving at least
$1.7 billion in unauthorized export credits to Iraq by the bank's
branch in Atlanta.
   Treasury Minister Guido Carli on Friday appointed Giampiero
Cantoni as chairman of the state-owned Banca Nazionale del Lavoro
and Paolo Savona as director-general.
   Cantoni replaces Nerio Nesi and Savona succeeds Giacomo Pedde.
They stepped down late Thursday at an extraordinary meeting of the
bank's board.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More automated record-keeping is needed to keep
U.S. futures markets honest _ but not at the expense of the
traditional trading methods of shouts and hand signals, a government
watchdog agency said.
   At a Senate committee hearing, the General Accounting Office said
Friday the systems used for keeping track of trades on the nation's
commodities markets are ``fundamentally inadequate'' to detect and
deter wrongdoing.
   Last month, more than 40 traders and brokers on the two Chicago
futures exchanges were indicted on a variety of charges alleging
schemes to defraud customers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' pilots say they have chosen ``a
gladiator'' to lead them after ousting the union leader who a month
ago suggested they end their strike.
   Skip Copeland, an Eastern captain based in New York, was chosen
by acclamation Friday to take over the union leadership. On
Thursday, the pilots' executive council voted to recall Chairman
Jack Bavis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief regulator of national banks has
proposed a new capital rule that he says will discourage banks from
making risky investments. Comptroller of the Currency Robert L.
Clarke, whose agency regulates about 4,000 federally chartered
banks, on Friday proposed a 3 percent minimum capital standard, or
leverage ratio, as part of a larger risk-based capital rule that
takes effect at the end of 1990.
   But Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman L. William Seidman,
whose agency insures bank and S&amp;L deposits, is pushing for a 6
percent leverage ratio as a floor beneath the 8 percent risk-based
standard.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market managed a small advance Friday in the final
session of its first losing week since late June. The Dow Jones
industrials average rose 2.66 to 2,709.54, reducing its loss for the
week to 42.55 points.
   The dollar rose, approaching the peaks reached in its June rally.
   Bond prices were up slightly in thin trading.
   Soybean futures prices staged a strong rally; coffee and energy
futures rose; livestock, meat and precious metals retreated.
</TEXT>
